<SLUG> BC-BORDER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSION ON BORDER NOT LIKELY TO DIMINISH SOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY DANIEL GONZALEZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No matter who wins the July 2 Mexican election, volatility along
the Arizona-Mexico border isn't going away, analysts say. In fact,
there is a possibility that it could escalate.
</P>
<P>
   The two top candidates, Francisco Labastida of the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) and contender Vincente Fox
of the conservative National Action Party (PAN) have both pledged
to create stable, good-paying jobs that would help stem the tide of
Mexicans crossing the border looking for work in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say it would take years for either to raise
Mexico's economy to levels that would drastically eliminate the
poverty that encourages tens of thousands of Mexicans to cross the
border every year.
</P>
<P>
   They worry also that the potential for political and economic
instability following the election could trigger a new wave of
migration, adding to an already explosive situation along the
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is going to be at a very critical juncture, not only on
July 2, but on July 3 and in the weeks that follow,'' said
political scientist Armando Navarro of the University of California
at Riverside. ``Certain historical forces are at play that could
lead to increasing instability across the border.''
</P>
<P>
   Navarro recently returned from a two-day mission to Douglas to
assess the tensions that are straining relations between the United
States and Mexico. He has scheduled a July 29 summit in California
to develop solutions to the border crises.
</P>
<P>
   CANDIDATES TAKE NOTICE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, armed ranchers in Arizona and Texas have been
capturing Mexican migrants and turning them over to authorities,
sparking outrage and indignation in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Most polls put Labastida and Fox in a neck-and-neck race for the
Mexican presidency, and leading up to the election both candidates
have tried to gain votes by speaking out against the treatment of
Mexicans who cross the border.
</P>
<P>
   At a foreign policy forum in Mexico two weeks ago, Labastida
blasted the rounding up of illegal Mexican immigrants by U.S.
ranchers and pledged to ``use all the resources available to stop
the wrongs against our compatriots.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, meanwhile has raised eyebrows by proposing an open border
with the U.S., allowing the free movement of workers similar to
that of countries within the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also has proposed an aggressive economic growth plan that he
hopes will coax back Mexican workers living illegally in the United
States, along with the job skills they acquired here.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Fernando Martinez, a Mexican attorney at the National Law
Center for Inter-American Free Trade in Tucson, calls both
proposals pie in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Wide economic disparity
</P>
<P>
   An open border policy between the United States and Mexico is
``inconceivable'' because, unlike European countries, the disparity
between the Mexican and U.S. economies is too great, Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   And the higher standard of living even among poor people in the
United States will prevent most Mexicans working illegally in the
United States from returning to their own country, Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Ramirez, an undocumented Mexican immigrant who has lived
in Arizona for eight years, said he has no intention of returning
to Mexico, no matter how much the economy improves.
</P>
<P>
   Life here is ``one thousand times better,'' said Ramirez, 23,
who earns $8 an hour as a landscaper in northeast Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   About 3.3 million Mexicans are working in the United States
without documentation, and 150,000 Mexicans enter the United States
illegally every year, according to Immigration and Naturalization
Service estimates.
</P>
<P>
   After suffering two major crises in the past 20 years, Mexico's
economy has been steaming ahead, but 40 percent of the country's
100 million people still live below the poverty line and the
economy has failed to generate the approximately 1 million jobs
needed to keep up with the number of new workers entering the work
force each year.
</P>
<P>
   Many have crossed the border seeking jobs in the U.S. Over the
past 10 years, the movement has included a growing number of entire
families.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico ``is losing a lot of talented people,'' said Roderic
Camp, an expert on Mexico and professor of government at Claremont
McKenna College in Claremont, Calif. ``These are the people willing
to take a tremendous amount of risk to improve their standard of
living, and Mexico needs these kinds of people.''
</P>
<P>
   William Ackroyd, a political science professor at Arizona State
University West, is optimistic that Mexico's economy will continue
to improve, no matter which candidate wins the presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida represents the safer status quo and if he is elected
Ackroyd predicts, the crises along the border will improve
``incrementally,'' with a steady increase in real wages resulting
in fewer migrants crossing the border and a greater demand for U.S.
goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, on the other hand, represents momentous change that could
lead to rapid economic growth, perhaps followed by an economic
meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Two possible outcomes
</P>
<P>
   ``If Fox gets in, two things are possible,'' said Ackroyd. ``One
is, we could see a rapid and dramatic increase in real wages and
demand for U.S. products; (the second is) a rapid increase in wages
followed by inflation and a decrease in real wages that could lead
to devaluation and another economic crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Ackroyd warns the presidential elections could result in a
possible ``doomsday'' scenario if either candidate fails to win
convincingly and loses the ability to govern effectively,
triggering an economic crisis and possibly even civil unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it means is, you get a massive influx of Mexicans coming
across the border without documentation, an impoverished border
area and maybe even a spillover of violence,'' Ackroyd said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Daniel.Gonzalez)(at)ArizonaRepublic. &QL; com or
at (602) 444-8312. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
