<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE BONDS MAY BEND, WON'T BREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY HAL MATTERN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arizona businesses that thrive on exports to Mexico are casting
a wary eye south of the border as the Mexican presidential election
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in decades, Mexico's ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI) is facing a serious challenge.
</P>
<P>
   That has Arizona businesses, investors and trade experts
wondering what a victory by the National Action Party (PAN) on July
2 could mean for their fragile cross-border partnership with
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Some say it will be business as usual, no matter which party
wins. Others, however, predict at least a temporary period of
instability if the PAN unseats the PRI, which has held power in
Mexico since 1929.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who feels there is not going to be some interruption is
foolish,'' said Art Martori, a Phoenix businessman who is
developing a resort community near Mazatlan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If PAN wins, the dinosaurs are going to be out, and there is
going to be change from one end of the government to the other,''
Martori said. ``It's going to disrupt everything, but it will be
short-term, and in the long run it will be a breath of fresh air.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has been Arizona's No. 1 trading partner since the late
1980s, with exports approaching $4 billion annually, and most
experts expect that to continue no matter who is elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show PAN candidate Vicente Fox running
neck-and-neck with Francisco Labastida, the PRI nominee. Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas of the leftist Democratic Revolutionary Party (PRD) is
running a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the leading candidates have expressed their support for
free trade, although neither has provided details. Cardenas opposes
the North American Free Trade Agreement. &QL; 
PRO-BUSINESS POLICIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Labastida likely would continue the pro-trade policies of
current PRI President Ernesto Zedillo. Fox, a former Coca-Cola
executive, is expected to embrace similar policies, although he is
considered a little more pro-business and friendlier to foreign
trade and investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think either one would make a good president,'' said John
Kugler, operations manager for Concise Fabricators, a Tucson
company that does about 75 percent of its business in Mexico.
``Regardless of who makes it, Mexico will continue to grow, and
free trade is what is going to make it grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Most experts on trade with Mexico tend to agree, although they
don't rule out the possibility of some minor problems associated
with a change of ruling parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any striking differences between the candidates,''
said Patrick Cronin, an assistant professor of international
studies at the American Graduate School of International Management
in Glendale. ``Whatever way the election goes, I wouldn't look for
any change in trade policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Arizona businesses are understandably skittish about any
change of leadership in Mexico, which historically has been
followed by upheaval, even with the same party retaining power.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1994 elections, Mexico experienced a severe peso
devaluation that sent the country's economy into a tailspin.
Arizona exports to Mexico declined by nearly half a billion dollars
between 1994 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Although such a negative reaction is not expected after this
year's election, some trade experts still say a brief disruption is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every six years, after the elections, there has been either a
devaluation or a little instability,'' said Steve Sullivan, the
director of Arizona's trade office in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1994 it was a crisis, but this time we have been reassured
that there will be no collapse. If Fox wins, there might be a
little disruption, a little uncertainty . . . but the country is
going to recover.''
</P>
<P>
   MINOR CHANGES EXPECTED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Margie Emmermann, Gov. Jane Hull's policy advisor on Mexico,
said any changes would be minor because Mexico has such a large
contingent of multinational companies influencing trade policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Businesses have more say than they used to about trade
policy,'' Emmermann said. ``No president can change that.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, some concerns that a PAN president's
policies could conflict with those of the PRI governors of Mexico's
various states. If Fox were to win, he wouldn't have a political
infrastructure in place in those states.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a bit of gridlock,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican states of Sonora and Sinaloa, Arizona's two largest
Mexican trading partners, both have PRI governors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Fox wins, we're not sure what will happen in states with
PRI governors,'' said Gail Howard, director of economic development
at Arizona State University. ``It could be a whole new ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Emmermann doesn't see a problem, although she said having a
president with ties to states close to Arizona would be helpful.
Labastida is a former governor of Sinaloa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't endorse one or the other,'' Emmermann said. ``We
would continue to pursue a good relationship with the Fox
administration. It just might take longer to get to know the
players.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Hal.Mattern(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or at
(602) 444-8652. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
