<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MORE BLAST FROM THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - Fourteen years ago this month, I spoke for the first
time to a grieving mother named Dolores Heil.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was about a week after Heil's daughter, Susan Dina, had been
killed by a stray bullet while sunning near the pool of a Mesa
motel.
</P>
<P>
   Susan and her husband were in town from Philadel phia for a
friend's wedding. Across the street, two men were busting up a bar.
As they did, a patron named Martin Olsen went outside to get a
handgun he kept in his car. Before he got back, the men left and
were driving away in a truck. Olsen tried to shoot out the
vehicle's tires. He missed. One of the bullets hit Susan Dina in
the face, killing her.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of a ``Wild West'' place is Arizona, Susan's mother
asked me at the time. Adding, ``I hope that people out there will
learn a lesson from this.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course they will, I told her. The story of Susan Dina's
tragic death was in all the papers and on TV. People would see the
danger of fire arms, even in the hands of those foolish enough to
be lieve they're doing ``good.''
</P>
<P>
   But time passed and bodies continued to pile up. I'd check in
with Dolores Heil every year or so, sometimes writing about her.
She told me how Susan's husband had suffered a mental breakdown.
She described the pain of watching Phoenix residents show more
sympathy for her daughter's killer, Martin Ol sen, than they did
for Susan. Mostly because Olsen was older and sickly. She spoke of
how Olsen spent a couple of years in prison while Susan's family
got life.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, I spoke to Dolores Heil about another senseless
shooting death in Phoenix, one that reminded me of her daughter's
killing. I told her if people heard from her _ again _ it might
teach the lesson she'd talked about years before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's this deep pain way inside you that you can't get at,''
she said at the time, ``and it just keeps throbbing and
throbbing.''
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, I called Dolores Heil one more time. It was
after another family lost a girl to a senseless shooting. There
were still les sons to be learned, I said.
</P>
<P>
   The pain in Heil's voice hadn't diminished in 13 years. She told
me, ``When people are reckless with guns, it echoes forever.''
</P>
<P>
   It does, I'm sure of it, but only to a victim's family.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago, a man and woman approached 18-year-old Danny
Marquez at a local Circle K. They pulled a gun and carjacked
Marquez's 1984 Oldsmobile.
</P>
<P>
   As the suspects drove away, Marquez took out a 9mm pistol and
fired about 10 shots. One of the bullets hit 23-year-old Jonathan
Ward in the head, killing him. He was an innocent bystander, like
Susan Dina.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors haven't charged Marquez yet, but a spokesman for the
Maricopa County Attorney's Office says they probably will soon.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, there will be talk of the danger of firearms and of
the cowboy mentality. And people will come for ward to say that
Marquez is basically a ``good'' guy who didn't mean to hurt anyone.
Then, as time passes and legal proceedings drag on, Jonathan Ward
slowly will be forgotten. And I'll drift back 14 years, brooding
over les sons we still haven't learned.
</P>
<P>
   Except for one.
</P>
<P>
   I've learned not to call Dolores Heil. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Montini at Ed.Montini &LR; ArizonaRepublic.com or (602) 444-8978. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
