A0716 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-     06-11 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO DO WITH WHITE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dodgers officials are hopeful Devon White can
return to the lineup from his partially torn left rotator cuff by
July 1, but the injured center fielder continues to resist putting
a date on a possible return.
</P>
<P>
   However, determining what will happen with White, who is also
the leadoff hitter, is crucial for the Dodgers in attacking the
rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers want White back because they quietly believe he is
the best center fielder on the roster, and his presence at the top
of the lineup is needed to be a championship club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten stronger,'' White said of the shoulder before
Saturday's game against Oakland at Dodger Stadium. ``It's
progressing, but I don't really know. There's good days and bad
days. I can't really put a timetable on it because what if I don't
meet it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say I'll be ready by early July and then not
be ready. I might wake up one day and feel great and be able to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, the miracle cure hasn't happened. But neither
has the decision to end White's season with surgery, so the Dodgers
are left in a bind.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers don't want to make a trade if White could be ready
to play in three weeks. But if they wait and surgery is needed, the
price for acquiring a starting center fielder goes up.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers talked with speedy outfielder Jacob Brumfield about
signing a minor-league deal that could have eventually led to a
shot with the Dodgers, but that's on hold because there's no room
in the organization for him.
</P>
<P>
   There's also interest in Kansas City outfielder Johnny Damon,
two sources said, though everyone in the organization isn't sold on
him. Damon is playing left field for the Royals, but spent most of
his career playing center field.
</P>
<P>
   He's hitting .268 with five homers and 25 RBI from the leadoff
spot for the Royals, has 17 stolen bases in 20 attempts and a .336
on-base percentage. In his career, Damon has a .342 on-base
percentage.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' lineup is powerful, potent and fixed, except for
the leadoff spot. It's been an area manager Davey Johnson worried
about, but decided to plug it with White, who won championships
with Toronto batting leadoff.
</P>
<P>
   White was hitting .289 with three homers, nine RBI and a .326
on-base percentage. Todd Hollandsworth, currently nursing a sore
right hamstring, F.P. Santangelo and Shawn Gilbert, who led off one
game, are hitting a combined .239 with five homers, 15 RBI and a
.324 on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Dodgers' leadoff spot is hitting .256 with 43 runs
scored and has an on-base percentage of .325.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLANDSWORTH'S HEALTH: Hollandsworth, platooning in center
field with Santangelo since White's injury, isn't improving at the
pace the Dodgers wanted. One way to temporarily stem the numbers
crunch on the roster is putting him on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   With Adrian Beltre and Orel Hershiser due back at some point
next week, Hollandsworth's right hamstring could buy the Dodgers
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely behind Beltre (in recovering),'' Johnson said.
``If it looks like it's going to be another four or five days
before he's 80 percent, it's possible we'll retroactive him (to
last Sunday) to the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely a pull and not a spasm or something. It's
definitely more serious. He's not that close.''
</P>
<P>
   HERSHISER'S RETURN: Hershiser is expected to be recalled from
Single-A San Bernardino during the upcoming four-game series
against Arizona, but for the time being it would be as a reliever.
For now, at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our starters are doing fine,'' Hershiser said. ``I
don't think it's fair for our starters to think they're on a short
leash because I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser is scheduled to throw a bullpen today, then talk to
Johnson. Dodgers managing general partner and CEO Bob Daly and
Hershisher are expected to converse Monday about the matter. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
