<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-NYT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIM, HERO? MYS TERY IN AJ KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY PETER ORTIZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Within a 72-hour period last February, Bricie Tribble
went from a puzzling victim to hero to suspect in a murder
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Four months later, Apache Junction police are still unraveling a
case that includes a killing that may or may not have been
self-defense, a dead man with no traceable past, a mysterious
package filled with potentially incriminating evidence, and notes
on a corpse that ended Tribble's brief status as a National Rifle
Association poster child.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, police disclosed their investigation in hopes of
finding people who knew the man Tribble shot in her kitchen and
locating the unknown person who sent the package.
</P>
<P>
   Their objective: pull together the final parts of a case against
Tribble, 28, for conspiring to kill her husband, Jeffrey.
</P>
<P>
   No charges have been filed so far. Tribble could not be located
for comment, although police say they know where they can find her.
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre case began shortly after midnight Feb. 1 when Sgt.
Ron Martin and other police responded to a call at Tribble's home.
On the kitchen floor, they found the body of Erick Fuentes Ramirez,
25, with bullet wounds in the neck, back and side.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tribble said she shot Fuentes Ramirez because he had
broken into her home and threatened to kill her family, police were
suspicious: There was no sign of forced entry or struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody had the same question: `Why this house? Why did he
pick this house to enter the back door?' '' Cmdr. Brian Duncan
said. ``I mean this house sits out in the middle of nowhere. Was it
as random as Bricie would like us to believe it was?''
</P>
<P>
   But their suspicions quickly evaporated when Tribble identified
the victim as a former employee of her husband's excavating
business.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, Tribble became somewhat of a hero when police
learned that just hours before he was slain, Fuentes Ramirez had
kidnapped, raped and shot a 33-year-old woman from a Wal-Mart in
Chandler, leaving her for dead in a Mesa desert.
</P>
<P>
   Fuentes Ramirez was wearing that victim's wedding ring on his
left pinkie finger when he was shot.
</P>
<P>
   Tribble quickly drew nationwide attention from pro-gun
advocates, who said her case showed the value of keeping firearms.
Police believe that the NRA hired a Phoenix lawyer to represent
her. &QL; 
THE 1ST CLUE &QL; 
But on Feb. 3, Martin and an identification technician, Karen
Gwaltney, discovered the first clues that ended Tribble's brief
ride as a hero.
</P>
<P>
   In Fuentes Ramirez's wallet, they found a note in which Tribble
had told the man she killed, ``You know how I love you.'' They
found a second note that read, ``If Jeffrey dies from overdose of
drugs, Bricie is { responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Tribble not only signed the note, but stamped her fingerprint
next to her signature, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were both startled,'' Martin said. ``We weren't expecting
to find something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan said Fuentes Ramirez kept the note in his wallet as an
insurance policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to us that Erick wanted some assurance from her
that he wasn't going to be left holding the bag,'' Duncan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand this is a correspondence signed by
Bricie to Erick, and we are looking at this note that says,
`Jeffrey dies,' '' he added. ``Automatically, the antennas are
going to go up and say something is wrong here.'' &QL; 
MORE EVIDENCE &QL; 
Police found more evidence that Tribble and Fuentes Ramirez were
having an affair. Her co-workers at the Mesa Christian Center said
she and Fuentes Ramirez had been seeing each other since October
and had been together the day before the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after the killing, an unaddressed package sent from
a Phoenix post office arrived at the Apache Junction police
station.
</P>
<P>
   It contained photos of Tribble standing next to Fuentes
Ramirez's car and exposing her bra and panties, Tribble's wedding
photo, an eight-page letter and other love notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not confused about what I want or who I want to be with. I
love you and I want you in my life,'' the letter read.
</P>
<P>
   Police also learned that Fuentes Ramirez had used Tribble's gun
to shoot the woman he had kidnapped and raped.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer had advised Tribble not to talk to investigators,
Martin said. After Martin notified him that there were criminal
charges pending against his client, the lawyer referred her to the
Public Defenders Office. The office has declined to represent
Tribble until charges are filed, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Police don't know why Fuentes Ramirez kidnapped the woman before
driving off in her sport-utility vehicle to Tribble's home. And
they don't know why Tribble shot Fuentes Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   Tribble, who gave a statement to police on the day of the
shooting, moved out of her Apache Junction home in March. She
submitted handwriting samples and fingerprints under court order,
but refused to speak any more with police.
</P>
<P>
   The samples showed she wrote the notes to Fuentes Ramirez,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police plan to eventually turn the case over to the Pinal County
Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Tribble learned of his wife's affair from police after
she moved out of their home. He has since cooperated with
investigators but declined to comment. &QL; 
SEEKING INFORMATION &QL; 
All police know about Fuentes Ramirez is that he is an undocumented
citizen who may have lived in Chandler. Other than a citation for
an expired motor vehicle registration, he does not appear to have a
criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   Police say they fear friends of Fuentes Ramirez who may be
undocumented may be avoiding police and emphasize they are
interested only in information about the victim and not the legal
status of the people who may provide information.
</P>
<P>
   To contact Apache Junction police, call (480) 982-8260.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not looking that she shot and killed Erick,'' Duncan
said. ``We have no evidence to show she did not do it in
self-defense. We are focusing on these letters and conspiracy to
kill Jeffrey.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Peter.Ortiz(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-7726. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
