<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN CAL HANDS FLORIDA STATE ANOTHER CWS SETBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ At the end of a long afternoon presented in
scorching detail to a national viewing audience, the Southern
California Trojans had 16 hits and a small problem Saturday in the
College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Their continuous barrage had produced a mere two-run lead, and
in the bottom of the ninth, Florida State had two runners on base
with one out. Mindful of the opportunity for a dramatic finish,
Seminoles catcher Blair McCaleb smashed a rocket toward the gap.
</P>
<P>
   At which point, the most useful weapon in the USC arsenal became
the glove of shortstop Seth Davidson, who leaped into the air,
speared McCaleb's drive, and tossed to second baseman Anthony
Lunetta to double up an FSU runner and seal a 6-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 16th consecutive victory for the Trojans (44-18), who
are scheduled to face Louisiana State on Monday in the second
round. For Florida State (51-18), which has never won a national
title in 17 previous trips to the CWS, it was another unhappy
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess saying I had a good day is one way of looking at it,''
said FSU first baseman Ryan Barthelemy, who was 4-for-4 with two
home runs and three runs batted in. ``But I'd give all four of
those hits for a win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans matched Barthelemy's homers with clouts from Beau
Craig and Lunetta, and scored three runs in the fourth and two in
the fifth to take the lead and chase FSU starter Blair Varnes
(11-3) from the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Cal coach Mike Gillespie praised the performance of
starter Rik Currier (15-3) and the overall play of his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``As usual, Rik gave us a real good, competitive performance,''
Gillespie said. ``He didn't get rattled when they had an early
lead. ... he's a very poised pitcher and perfect for a game like
this. It was frustrating to score so few runs on so many hits, but
we had good execution, a little luck and a big play to end the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Currier pitched strongly before being relieved with two out in
the eighth by Ronald Flores, who gave up back-to-back singles with
one out in the ninth before being rescued by Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy really scorched it,'' Davidson said, ``It wasn't
exactly a sno-cone, but it almost put a hole in my glove.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a big day for Lunetta, who was diagnosed with strep
throat when he arrived and had a temperature of 101 on Friday, but
awoke Saturday ``feeling great.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the home run, he launched a crowd-pleasing
defensive play by going to his right for a ground ball and flipping
it to Davidson, who made the throw to first for the out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We practice that, and I know Coach likes to see it,'' he said,
``and when I heard Seth yelling, `flip, flip, flip,' I did it. I
guess it's a good thing it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   For Varnes, who lost the CWS final to Miami last year while
gamely pitching with a knee injury, it was another disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not very happy right now,'' he said. ``It wasn't a
good day.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
