<SLUG> BC-CAR-CHEEVER-IROC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAVE IT TO CHEEVER: IRL DRIVER WINS IROC EVENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Eddie Cheever looked worn out after hopping
a plane from Michigan Speedway to the Texas Motor Speedway on
Saturday afternoon. But the smile on that worn-out face said it
all.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday morning, Cheever took advantage of his front row
starting position in the 50-lap International Race of Champions
event in Brooklyn, Mich., to win his first event in the all-star
series and the first for an active driver in the Indy Racing
Northern Light Series.
</P>
<P>
   The four-race series concludes during the Brickyard 400 weekend
at Indianapolis Motor Speedway in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I beat (Dale) Earnhardt today. I beat (Mark) Martin,'' Cheever
said with a grin during a news conference at the infield media
center at TMS. ``For me to go down there and do well, that says a
lot for our racing series. I'm sure the `Good Ol' Boys' thought I
was crazy. I was as crazy as a fox, and it was the right way to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheever admits his previous performances in the invitation-only
series, which features drivers from various forms of motorsports in
identically prepared Pontiac Firebird Trans-Ams, have not been
good, and he was tired of getting beat.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning he proved that he can mix it up with the boys
from NASCAR's Winston Cup Series on their turf by using a different
line than several of the drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Cheever stayed low on the track, while others ran higher in the
groove. Cheever rolled to the first victory by a non-Winston Cup
driver since Al Unser Jr. in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``He roughed me up a little coming off (Turn) 4 one time, but I
got over it in a lap or so,'' Earnhardt said. Cheever has ``raced;
he's paid his dues. I think Eddie could run in NASCAR with the
right equipment. It's fitting he won. It wasn't given to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheever fell back no farther than fourth in the 50-lap event and
took the lead for good on Lap 33.
</P>
<P>
   He beat former IRL champion and current Winston Cup star Tony
Stewart by 0.711 seconds on the two-mile banked trioval, with
Earnhardt finishing third and Martin fourth.
</P>
<P>
   IRL regulars Greg Ray and Mark Dismore, who also flew to and
from Michigan with Cheever, competed in the event. Dismore finished
10th and Ray 11th in the 12-car field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty laps in (IROC) is a lot more nerve-wracking than 200
laps out here,'' said Cheever, whose previous best IROC finish was
a third at IMS last year. ``I am not relaxed in the car because it
is closed in and there is a lot of dust in the car. And you have
(11) maniacs behind me trying to get even with me. My car was
working, and I was lucky that Earnhardt and Martin were fighting
because I would lose 10 yards and gain 10 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheever, driver of the No. 51 Excite &LR; Home Dallara/Infiniti on
the IRL circuit, said he is slowly learning the subtle nuances of
driving in the series by racing with NASCAR's top stars on tracks
that NASCAR drivers sometimes visit twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   Like learning that when the cars touch it's all right, or what
certain hand singles mean, especially from people such as Earnhardt
and Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only mistake I made that I really regret is coming out of
Turn 2, I got a little close to Dale Earnhardt,'' Cheever said. ``I
just rubbed up a little, what they call `rubbin'. ' I think I
knocked the (heck) out of it, but they call it rubbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I went by I looked at him in a very differential way. I had
a full facemask on. He didn't.'' Cheever continued. ``You could see
his expressions. I was like, `I am really sorry.' He just gave me
the thumbs-up, and I guess there is no death warrant on me, so I
just continued on.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Cheever it was further proof that the Indy Racing
Northern Light series has drivers who can compete in any series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last five years, Indy Racing drivers _ thanks to
CART's excellent PR work _ are (perceived) at a level that
everybody is incompetent who drives in the Indy Racing Northern
Light Series,'' he said. ``I don't believe that. I'm very proud of
the fact that we have such good races.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
