r a BC-INCOMETAX-AZR &LR;      06-11 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INCOMETAX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCOME TAX BAN SCARES OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY CHRIS MOESER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) 
Even as lawmakers contemplate a sales tax hike to raise $450
million a year for education, Arizona faces the possibility of
losing annual revenues five times that amount.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A citizens group has been amassing signatures to place on the
November ballot a proposal to abolish the state income tax.
</P>
<P>
   The movement has Arizona leaders so alarmed that they have
launched an all-out, largely behind-the-scenes assault on the
supporters behind the plan, hop ing to hobble the measure from
making it on the Nov. 7 ballot, or to defeat it at the ballot box
should it survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to open the prisons and close the schools, this is
the initiative for you,'' said Gov. Jane Hull, who predicts massive
budget cuts and huge increases in sales and property taxes to make
up the lost money.
</P>
<P>
   Hull and other state leaders fret that voters might approve her
proposed state sales tax in crease in November and, at the same,
give themselves a break on income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the income tax initiative say that it is an idea
whose time has come. They say it would also force legislators to
cut the fat from the budget, among them tax exemptions that benefit
special groups to the tune of billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, which would eliminate individual and corpo rate
income taxes over four years, is the most comprehensive reform
package ever to go before voters, the backers say.
</P>
<P>
   Besides eliminating $2.6 billion in revenue - it makes up nearly
half of the state's budget - the initiative requires a two-thirds
vote of the Legislature and a public vote to replace any of the
money. It also would identify candidates on the ballot who favored
eliminating the federal income tax. &QL; 
LONG ROAD AHEAD &QL; 
It faces a long road. The group behind the initiative, Taxpayer
Protection Alliance, is still short of the 152,643 signatures
needed for the issue to qualify as a ballot measure. And then
there's the political heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will absolutely be out cam paigning,'' Hull said. ``That
one, Growing Smarter and the educa tion proposal will be the three
main initiatives I'll be involved in.''
</P>
<P>
   Two high-profile politicians who had signed onto the ini
tiative, former Attorney General Grant Woods and U.S. Rep. Matt
Salmon, have withdrawn their support. And a powerful devel oper,
Suncor, withdrew a $10,000 donation to the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Mahoney, a former secretary of state who endorses the
plan to scrap the income tax, accuses Hull of being the puppet
master behind the moves.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has mobilized a powerful opposition group, in
cluding the Arizona Chamber of Commerce, police and firefight ers
groups, unions, and cities and lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney said Hull and other opponents are playing a game of
Chicken Little.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think those people have a piece of the pie,'' Mahoney said.
``They have a vested interest on the inside in that money and they
don't want to let go.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughly half of the state's $6 billion budget comes from in come
taxes: 40 percent from indi viduals and 9 percent from
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the rest of the money comes from sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Hull and other critics say it would be virtually impossible to
make up that revenue with other taxes, particularly with the re
strictions the income tax initia tive proposes on tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about elim inating half of the money in the
general fund, I don't think there's ever been a proposal before vot
ers that's been more dangerous,'' said Kevin McCarthy of the Ari
zona Tax Research Association. ``The reason they don't include
replacement revenues is they don't want that in the debate. It's a
sham.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy points out that law makers have already cut the state
income tax by 30 percent in recent years. Arizona has the fourth
lowest income tax burden of states that have the tax.
</P>
<P>
   City officials, which depend on the tax for a portion of their
revenues, warn that city services would be dramatically curtailed.
Phoenix Councilman Phil Gordon predicts cuts in fire and police, as
well as social services.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't anything in this community that has been more
devastating than if this passes,'' Gordon said. &QL; 
SCARE TACTICS &QL; 
But Lori Klein, executive direc tor of the Taxpayer Protection
Alliance, says those predictions are nothing more than scare
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   She said eliminating the in come tax would make the state more
attractive to corporations, which would dramatically expand the
economy. And it would make government more accountable to voters,
who would have more control over spending and taxa tion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most taxpayers on the street would rather pay a penny on the
dollar for police and fire than pay an income tax,'' Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney adds that lawmakers would have four years to cut the fat
in state government. Cutting the income tax would force politi
cians to make tough choices, something supporters say is long
overdue. He, for one, suggests a 10 percent budget cut.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney also points to 600 exemptions in the sales tax code that
total about $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these are handouts to people who have their own lobby
ists down at the Capitol,'' he said. ``The people who are paying
taxes are the working poor. The people who don't pay are the guys
with accountants who can find the loopholes.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Chris.Moe ser &LR; Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or at (602) 444-8069. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
