r s BC-BBO-DODGERS-ATHLETICS     06-11 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-ATHLETICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARROS TIES HOMER MARK IN DODGERS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Right-hander Kevin Brown did his typical gig. He
baffled Oakland hitters with an array of pitches from a bunch of
arm angles in a complete-game 7-2 Dodgers victory Saturday at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was Eric Karros who became the center of attention with
one historic swing. The first baseman, a symbol of the Dodgers, not
to mention a link to the O'Malley days of a family-run business,
stepped to the edge of Los Angeles Dodgers lore with a sixth-inning
homer.
</P>
<P>
   It gave the Dodgers a 7-1 lead, but the meaning was far deeper.
With it, Karros tied Ron Cey for the L.A. franchise record for
career homers with 228. With his next homer also comes the
distinction of being the most prolific home-run hitter since the
franchise moved from Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice, but when I hit the one that breaks it, it'll
probably have a little more meaning,'' Karros said. ``It's nice to
be mentioned in the same breath as Ron Cey and Steve Garvey, but I
want to mentioned in the same breath as them when you're talking
about the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Karros' 17th homer of the season came off Oakland reliever Scott
Service, carrying just beyond the thigh-high wall in left field.
Dodgers reliever Mike Fetters then got the ball from the fan and
gave it to Karros.
</P>
<P>
   The home run also ended Karros' second-longest homerless streak
of the season at 24 at-bats. His 227th career homer came last
Saturday at Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a slider,'' Karros said. ``I haven't been swinging
the bat well the last few days. It was more luck than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Karros is tied with Gary Sheffield for the team lead in homers,
and leads the Dodgers with 55 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Even Karros, a Dodger throughout his nine-year career, admitted
passing Cey was as much as a given could be this side of death and
taxes, especially since he signed a three-year contract extension
in February.
</P>
<P>
   But becoming the Dodgers' all-time home run leader is more of a
long shot. That distinction belongs to Duke Snider, who hit 389.
He's followed by Gil Hodges at 361 and Roy Campanella at 242.
Karros is 10th on the franchise RBI list with 789, which is fourth
all-time in Los Angeles history.
</P>
<P>
   Karros hit at least 30 homers in four of the last five seasons,
including matching a career-high in 1999. He's homered once every
21.1 at-bats in his career and once every 12.5 at-bats this season.
Karros is on pace to hit 47 homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a clutch guy, he's a special hitter,'' Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said. ``He grinds it out. The more I see him the more
I appreciate him. He may start slow, but he's a special player.
He's giving it everything he has every time up there. Before I came
here, nobody had to tell me he was the one who got the clutch hits,
and it didn't have to be a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   The drama wasn't as grand for Karros' record-tying homer because
the rest of the Dodgers' power hitters gave Brown an early lead.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield gave Brown a rare early cushion with a two-run
double, and Shawn Green followed with a run-scoring single to give
the Dodgers a 3-0 lead in the bottom of the first off former Angels
hurler Omar Olivares.
</P>
<P>
   Brown added an RBI single in the third and Green hit his 11th
homer, a two-run shot in the fourth, as the Dodgers built a 6-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still have to pitch (even with an early lead),'' Brown
said. ``Early in the game, you can't go out and say, `OK, I'll
throw it over the plate.' Not with every guy from first to ninth in
the order hitting homers.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown allowed seven hits, walked one and struck out four in his
second straight complete game, his third of the season. By
comparison, Olivares (3-8) allowed six runs on nine hits in four
innings. He's lost his last five starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what's going on, (but) I'm not able to physically
(change) it,'' Olivares said. ``I'm not throwing the low strikes. I
haven't been able to hit my spots.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
