<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0777 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0612-COX     06-11 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0612-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When it comes to sex, power struggles can be deadly
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dr. Robert Hatcher is recognized worldwide as an
expert in family planning and population control, but at Emory
University in Atlanta his medical students just call him Captain
Condom.
</P>
<P>
   In a week when the Vatican and Muslim nations tried mightily at
the U.N. meeting in New York to weaken the reproductive rights goal
of the 1995 Beijing conference on women, Hatcher, a professor of
obstetrics and gynecology, offered insights on the volatile issue.
They are based on a lifetime of research and experience with
real-life situations around the world. One of his books, ``The
Essentials of Contraceptive Technology,'' published by Johns
Hopkins University Press and translated in many languages, is
distributed by the United Nations to health care professionals
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Modern medical technology and the availability of
contraceptives, even in developing nations, should make unwanted
pregnancies and abortions rare, Hatcher says. But male attitudes,
cultural mores and religious views still are obstacles. The
solution hinges on improving the status of women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' he says, ``men don't want to relinquish this
important (sexual) power over women.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher tells two stories to illustrate his point:
</P>
<P>
   In the Congolese capital of Kinshasa, Dr. Manzila Tarande, a
gynecologist with the Centers for Disease Control in Africa,
counseled a man who was HIV-positive and his spouse who was not. He
advised the couple of the risk to the woman and instructed them on
how to use condoms. Two weeks later, the woman returned with an eye
swollen, her body bruised and cut. ``See what your condom advice
got me,'' she said. She later died of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``This woman didn't die because of a lack of access to
contraceptives or of a lack of understanding about how to use
them,'' Hatcher says. ``She died because of the status of women.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in America, where women have led the way in improving their
status and choices, there are underlying problems of power and
control in relationships. For example, a woman who worked in the
OB-GYN department at Atlanta's Grady Hospital decided after her
fifth child she wanted to be sterilized, but her husband objected.
And for religious reasons, he also rejected contraceptive use. Soon
after the woman became pregnant with her sixth child, she died of a
self-induced abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't die because she had no access to contraceptives or
legal abortion,'' Hatcher says. ``She died because of her lack of
power. She died because of the status of women.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hatcher is encouraged that the education of women and the
availability of contraceptives through the U.N. and other world
health organizations has helped decrease the average family size in
many nations. In Kenya, for example, the birth rate between 1976
and 1999 dropped from 8.4 children per family to 5.4. In Peru, from
6.7 to 3.5.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, teenage pregnancy is down, but not by
enough. Studies show 93 percent of young people engage in
premarital sex, most while still in high school, Hatcher says.
Although he preaches abstinence to teens and believes strongly sex
education should be taught in a framework of moral values, he also
believes in offering the safety net of education about
contraception. But much of American society is not ready for that,
he says. ``If I suggested such to some (parent) groups I speak
to,'' he says, ``I wouldn't be asked back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beijing goal of reproductive rights for women and sex
education for girls must be more than just a women's effort.
Hatcher says: ``Improving the status of women has to include men _
husbands, boyfriends, physicians and political leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
