<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-LAWRENCE0612-COX     06-11 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWRENCE0612-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawrence pinned life to the canvas perfectly
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was in a New York gallery that I met Jacob
Lawrence, five years ago, just before his powerful Migration Series
opened at the High Museum in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   He had traveled by plane from Seattle, as I had from Atlanta. As
we sat chatting about his work, neither of us said anything about
the underlying significance of a couple of plane trips. But, as we
talked, two gray-haired men, I couldn't help thinking of the irony
of how our ordinary travels had become a stark counterpoint to
Lawrence's series, his best-known work and the definitive artistic
statement about the pain and the promise surrounding black people
as they left the Deep South for the industrial North in the 1920s
and '30s.
</P>
<P>
   While our flights were without disrespect, the travelers in the
black exodus Lawrence depicted in his 60 paintings suffered and
endured Jim Crow's worst, in a world already afflicted with
lynchings, race riots and denied opportunities throughout society.
</P>
<P>
   I knew these paintings, I knew these travelers and I knew these
stories. Many of my relatives and family friends had migrated from
rural Alabama, north to the rubber factories in Akron, Ohio, to the
railroad yards in Cleveland. The packing houses in Chicago and
steel mills of Pittsburgh. And, in a continuing version of the
migration from Down Home to Up South (the North often treated black
people as badly as the South) my own parents left Meridian, Miss.,
in the 1950s for East St. Louis, Ill., site of a 1917 race riot
ignited by tension over the hiring of black factory workers. That
riot, in which at least 48 people died _ 40 black, eight white _
was depicted as No. 52 in Lawrence's series.
</P>
<P>
   Another painting, No. 15, showed one reason my parents and I had
left Meridian. It was a stark scene of a figure in red, bent in
grief after a lynching (no body shown). Like many other black
Southerners, we left after hearing about the lynching of Emmett
Till, who in 1955 at the same age as I _ 14 _ was murdered near
Money, Miss., after allegedly flirting with a white woman.
</P>
<P>
   Moved by my familiarity with the lives and times that inspired
these paintings, I exclaimed, ``You painted my story.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence replied, gently: ``It's our story. One of the
greatmovements through United States history. People are always on
the move, trying to better themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   He understood that hope for a better life has put countless
other groups in motion, too, including white Southerners, Irish
immigrants, Salvadorans, Mexicans, Laotians, Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing to tell the American story through the
black-American migration, Lawrence made it universal. Meeting him
made it clear that he was a universal man.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he painted the story that so many black people had
lived, Lawrence did it with such elegance and force of talent that
he rose above the injustices he illuminated. That quickly became
apparent when he walked into the room at the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing taupe trousers, brown-patterned jacket, blue sweater and
a friendly smile, he exuded both confidence and accessibility. As
important was what he did not show. There was no weariness, that
sense of being beaten down by injustice. He showed no rage, but
rather a clear sense of purpose. And a recognition that change is
to be embraced.
</P>
<P>
   His work, of course, has always shown purpose, telling stories
and history in bold, primary colors and with a fine sense of
economy _ an almost abstractness all the more powerful for its
absence of sentimentality and preachiness. In some ways, Lawrence
was a vessel through which stories with lives of their own flowed.
</P>
<P>
   During our 1995 conversation, he talked about a project he had
been working on, ``a builder's theme,'' drawing on his own love for
tools; he had collected saws, planes, hammers, chisels. ``I
consider tools a metaphor for uplift,'' he said, adding that tools
in Renaissance paintings still look perfectly beautiful: ``I use
them the way some painters use fruits in still life.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest fruit borne from the works of Jacob Lawrence may be
his essential Americanness. Like any true artist, he painted truths
about the place he knew, caring enough about it to tell its story
and try to make it better. That's what Norman Rockwell did. What
Carl Sandburg did with poetry. What Bob Dylan and Billie Holiday
sang about .
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great country,'' Lawrence said at one point during
our conversation. His work helped make it that way. By telling the
truths he told, he helped Americans understand where our country
had been and where it might go if it could acknowledge its past: He
painted people who worked hard in desperately trying times to get
the good from society, including abolitionists Frederick Douglass
and Harriet Tubman. And, when you looked at the people in his
migration series, you always wanted them to go north and do well,
even though you knew that wouldn't always happen. What you did know
was that they had to go, and the country had to aspire to making
change for good.
</P>
<P>
   His portrayals of these migrants demonstrated the power of
positive self-perception. Though born in Atlantic City, N.J., he
embraced Southern culture, learning about it from his childhood
peers and from his mother, who was born in Fredericksburg, Va.
Thus, his paintings carry the weight of cultural intimacy that you
can't make up.
</P>
<P>
   And, because all of us, in some way, have lived his story, we
look for ourselves in his work and his life.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence and his wife Gwen (also an artist) were married in
1941, the year I was born. When, as newlyweds, they visited New
Orleans, they found, not unexpectedly, wide and deep segregation.
Returning years later, he found changes that were equally profound:
``There was a mix of the races, going to bars and things like that.
It looked as if whites welcomed this change. This was true
throughout the country. They seemed freer.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the same feeling I had when returning to live in the
South in the 1970s, after living in the North for almost 20 years.
Freedom seemed at hand. Possibility, at last, certainly was.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Lawrence's paintings of train travelers never
fail to recall my own trips in segregated cars, where black people
ate home-prepared sandwiches wrapped in greasy paper and stored in
shoeboxes. Those paintings, too, always remind me of treks by car
when none of the restaurants would serve us, so those sandwiches
served again.
</P>
<P>
   We talked about those times, and those reminders, but we agreed
that we were fortunate to have moved past the pain, just as America
moved past the behavior that brought the hurt. And, that is why we
didn't have to talk about the plane ride anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to learn, teach and move on is what I'll always
remember about Jacob Lawrence, artist. American artist.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 1425EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0791 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0612-COX     06-11 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0612-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get a whiff of this city
 &HT;    by John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ This city smells terrific.
</P>
<P>
   I find this realization startling. Cities commonly stink, and
this city has its smelly moments.
</P>
<P>
   Yet more than one moment recently caused me to stop and cock my
head toward something _ something pulling me to pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   I deduced shortly that at least part of what I was smelling was
new landscaping on the exterior of this newspaper's grounds.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know an Indian hawthorn from a Mexican marigold.
Couldn't tell you if a red sage had me at gunpoint. But all of
those are in the ground on these grounds, and every day they take
stink away. Or they distract us from it.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the multi-dimensioned distraction of the crape myrtle.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago the persuasive activists of Keep Waco
Beautiful convinced the city council to pronounce it Waco's town
tree. The organization backed its promotion with a donation of 150
of them.
</P>
<P>
   COLOR _ AND AROMA
</P>
<P>
   With blossoms varying from white to purple to melon and more,
the crape myrtle stays blooming for months. And, said local
beautification stalwart Frances Sturgis, ``even when it's bare its
limbs are pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Keep Waco Beautiful considered the blossoms' scent when
making its pitch?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Sturgis said. ``We considered the beauty.'' She then
granted that the group had missed a lick. Scent would have sealed
any deal.
</P>
<P>
   Now the crape myrtle is all over. While its scent varies in
intensity _ boosted by a generous rain, for instance _ there's no
question that fragrance comes with the package.
</P>
<P>
   A landscaper has a lot in his bag of tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the butterfly bush, genus buddleia davidii, a floral
hedge that gives off a scent that drives butterflies wild.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are non-blooming aromatic plants like rosemary, mint
or sage.
</P>
<P>
   I looked on the Internet for a term for this scent science _
this side benefit of urban forestation. We have experts devising
strategies for shade, promoting energy savings from green (turf
around a building lowers ambient temperation by 15 degrees, you
should know.)
</P>
<P>
   We know green gives off oxygen and consumes carbon dioxide. But
clearly one of the most compelling reasons for greening a city is
rarely discussed, this smell thing.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Waco Inc. Executive Director Margaret Mills, Waco's
chief urban revivalist, ought to have a name for this science, but
all she can do is fall back on the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It provides a serenity and peacefulness to what can be a loud
and cumbersome sort of environment,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the other day Downtown Waco Inc. was promoting the
concept without knowing it. To kick off an outdoor concert series
downtown, she invited Tinker Clift of the Texas State Technical
College turf management department to come and sell beddable
flowers and ferns grown by students in the TSTC greenhouse. Sold
out.
</P>
<P>
   Clift knows the attraction of plants, not just in terms of
earning people's affection but also in urban centers bringing
people back. In a host of ways, plants improve shoppers'
dispositions, diners' appetites, and property values in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a city that has a lot of plants, your whole well-being is
better,'' said Clift. ``Everyone in the world wants to live in
Austin and that's one of the reasons,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Nealy, whose Town and Country Gardens remade the Trib's
beds, says such plants as roses, gardenias, wisterias and magnolias
are big aroma makers, as are the mountain laurel he planted at one
corner of our property.
</P>
<P>
   A city that wants to win people back, or businesses that want to
earn customers' good graces, could do so leading them right by the
nose.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
