<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0796 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TEENS-SUMMERJOBS0612-     06-11 1720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-SUMMERJOBS0612-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Helping teens apply themselves
 &HT;    By Ruth Innis Quast
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Thousands of high-school teen-agers are pounding
the pavement looking for summer jobs. What are their prospects?
What opportunities are available to them? And how will they go
about seeking employment?
</P>
<P>
   Retail stores and fast-food restaurants are popular places of
employment for teen-agers _they can usually get hired on the spot.
But sometimes it takes a village to put teen-agers to work, and the
Miami Valley is doing just that with help from business
organizations, high-school guidance counselors, federally and
state-funded programs and family members.
</P>
<P>
   The Kroger Co., in conjunction with the Dayton Urban League,
will launch its annual registration drive this month to prepare
hundreds of teens 14 and older to apply for bagger positions that
start at $5.40 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we get them ready for their first job,'' said
Krista Austin, Kroger's Cincinnati labor-relations specialist. ``We
teach them how to fill out an application, basic interview skills
and how to act on the job,'' she said. ``After training, they go
out to a Kroger location of their choice and apply for a courtesy
clerk position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teen-agers who go through our training program get preference
over any other job applicant,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Municipal aide positions starting at $8.50 an hour are available
at the City of Dayton Parks, Recreation and Culture Department.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers should apply through civil service, be at least 16
years old and have one year of paid or volunteer youth leadership
work experience, said Peggy Collins, the department's recreation
superintendent. After training, they assist program directors in
running community-center programs, city day camps, swimming pools,
park playground activities and cultural affairs programs.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD WORK HABITS ARE ESSENTIAL
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bayless, a career specialist at Colonel White High School,
scans the ``Employment Guide,'' a free ``help-wanted'' publication
that can be found at most grocery chains and retail outlets. He
posts jobs of interest to teen-agers on the high-school bulletin
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also do referrals,'' Bayless said. ``Recently, we posted a
flyer received from the Potter's House Relief Center, announcing
its annual application drive to attract teen-agers into its Dayton
Youth Program.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any teen-ager between 14 and 17 years old can apply,'' said
Duane Darden, executive director of the relief center, where
assistance is provided to the needy and to the homeless. ``The
program's designed to put teen-agers to work and to keep them off
the streets and involved in positive activities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the kids come into our program, we teach them the proper
way to dress, how to talk to people, the importance of getting to
work on time and the necessity of obeying authority,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After training, participants earn a weekly paycheck by raising
funds for the relief center. ``We set up booths at prearranged
business locations throughout the city, where program donations are
solicited, under the direction of one of our adult mentor
volunteers. We sell candy, cookies, custom return-address labels
and household cleaning products,'' Bayless said.
</P>
<P>
   When students aren't working, they have access to the
organization's activity center, where they mingle, play games,
practice basketball and sign up for monthly chaperoned field trips.
</P>
<P>
   About 250 jobs will be available to teen-agers through the Jobs
for Graduates program, said John McConnell, Partnership for Youth
program manager. ``We give students, usually 14 and 15 years old, a
chance to get job experience working at nonprofit organizations
throughout the county,'' he said. ``They're paid through grants and
work for minimum wage ($5.15 an hour).
</P>
<P>
   ``Before they go out on the job, we teach them the basics about
being punctual, getting along with co-workers, how to follow
directions and how not to be afraid to ask their boss a question.''
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER JOBS AS CAREER STARTS
</P>
<P>
   Another arm of Jobs for Graduates is a ``school-to-work
transition'' program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're stationed at 22 high schools throughout the Miami
Valley,'' said McConnell. ``Students start the program as freshmen
and take classes for academic credit where we teach them
employability skills. We also work closely with the business
community and when students get close to graduation, we help match
up employers with their career interest and give them assistance in
getting a job.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Shannon Jones, 15, a freshman, plans to do. Last
summer, to prepare herself for the work force, she took a volunteer
job at the YMCA West Area Branch assisting counselors at the summer
day camp for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I want to go for Jobs for Graduates,'' she said,
``in hopes of getting on at the VA Center.''
</P>
<P>
   Someday, Jones would like an internship in the computer industry
because her career plan is to become a computer engineer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps to find a job you can make a career out of and get
on-the-job training,'' said Rhett Walters, a Vandalia Butler high
school junior. He works at THT Presses, a tool-and-die shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cut metals with a band saw and sandblast parts,'' he said.
After graduation, ``I'll go on to Sinclair to learn CNC machining
and end up with a degree in tool-and-die.'' Walters said he got his
job through a friend of the family who works at THT.
</P>
<P>
   Francine Howell, 17, a senior, encourages teen-agers to use
family connections to get summer jobs. Last summer, she painted
houses for her brother, a painting contractor. ``By the end of the
summer, I was earning $7.50 an hour,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, she's worked at Crown Equipment Co., where her
sister recommended her for a clerical job. Howell recently applied
for an escort position at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base, where
her mother works. She found an ad in the Skywrighter, a base
newspaper, that lists summer jobs for teen-agers, a good source for
other students who are looking for summer work, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Schirmer, a senior, is involved in one of nine Miami
Valley Tech Prep programs.
</P>
<P>
   Schirmer takes automotive technology classes in the morning and
works at Slone's Automotive garage in the afternoon, where he does
oil changes, tuneups, brake jobs, and engine repairs _ getting
hands-on experience while working under this mentorship program.
After graduation, he plans to go into the two-year automotive tech
program at Sinclair and someday open up his own automotive-repair
shop.
</P>
<P>
   TECH PREP PROGRAM SERVES HUNDREDS
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Jayne, assistant coordinator for the Miami Valley Tech
Prep Consortium said, ``We serve 64 area high schools and have
1,500 students participating in our tech prep programs. We look at
it as a four-year college-bound program starting in the junior year
of high school and leading to a two-year associate's degree at
Sinclair,'' she said. Programs include information technology,
electronics and computer engineering, business technology and an
interactive media program, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Although the tech prep program is federally funded, it operates
under the Ohio state educational system and, in the Dayton area,
the consortium is housed at Sinclair Community College.
</P>
<P>
   For the noncollege bound student, the Occupational Work
Experience program is available to juniors and seniors at most high
schools in the Miami Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a state-funded program,'' said Bob Sells, Vandalia Butler
High School's OWE coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are in school part of the day earning required credits
towards graduation and work in supervised jobs in the afternoons
and evenings to earn their elective credits,'' explained senior
counselor Donna Moosbrugger. In most of these jobs, ``students earn
about $6.50 an hour, but we did place one young woman at Henger's
Nursery as a flower arranger and she's earning $9 an hour,''
recalled Sells. Most of these jobs can turn into summer jobs as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Sudie Jacques, a high school guidance counselor, recommended
that students check the school's Job Opportunity Bulletin Board,
dedicated to job listings available in the community. Most high
schools maintain them. Jacques said they get requests for help from
veterinarian offices, nursing homes, summer day camps, grocery and
discount stores and some hospitals, who have volunteer positions
available for those students too young for most other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been taking applications since March,'' said Erthale
Barnes, a Montgomery County Department of Human Services
supervisor. ``We provide students with academic enrichment programs
and work experience throughout the summer.'' After they take life
skills and pre-employment classes, students are placed in
prearranged jobs in the business community at $5.46 an hour, Barnes
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton Area Chamber of Commerce also is involved in putting
teen-agers to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a Web site that holds over 2,400 jobs open in the
Miami Valley,'' said Wendy Smith, work force development manager.
``Some are internships or summer jobs for teen-agers, and we
encourage companies to get these jobs on our Web site at every
level,'' she said. The address is www.nationjob.com/dayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Web site is also the main site used by the Job Bank,
located at the Montgomery County Job Center, a resource center for
job seekers. It's free and it's a great place for teen-agers to go
to access the internet. They have about 30 computers, as well as
copiers and fax machines, plus career guide books.''
</P>
<P>
   And for those teen-agers who want to leave the county and have
fun working at an amusement park, Paramount Kings Island hires up
to 4,000 employees during peak season. The park holds a job fair
every January and February but continues to hire all summer long,
stated Jeffrey Siebert, marketing communications area manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can come here during park hours, fill out an application,
and we interview them on the spot,'' he said. ``We also offer
internships to high school seniors who want to enter the field of
marketing, public relations or advertising.'' Siebert said they're
taking applications now for internships.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
