 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, June 12:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA (Beirut, Lebanon) _ Developments after the death of
Syria's longtime leader, Hafez Assad. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-ISRAEL (Jerusalem) _ The view from Israel and how Assad's
death affects the regional peace effort. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-SCENE (Damascus, Syria) _ The scene in the Syrian capital.
By Courtney Kealy
</P>
<P>
   MONTENEGRO-ELECTION (Podgorica, Yugoslavia) _ Montenegrins turn
out in force for local elections that are seen as a key test of
their desire for independence from Yugoslavia. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL-COURT-U.S. (United Nations) _ The United States is
going into a crucial conference Monday on the
soon-to-be-established International Criminal Court, still asking
for changes in its charter. The United States is trying to protect
U.S. soldiers and officials from falling under the court's
jurisdiction. But all members of the European Union and other
members of NATO support the court and have told the United States
that there should be no attempt to reopen debate on how it will
work. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Zhongshan, China) _ Hong Kong entrepreneurs have
helped transform Guangdong Province into the fastest-growing region
in China _ a capitalist hothouse on the South China Sea. As China
moves closer to its dream of entering the World Trade Organization,
though, people here are nervous. Far from relishing the prospect of
free trade and wide-open markets, they worry that the new
competition could threaten their livelihood. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-BOMBING-RANGES (Tsuu T'ina, Alberta) _ It is a
little-known footnote to the military history of North America that
when wars loomed in the 20th century, military planners in Canada
and the United States repeatedly turned to the defeated native
peoples of the West and took control, through leases or outright
expropriation, of large swaths of land for bombing ranges. In the
United States, at least 16 tribes have land contaminated with the
litter of bombs. In Canada, the pattern was similar, with old
bombing ranges on about half a dozen Indian reserves, ranging from
British Columbia to Ontario. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-PENALTY-STUDY (Undated) _ The most far-reaching study of
the death penalty in the United States has found that two of three
convictions were overturned on appeal, mostly because of serious
errors by incompetent defense lawyers or overzealous police and
prosecutors who withheld evidence. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-CHEATING (Potomac, Md.) _ Six students at the highly
regarded Potomac Elementary School complained at home about some
odd things they noticed about the way their fifth-grade state
achievement tests were administered last month. They thereby
precipitated the resignation of the school principal, the
suspension of a teacher, and the discovery of what officials
describe as substantial evidence of administrative cheating on a
test that lends ranking and, inevitably, cachet to the best schools
across the state. The test incident has made Potomac Elementary a
new focus in the national debate about whether high intensity
standardization tests risk skewing education as much as helping it.
By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   EXETER-GAY-FACULTY (Exeter, N.H.) _ The board of trustees at
Phillips Exeter Academy, the nation's most prestigious private
school, has voted to permit gay faculty members to live openly with
their partners in academy dormitories starting in the fall of 2001.
The decision, which the trustees said is aimed at encouraging
inclusiveness and diversity, follows similar moves at Phillips
Andover and Concord Academy. By Kate Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   MAYORS-CONFERENCE (Denver) _ Not too long ago, cities like
Akron, Ohio, were given up for dead. Crime was on the rise, local
industry on the decline. Downtowns resembled a ghost town. Those
down days are a memory for city leaders gathering at a national
mayors' conference. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CLIMATE-CHANGE (Undated) _ A widely anticipated warming of
the planet in coming decades is likely to have profound impact, for
better and worse, around the United States, with consequences
ranging from chronic erosion and flooding on the coasts to rising
agricultural productivity in the grain belt. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Washington) _ House Republicans will flesh out
their proposal for Medicare drug benefits this week and try to push
it through two House committees in three days. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SECURITY-ADVISER-PROFILE (Washington) _ Jim Steinberg, the
deputy national security adviser, is departing the White House
after being with Clinton since before the beginning. By John
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ABORTION (Washington) _ Gov. George W. Bush and his fellow
Republicans are beginning seven weeks of difficult politics around
the issue of abortion. It is a potentially divisive element in his
decision on a running mate, his handling of the party's platform
and the moderate, upbeat image he seeks to project at the party's
convention in Philadelphia. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Dateline TK) _ The vice president launches a new strategy,
emphasizing his role in the economy. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Commentary; subject TK. By William
Safire.
</P>
