<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0829 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-REALWORLD-MTVKIDS0612     06-11 1504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REALWORLD-MTVKIDS0612-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seven new faces joining hit MTV show
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ It's kind of a real world: the Belfort mansion,
facing the St. Charles Avenue streetcar tracks in the Garden
District, home this year to MTV's ninth season of ``The Real
World,'' which premieres at 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the Greek Revival house's white pillars, a cell phone is
ringing. Somebody's explaining to somebody else about the robot
dog: the . . . stupid . . . robot . . . dog. A grandfather clock
contains a fish tank. Dozens of plain-covered books are bolted to a
wall along the stairs (``20 Reasons Why Danny Isn't Gay'' somebody
scribbled on one).
</P>
<P>
   The upstairs hall is lined with armoires; these old New Orleans
mansions didn't bother with closets (and ``Real World'' doesn't
allow interior doors). Giant metal bug sculptures hang from the
bright, funhouse walls. So do carved skeletons and local folk art
and . . . name it. One ``Real World'' cast member sums up the
unisex bathroom's decor: ``Where Martha Stewart and Busta Rhymes
got together.''
</P>
<P>
   But after 124 days, the tiny cameras and microphones planted
everywhere in this house are no longer recording each twitch and
syllable of the seven young cast members. (From January to May, a
director sat in front of 26 monitors, behind a temporary wall,
dispatching camera crews to anywhere in the house any time of day).
Their unobserved lives will take some getting used to; they're only
back inside the mansion on this sultry May morning to tout the
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like what people must feel like,'' says Danny Roberts,
a University of Georgia graduate from Rockmart, Ga. about being
freshly unobserved. ``It's the oddest feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an odd sign of these unblinking times how once the reality
of a ``reality'' show ends, the real world feels not quite so real.
You'd think we'd be better acclimated to the blur by now; that as a
species we'd have contorted to the televised realityquake that
``The Real World'' has spawned in the form of ``Survivor'' and the
upcoming ``Big Brother,'' in the same way our spines shot upright
after we developed an opposable thumb.
</P>
<P>
   But after walking out of the house unrecorded for the first time
in four months the day before, the cast spent the evening screening
the season's hourlong ``Real World'' premier. They watched
themselves arriving at the house for the first time all over again,
and some got that down-the-rabbit-hole feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was intriguing to walk out the door here at noon, and then
watch ourselves walk in this same door on the show,'' says Matt
Smith, a 21-year-old Georgia Tech junior from Hiawassee, in far
north Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something else, man,'' he adds of the whole ``Real
World'' experience. ``No one can prepare you for it.''
</P>
<P>
   CAST MEMBERS
</P>
<P>
   ``The Real World'' is one of MTV's highest-rated series, and it
has never been more popular: Last season's Hawaiian cast averaged
3.2 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Each year's septet becomes a kind of one-season-only,
love-'em-or-hate-'em boy-girl band. Cast members are known to
viewers _ the demographic bulge is 18- to 24-year-olds _ by their
first names , their obvious character traits (especially the
nauseating ones) and the city they lived in.
</P>
<P>
   There's a kind of paint-by-numbers method to the casting that's
designed to keep things stirred up: a gay guy, a black guy, a naive
white girl, an ambitious white guy. . . . Two thousand hours are
taped, then edited story line-style down to 22 half-hour episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a crazy chemistry experiment that can explode in
your face, or make great TV,'' says Jon Murray, who developed the
show with Mary-Ellis Bunima, former daytime soap producer.
</P>
<P>
   He adds of the show's granddaddy status amid TV's current
reality craze: `` `Big Brother' and `Survivor' wouldn't be there if
this show didn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   This season's Georgians are key. Danny, 22-year-old UGA grad
(class of '99, French major), is the gay guy. A visit by his armed
forces boyfriend Paul, whom he met weeks earlier at Blake's bar in
Atlanta, is Tuesday night's most dramatic event. (Because of
possible repercussions from the military, Paul's face is blurred,
like a ``Cops'' suspect.)
</P>
<P>
   Matt, a Tech industrial design major, is the blond hip-hop moral
compass Webmaster (his Web page: www.supa-fly.com). He's a Life
Teen leader at Atlanta's Christ the King Catholic Church, and in
New Orleans he attended mass daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love them both _ they had the biggest lasting effect,'' says
Julie, the questing, wide-eyed Mormon chick. ``Danny is so tolerant
and such an awesome person. And Matt is a genuine, caring person.
And he has such a cute butt!''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Kelley, the babe, from Arkansas, playing up the small-town
roots she shares with Danny and Matt: ``Georgia just makes a good
buncha boys _ there's some good breedin' down there.''
</P>
<P>
   TWO SMALL TOWN GUYS
</P>
<P>
   Danny and Matt aren't much alike, except for coming from small
towns, moving to Atlanta and winding up in ``The Real World.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny and I would allude to Atlanta about every three
minutes,'' says Matt. ``It was, `In Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   this . . . ' and `In Atlanta that. . . . ' ''
</P>
<P>
   Danny's biggest accomplishment was exiting Rockmart.
``Everything I did there was about getting the hell out.'' He left
for UGA. He planned to teach high school French, but hated student
teaching. He landed a job with an Atlanta accounting firm.
``Everything that happened after college has been a complete
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   He signed up for a ``Real World'' audition ``to escape.'' He
hadn't watched the show in five years, but made the final cut,
among 35,000 applicants, last December. He came out to his parents
on Christmas Eve. ``A nice Christmas present for my folks,'' he
sighs. ``I wouldn't think of coming here without telling them
first.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows he's the show's Gay Guy _ ``It's definitely part of my
package, but it's not all of my package'' _ and his relationship
with Paul is a vital part of the season. Like his housemates, Danny
says the ``Real World'' experience was an emotional, Freudian
roller coaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times I didn't think I'd be able to finish, and
times I was on a natural high,'' he says. ``It was day to day. Your
natural moods are increased tenfold _ there's so much in this
environment to annoy you. ``But I learned an important lesson in
life: how to listen.'' I had a big ego before I came here and
didn't listen to anyone. The majority of people here have their
egos blown up. People were really wanting to be the center of
attention, and not just because of the camera. You get to a point
where you tune the cameras out.''
</P>
<P>
   Each cast member went every Monday into a ``confessional'': a
private room where they were interviewed about the week before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was out of the interviews that I learned about myself,
having people questioning me about things I'd said and done,''
Danny says.
</P>
<P>
   Is he ready to have it all out there on TV?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no choice,'' he says. ``But just thinking about seeing
myself on TV weirds me out right now.''
</P>
<P>
   REAL WORLD EXPERIENCE
</P>
<P>
   Matt wanted out of Hiawassee, but not because he hated it. He
loved it. He just wanted more. More . . . everything.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to be an artist, but when he got to Tech, he also
wanted something practical. Solution: industrial design. He was
active in clubs, hosted a video show on the Georgia Tech Cable
Network. When a GTCN segment on a ``Real World'' audition fell
through, he made his own audition tape. ``I'm about knocking on
doors,'' he says. ``If you don't knock, they'll never open.'' He
describes MTV's final-cut phone call as ``the most intense moment
of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt was more prepared than most for living with six new
roommates: His parents took a total of 38 foster children into
their home while he was growing up. But even that wasn't quite up
to what he faced in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This house was a whirlpool of relating _ it was a shock,
people all hours of the day wanting to relate,'' he says.
``Sometimes I just wanted to tell everyone to get a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard, fun, exciting, trying _ nothing like this ever
happened to me. Two thirds of the way into it, I asked myself why I
came here. But I came out a confident, happy man. I'm more
fine-tuned in my communicating skills. You have to communicate with
six weirdos _ we're all weirdos _ all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have to talk and cry and fight about everything.
I'm not about that. I thrive off being productive. So I did a lot
of reading and Web design, while they were relating 24 hours a day.
`How do you feel? How do you feel?' Almost makes you want to puke
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   So was his ``Real World'' experience real?
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it absolute reality? No. In reality, there are no
cameras,'' Matt says. ``But nothing could have been done to make it
more real.''
</P>
<P>
   Really.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
