<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LICENSING-AD-COLUMN-A     06-11 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LICENSING-AD-COLUMN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELOISE, THE GRINCH AND FRIENDS TAKING A PAGE FROM HARRY POTTER
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood was stunned last summer when Kenn Viselman's Itsy
Bitsy Entertainment Co. beat out several big studios for the
merchandising and film rights to the Eloise books, the classic
1950s children's series about a cheeky little girl who lives in the
Plaza Hotel in Manhattan. Variety called it ``not just an itsy
bitsy surprise: it was a shock.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Viselman was enchanted by Eloise's comic antics, it
wasn't just the appeal of the character that turned his head. As
the man behind the marketing of ``Teletubbies,'' Viselman saw in
the Eloise books a long-term brand franchise that could be
transformed into everything from dolls to a television series to a
string of feature films.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can build a brand or you can build a movie franchise: a
brand generates a lot more money and a lot more exposure over
time,'' Viselman said. ``A successful book will sell 100,000
copies. A hundred million is a successful movie, but a successful
licensing program can do $1 billion in its first year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eloise licensing program is still in its infancy, so exactly
how much revenue it generates remains to be seen. But one thing is
certain: in this year of J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter, Eloise will
have lots of famous company from the world of children's
literature: Dr. Seuss' Grinch, ``Clifford the Big Red Dog'' by
Norman Bridwell and ``Curious George'' by H.A. and Margaret Rey.
</P>
<P>
   All are getting expanded merchandising, from key chains and
lunch boxes to puzzles and CD-ROMs, as the licensing of children's
book characters becomes a story in itself.
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight is on book characters at a moment when movie
marketing has slowed and Harry Potter has captured the imagination
of millions. The Potter books _ the latest one will be published
next month _ are the most obvious touchstones. But the exploitation
of book characters also fits into a trend of conservatism in the
often-brazen world of licensing.
</P>
<P>
   At least some of the wariness emanates from the outrageous
expectations and hype of films like last summer's ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace.'' Book characters, in contrast, are
recognizable brand names with an established fan base that
presumably makes them easier to sell as broader media and
merchandising properties. Classic books also appeal to adults, who
are the gatekeepers in the children's market.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Eloise and the others will be on display at Licensing
2000 International, the annual trade show of the International
Licensing Industry Merchandisers Association, which opens Tuesday
at the Javits Convention Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of buzz around Harry Potter and around Eloise _
these are two very big deals,'' said Charles M. Riotto, president
of the trade group. ``But it's part of the whole trend. Even before
Potter or without it, you'd still see this move into building the
publishing segment. There's a higher comfort level to deal with
properties that have an established audience base.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Brothers, which has the worldwide rights for Harry
Potter, will begin releasing selected products based on the first
book in the fall, with another round next year linked to release of
a feature film.
</P>
<P>
   The Universal Studios Consumer Products Group, a unit of Seagram
has awarded licenses to 70 companies to produce merchandise tied to
the holiday release of Dr. Seuss' ``How The Grinch Stole
Christmas!'' directed by Ron Howard and starring Jim Carrey.
</P>
<P>
   And after years as a book, ``Clifford The Big Red Dog'' is being
turned by Scholastic Entertainment into a television series on PBS
this fall, with the actor John Ritter as the voice of Clifford and
the Nickelodeon star Kel Mitchell as the voice of his friend
T-bone.
</P>
<P>
   Itsy Bitsy Entertainment will turn Eloise _ who made her debut
as a fancy doll at F.A.O. Schwarz _ into the first of several
feature films next year and is also working on an animated
children's series.
</P>
<P>
   Universal has awarded licenses to 150 companies to produce
Curious George products _ triple the number of companies three
years ago _ and it plans to bring the little monkey to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The licensing of children's book characters is not new. Indeed,
licensing based on the characters of Beatrix Potter, which include
Peter Rabbit and Squirrel Nutkin, dates back almost a century, and
there are a lot of perennial favorites like ``Winnie The Pooh'' and
``The Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   But last year, the business of licensing publishing properties
saw a 33 percent increase in royalty revenues to $40 million,
according to a study by the licensing industry association. Even
some adult book series are benefiting, like ``Chicken Soup for the
Soul,'' which is now a television series and a board game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Literary properties are great assets because they have a
history and a familiarity,'' said Dan Romanelli, the president of
Warner Brothers Worldwide Consumer Products. ``Today there is some
risk involved in any business, but when you have 20 million books
sold like Harry Potter, and a fourth about to be released, you know
that there's continuity, and that's difficult to find.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, there is no one big movie this year, like ``The Lion
King'' or ``Jurassic Park,'' that would drive a huge merchandising
onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   And the industry is wary. Walt Disney, a virtual marketing
machine, has not had a blockbuster movie merchandising property for
some time, said Viselman. The Star Wars film generated an estimated
$1 billion in retail sales, but that was not always enough for
companies to cover the cost of the licenses and still make a
profit. Producers saturated the market, and some retailers were
stuck with too many products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation of how much you could do got so out of hand
that people lost all sense of reality as to what was possible,''
said Marty Brochstein, executive editor of The Licensing Letter in
New York. ``It was a marketing machine that fed on itself, and a
lot of people ended up paying the price.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Book publishers say it is exactly this kind of fad-chasing that
is playing into the growth of treasured book characters. At
Scholastic Inc., the executive vice president Deborah Forte said
she sensed a growing weariness among retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this hype for a six-week window, and then they have to
find the next big thing,'' Forte said. ``I think the longevity and
sustainability of publishing properties tends to be better than
some of the just-media properties.''
</P>
<P>
   Overpromotion is a concern in expanding book characters as well,
and Viselman and others said they were carefully controlling
expansion of their product to avoid saturation. Warner is so
concerned about keeping a brand franchise for Harry Potter over the
long term that it went to Madison Avenue for help and hired Grey
Advertising to advise the company on building a brand.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the book character trend is just one inside the $74
billion licensing industry that spans a broad spectrum of
businesses and pop culture. The publishing category generated some
$1.3 billion in retail sales last year, a tiny portion compared
with huge categories like the $17.9 billion business of corporate
branding, or the $15.9 billion in licensed retail sales from the
entertainment industry, according to The Licensing Letter.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the classics are coming to life now by sheer
happenstance. The Eloise books became available after the death in
July 1998 of the author, Kay Thompson, who did not market the
property. And licensing around Dr. Seuss occurred after the widow
of the author Theodor Seuss Geisel learned that copyright laws
required that she use the rights or risk losing them.
</P>
<P>
   One big reason books make popular licensing is that they have
inherent value as an educational tool. Parents, who wield some
control over these purchases, often prefer book properties in a
world where shielding children from violent and inappropriate
material is a daily chore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Books in world culture are viewed as very important and
well-respected,'' said Nancy Cushing-Jones, Universal Consumer
Products' president for publishing rights. ``A good book has an
intrinsic value that a T-shirt doesn't have. And the process of
bonding with kids through reading is extremely important.''
</P>
<P>
   But Seth Siegel, co-chairman of the Beanstalk Group, a licensing
agency and consulting firm in New York, said the entire trend was
simply entertainment licensing, albeit inspired from books. He said
the classics had been around forever, but the products did not move
off the shelves until they were made into a media property.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't elevated literary properties,'' he said. ``We've
just given Hollywood another way of taking pop culture icons and
turning them into images that can be absorbed by the mass
population.''
</P>
<P>
   And what will become of it all? Siegel predicts a rash of
children's stories will be turned into films followed by a few wild
successes and then, the inevitable losers.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then one day we'll be reading a trend report that says
properties based on books don't work,'' Siegel said. ``I think it
was Balzac that once said all fashion ends in excess. He was
speaking of something else. But he should have been speaking of the
licensing industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
