<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0860 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FADING-BOUNDARIES-2TA     06-11 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FADING-BOUNDARIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET ARTISTIC GRAY AREAS BE, AS LONG AS TRUTH IS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given how many things _ politics, economics, cultural moods and
movements _ we preface with amorphous terms like ``post,''
``trans,'' ``global'' and ``multi,'' we're clearly in a state of
high anxiety about how to define them. Definitions mean boundaries,
and all of these terms make clear that the boundaries we once knew
are disappearing. At most we have borders now, meant to be crossed,
redrawn or erased.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the furor over the Tony-winning show ``Contact.'' It was
nominated as a musical. It is all dance and music built around
three revuelike sketches, one in pantomime. But the American
Federation of Musicians protested the use of tape instead of live
music. So did others, Tony voters among them.
</P>
<P>
   A musical must have an original score, people I spoke to said.
(The dances in ``Contact'' use an antic mix of music: classical,
jazz and rock; Tchaikovsky, Bizet, Stephane Grapelli, Benny
Goodman, ``Do You Wanna Dance?,'' ``Runaround Sue'' and more.) What
kind of encouragement does this give to lazy, cynical producers who
don't want to risk money on more expensive productions with new
music that the public must learn to love?
</P>
<P>
   It's true that the musical can't thrive without new composers.
But consider the cultural crimes that have been committed in their
name? No sooner did Andrew Lloyd Webber loosen his hold on Broadway
than Frank Wildhorn and Elton John arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The best new composers and lyricists are getting their start in
small houses off Broadway's beaten, musically abused track.
``Contact'' imitators aren't likely to be anywhere near as smart or
talented as its choreographer and director, Susan Stroman, or its
book writer, John Weidman. But that's always the case with
imitators, whatever they're copying.
</P>
<P>
   The musical has been in such bad shape for so long that I'm game
for all experiments. Call ``Contact'' a dance play or a musical
performance piece; invent a new category for shows that put music,
movement and language together in unpredictable ways.
</P>
<P>
   However it's done, let a show like ``Contact'' stir people to
keep inventing musicals instead of copying them. Its form was
unusual, but its impulse was primal. It showed us that musicals
don't exist except to convince us that the people onstage always
feel a song coming on, and therefore, in the succinct words of Gene
Kelly, ``Gotta dance, gotta dance, gotta dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Literature, too, is in something of a tizzy over definitions,
appropriations, genres and such. Fiction and nonfiction use each
other's techniques. History and fantasy combine forces; memory is
both lying and truth-telling. And nowhere is all of this clearer
than in the historical novel.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the furor that broke out a few weeks ago over Susan
Sontag's historical novel ``In America'' (Farrar Straus &AMP; Giroux).
It was based on the life of the great Polish actress Helena
Modjeska, who emigrated to the United States in 1876 and lived a
glamorous and dazzling life.
</P>
<P>
   Sontag has been accused of taking passages from the works of
historians, journalists and Modjeska herself that are virtually
unchanged and unacknowledged beyond a briefly expressed debt to
``material and anecdotes used and altered.''
</P>
<P>
   And naturally other writers of historical fiction, as well as
historians, began debating the conjunction between what you invent
and what you borrow, and what you need to tell the reader about
this process. Some go no further than acknowledging the libraries
where they did their research. Others supply short bibliographies.
I suspect it's often a struggle: What novelist doesn't want to get
as much credit as possible for creativity and inventiveness?
</P>
<P>
   Sontag's solution, as reported in The New York Times on May 27,
was to dismiss the historians and journalists in question, along
with Modjeska, as being merely information sources, not writers.
She said that while they supplied the raw matter, she produced a
work of art. But what interested me most in the end was the
question of how history _ fact if you will _ shapes
characterization.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing her surprise that Modjeska scholars were not
thrilled, Sontag concluded: ``She was a great figure. I made her
into a marvelous person. The real Modjeska was a horrible racist.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, I thought, the race card does pop up in unexpected places.
Sontag certainly tries to make her heroine marvelous by propping
her up with period dialogue, letters, journals and aphoristic
musings.
</P>
<P>
   But I would much rather read about a woman of great talent and
charisma _ a marvelous creature indeed _ who was also a woman with
monstrous beliefs. I want to feel and understand all of this. I
don't want things to be prettified and simplified in the name of
literary uplift.
</P>
<P>
   While I was thinking about all this, a 12-year-old friend with
excellent taste recommended a historical novel that she loved, Ann
Rinaldi's ``Hang a Thousand Trees With Ribbons''(Gulliver
Books/Harcourt Brace).
</P>
<P>
   It was about yet another immigrant artist (an immigrant by
force, not choice), the 18th-century slave and poet Phillis
Wheatley. And it presented a good test; I am not alone in having
always found poor Phillis an aesthetic trial and psychological
embarrassment, despite her interest historically.
</P>
<P>
   She was taught to read and write by her relatively enlightened
Boston owners, petted and coddled as she began to write poems, and
then examined on her Greek, Latin and verse by a group of
Massachusetts men who included the governor and John Hancock. It
was then certified that she had indeed written the poems in
question.
</P>
<P>
   One heard from childhood about her precociousness, her piety and
her well-behaved poems. What could one feel besides pity or
contempt for lines like these, in ``On being brought from AFRICA to
AMERICA''?
</P>
<P>
   'Twas mercy brought me from my Pagan land,
</P>
<P>
   Taught my benighted soul to understand
</P>
<P>
   That there's a God, that there's a Saviour too;
</P>
<P>
   Once I redemption neither sought nor knew.
</P>
<P>
   Rinaldi doesn't quote these lines in her novel. She quotes very
few of Wheatley's proper, Alexander Pope-inspired, acutely
melancholy poems. She gives us the Phillis Wheatley who had to
learn how to be pious and conventional _ the price of a slave
girl's education _ and who sometimes fought, sometimes embraced her
role as the symbol of how a debased race might prove itself worthy
of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   She shows us how the writing, which always had to meet the
approval of her owners and their friends and doubting publishers,
was as much genteel bondage as intellectual or spiritual freedom.
</P>
<P>
   She gives us a spunky, high-strung Phillis Wheatley, but also a
Phillis who is crushingly dependent on the kindness of strangers
who become first her owners and then her family. She needs to
believe in some form of salvation, and she needs to display
spiritual obedience. Thanks to Rinaldi, I now understand what it
took for her to write the next lines of that poem, the only racial
defense that Puritan Boston and Christian Britain would understand.
</P>
<P>
   Some view our sable race with scornful eye,
</P>
<P>
   ``Their colour is a diabolic die.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Christians, Negros black as Cain,
</P>
<P>
   May be refin'd, and join th' angelic train.
</P>
<P>
   Do I like these lines any better than I did before? No. But now
I understand the circumstances and the needs that make her
admirable, infuriating and, almost unbearably, sad.
</P>
<P>
   Give us the infuriating, the shameful and the horrible. The
purely noble and marvelous are much too simple.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 1646EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
