<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0862 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NEW-ECON-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-11 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ECON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ECONOMY COLUMN: TECHNOLOGY STOCK SLUMP HASN'T EASED MANPOWER
CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURIE J. FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the recent sell-off in technology stocks and the steady
drumbeat of failing dot-coms, the search for the best
high-technology employees continues. And recruiting them still
takes extreme measures _ not the least of which is learning the
names of potential recruits.
</P>
<P>
   One ploy currently in vogue _ with many variations on the theme
_ has a headhunter call a company, posing as a prospective date who
has lost the name and phone number of the nice guy she met at the
gym the night before. ``He said he was director of engineering,''
the headhunter confides to the company receptionist, who can't help
but oblige by producing a name and extension. In another ruse, a
recruiter phones a company's front desk and pretends to be the
manager of the new restaurant that just opened up down the street:
``We'd like to send everybody in marketing a gift certificate for a
free lunch. Now if I could just get their names.''
</P>
<P>
   And so goes the race to hire away the best minds of the
information technology industry. Even as some dot-com companies
hand out pink slips, true high-technology jobs remain a employee's
market, with far more jobs than job candidates. Microsoft, which
has not let its antitrust travails slow its talent search,
currently has 3,000 unfilled positions. Cisco Systems hires 3,000
people every quarter _ if it can find them.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the point of view of companies trying to hire, this has
been the worst few years in the history of the planet,'' said John
Holman, a San Francisco recruiter. The hardest workers to find are
technical ones _ software designers, test engineers, programmers.
And start-ups are also plagued by a shortage of managers.
</P>
<P>
   While demand for workers shows no sign of abating, what has
changed recently is what it takes to lure away a new senior-level
employee: cash. Stock options, particularly in companies not yet
public, have considerably less allure than they did just a few
months ago, according to the recruiters helping to craft
compensation packages.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, executives changing jobs might have agreed to
pay cuts as long as they received plenty of stock options. Now,
though, companies are finding they must pay more in salary and
options, as well as a bonus and other perks.
</P>
<P>
   Pay for a marketing vice president now runs between $170,000 and
$250,000 plus stock options and, often, a bonus. That compares with
top salaries of about $150,000 six months ago. And potential
employees are scrutinizing companies' financing and management more
closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would rather go to more established companies,'' said
Valerie Frederickson, president of a high-technology recruiting
company in Menlo Park, Calif., that bears her name, so they need
not worry about when or if a promised initial public stock offering
actually happens. ``Employees are getting angry that their
companies are delaying their IPOs.''
</P>
<P>
   Frederickson did note that layoffs at smaller Internet companies
had helped create a noticeable increase in job candidates in May.
</P>
<P>
   David Pritchard, Microsoft's head of recruiting, said there was
no end in sight to the shortage of workers, though he added that
competition from Internet start-ups for new recruits had
diminished. ``Given what's been happening in the stock market
lately, people are looking a little less at the big payoff that the
dot-coms are offering,'' he said. ``When candidates have a
competing offer, we tell them to go do some research.''
</P>
<P>
   Holman, the recruiter, said he, too, had noticed greater caution
on the part of job candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine months ago, you could say to someone at Hewlett-Packard,
`Sure, we're going to pay you less, but your stock may soon be
worth $50 million,''' Holman said. ``Now, that same stock looks
like it will be worth only $10 million. It's a change in the
risk-reward trade-off.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider Thomas Blanco, who just last month took a job at a
publicly traded Internet music company in San Francisco after a
year at a telecommunications company and 20 years in banking before
that. He spoke on condition that his current employer not be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   A human resources director, Blanco had considered a competing
offer from an Internet start-up that planned to go public soon, but
he decided the risk was not worth it. Had he been making the move a
few months earlier, before the Nasdaq's dive in April, he said his
decision might have been different. ``I knew that the number of
IPOs from here on would be smaller,'' Blanco said.
</P>
<P>
   To lure new hires, companies continue to add perks, including
catered dinners on a daily basis. In a recent survey by Deloitte &AMP;
Touche of chief executives at high-technology companies, a quarter
said they offered their employees free meals at work. Six percent
said they allowed employees to bring pets to work. Other flourishes
included in-house gyms, dry cleaning and even flu shots.
</P>
<P>
   But few things beat more money. Back in February, Microsoft's
management in Redmond, Wash., raised salaries in the company's
Silicon Valley operations 15 percent across-the-board. That move
came after Microsoft concluded that it would otherwise be unable to
compete in the Northern California job market, where housing costs
and living expenses were far higher than in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   And in April, Microsoft's president and chief executive, Steve
Ballmer, announced a new companywide stock option program. The hope
was to bolster the confidence of current employees and attract new
ones in light of both the lower stock price and the vagaries of the
government's intention to split the company.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq uncertainty is not scaring everyone away from start-ups.
Michael Marrow, an executive with more than 10 years experience in
providing outsourced customer service, recently signed on as chief
operating officer of a new company called ShipServ, which plans to
develop an e-commerce marketplace for the deep-sea shipping
industry. He turned down more lucrative offers in order to ``create
something that has not been created before,'' he said, despite the
fact that other dot-coms were facing layoffs and delayed stock
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a 25-year-old programmer,'' Marrow said. ``I know
there are not guarantees, that the payoff may be further down the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, joining a start-up is still considered boot camp for
managing larger companies. In fact, Frederickson said some of her
clients in large, established corporations would consider only
candidates with some experience at companies before they went
public. ``You have to get your ticket punched at a pre-IPO company
or you don't get any respect,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The difference now, she says, is job candidates may want more
cash along with the respect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-REALITY-SHOWS-2TAK     06-11 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REALITY-SHOWS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: IN TV GAMES OF `LET'S PRETEND,' REALITY LURKS
</HEADLINE>
  By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dressed in authentic Victorian clothing, members of the Bowler
family step inside 50 Elliscombe Road, the 19th-century house in
suburban London that will be their home for three months. They have
agreed to live there as their ancestors would have _ without
telephones, computers, dishwashers (or detergent, shampoo, tampons)
_ except their ancestors weren't televised, as the Bowlers will be.
</P>
<P>
   The house, stripped of all modern trappings and painstakingly
refurbished, is a pristine example of turn-of-the-century
middle-class propriety. After gasping at the elegance, the family
matriarch, Joyce Bowler, says slyly of her new home, ``It's an
original, but I'm a fake.''
</P>
<P>
   With this, the excellent new PBS reality show ``1900 House,''
(which the network is coyly billing as a ``docu-soap''),
immediately distinguishes itself from the pack. While capitalizing
on our apparently insatiable voyeurism, this British-produced
four-part miniseries (which begins Monday) has a sense of humor
about itself, a quality noticeably absent from CBS's ``Survivor''
and even from MTV's coltish ``The Real World.''
</P>
<P>
   Another difference: You can emerge from the ``1900 House''
experience with new insight, not only into the obvious (differences
between life then and now) but also into the nature of reality
itself. Or at least the nature of reality as television presents it
these days.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Survivor,'' which had its premier on May 31, 16 men and
women were stranded _ with a camera crew _ on a deserted island.
Every week they vote to eject one person. The final ``survivor''
wins $1 million. Later this summer on ``Big Brother,'' CBS installs
a group of people in a house under nonstop surveillance. Every week
the audience votes someone out, with a half-million-dollar prize to
the last remaining tenant.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday's season premiere of ``The Real World'' seven
strangers, all young and attractive, move together into a house in
New Orleans, where they will spend the next few weeks producing
their own cable-access show. Will they get along? Who will sleep
with whom?
</P>
<P>
   The CBS ``Survivor'' Web site, cbs.com/survivor, which is more
interesting and complex than the show itself, does venture a bit of
anthropologic theorizing: ``The behavior of B.B. (the 62-year-old
real-estate developer who was kicked off the island last week) and
Joel closely matched that of Rwanda's Silverback gorillas,'' says
one article about two of the island dwellers. ``In every tribe of
gorillas one dominant male assumes control. No other male is
allowed to mate with the group's female gorillas or lead the group
in any way. Through age and infirmity, a dominant male can lose his
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Shows like ``Survivor'' and ``The Real World'' seem most like
the audience participation segment at an improvisational theater,
performed by amateurs but cleverly packaged by entertainment
professionals. By carefully choosing their subjects and settings,
the producers can almost predict possible scenarios and edit the
material accordingly. Unlike actual reality, which is distressingly
random and unedited, these shows fall into a predictable pattern.
There will be quarrels, flirtations, danger and revulsion. On
``Survivor,'' bugs have already been eaten.
</P>
<P>
   What do we learn about the human condition? People apparently
enjoy watching other people's pettiness and problems, even when the
people themselves aren't all that interesting. The ``Survivor''
ratings, already high, increased for the second show and topped
those of the ratings Goliath ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
People (in general and on these shows) in their early 20s are
obsessed with themselves and sex: ``The Real World'' entices with
the prospect of a good-looking young man who shocks the group by
declaring that he intends to remain a virgin until marriage.
</P>
<P>
   These shows are very different from old reality television,
which earnestly believed in truth with a capital T. Most famous was
``An American Family,'' the PBS series _ controversial in the '70s
_ which followed the Loud family right through the breakup of the
parents' marriage. On the other hand ``Candid Camera'' planted the
seeds for ``Survivor,'' by contriving situations in which people
could be ``caught in the act of being themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``1900 House,'' too, plays to our desire for story and drama,
indulging our increasing cultural inability to digest unsweetened
information. So the Bowler family undergoes its share of
deprivation and reacts with satisfying outbursts of temper and
frustration, and subsequent reconciliation and renewal.
</P>
<P>
   But this series has a larger purpose that it fulfills with great
success. The Bowlers know from the outset that the only prize
they'll win is knowledge, about the Victorian era and about
themselves. There is no cash award. In a clip from the Bowlers'
audition interview (they were chosen from more than 400
applicants), Joyce explains that she wants to know if her family is
held together by 20th-century technology. Can its members be happy
without it?
</P>
<P>
   Designed as an experiment rather than a contest, ``1900 House''
tries to honor its documentary duty. The producers present not only
the family's travails but lots of miscellaneous information about
the Victorian era, including the kind of earthy detail Edith
Wharton couldn't divulge (about feminine hygiene, for example).
</P>
<P>
   A narrator periodically informs us about the hardships: the
dearth of hot water for baths, the terrifying rate of infant
mortality (one in four children didn't survive past age 6) and
household dangers like wallpaper containing arsenic.
</P>
<P>
   Fashionably, the producers have made the process part of the
program. The first episode is devoted to the enormous task of
refurbishing the house and choosing the family. This proves to be
surprisingly engaging, in part because the man who does much of the
explaining _ a social historian named Daru Rooke _ turns out to be
perfectly cast. A mild, balding man in his 30s, he's like a good
character actor playing a crucial secondary part, the fellow who
help moves the plot along. (Such men are valuable in life, too, but
appear more frequently on television.)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   During the selection it would become obvious who couldn't stand
yesterday's realities. ``If we go more than two weeks without a
proper curry, I mean a proper Indian curry, we become very
irritable,'' says one of the fathers who wasn't picked.
</P>
<P>
   A consulting psychologist explains why the Bowlers were chosen:
``They have a sense of adventure, a good sense of humor, and
they're also quite comfortable with the camera.''
</P>
<P>
   All true, but even the good-natured Bowlers will become cranky
at times. After their initial infatuation with the house subsides,
they learn some hard truths about Victorian life, even for a
comfortable middle-class family. The indoor light was gloomy, the
food was bland, and people were more pungent because it was so
difficult to wash clothes and bodies. And there was an awful lot of
family togetherness, too much, perhaps, for people accustomed to
the diversions of television, movies, computers and Gameboys.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce, who dragged her husband and four children into this
adventure, emerges as the leading lady. A small, thoughtful
44-year-old, she offers a running commentary on her expectations
and disappointments. Her battle with the demands and restrictions
on a Victorian woman fulfills both the program's documentary and
dramatic needs. The roots of feminism are easy to see.
</P>
<P>
   Her real struggles with her whalebone corset brought to mind a
vivid description from a Louisa May Alcott novel, ``Eight
Cousins,'' written in 1875. The heroine is Rose, a young orphan
girl being raised by her uncle, a doctor with radical ideas. When
he finds out someone has tried to put a corset on the girl, he
asks, ``Have you lost your senses that you can for a moment dream
of putting a growing girl into an instrument of torture like
this?''
</P>
<P>
   But Joyce's true awakening comes when she decides to hire a maid
(who has to agree to abide by the show's rules while working at 50
Elliscombe Road). Thrilled with her new-found freedom (without a
machine, the laundry alone consumed three days a week), Joyce goes
to the library. She reads about the burgeoning feminist movement
and feels at one with the suffragists. But her appeal lies in her
self-awareness, as both would-be suffragist and quasi-actress, so
she soon feels guilty about having someone else _ a woman no less _
cleaning up after her.
</P>
<P>
   In an act that seems chivalrous to her, she decides to let the
maid go, but is too cowardly to do it in person. She fires her by
mail. This shocks and wounds the maid _ who in fact is an actual
maid, like her mother and grandmother _ and makes Joyce feel
ashamed. This sort of no-win situation feels very real.
</P>
<P>
   The others have their own problems and pleasures. The husband,
Paul, has to shave with a straight razor and the teen-age daughter,
Kathryn, is overwhelmed by her unshampooed ``dirty, smelly, greasy,
skanky'' hair. Nine-year-old Joe refuses to eat almost everything.
The 11-year-old twin girls, however, adapt best, concocting
theatrical performances with paper-doll puppets and a homemade
stage and otherwise amusing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, reflecting on their experience, Joyce says she would
like to be able to say the family will change. ``You have to make
more time _ more thought _ more time for each other,'' she says.
Kathryn, on the other hand, can't wait for the family's first stop
after vacating the ``1900 House,'' at Burger King.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to sympathize with Kathryn. Maybe soon all of us will
reach our saturation point with artificial reality (though the
climbing ratings of ``Survivor'' indicate that soon may be later).
Maybe after watching ``1900 House'' everyone should turn off the
television for a while. Consider the words of the French
existentialist Albert Camus, born just after the Victorian age, in
1913.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a sin against life,'' wrote Camus, ``it consists
perhaps not so much in despairing of life as in hoping for another
life and in eluding the implacable grandeur of this life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
