<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0871 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKLE-INTERNET-ART-N     06-11 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKLE-INTERNET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPRAH AND U.N. CANDIDATES FOR INTERNET WATCHDOG, SURVEY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If a group of grandmothers from Atlanta were running the
Internet, there would be no chat rooms and absolutely no government
involvement. And they would enlist Bill Gates, the church and the
United Nations to help them oversee the global network.
</P>
<P>
   College students, on the other hand, want the CIA, the National
Security Agency and the Internal Revenue Service involved, since,
as they see it, ``these people pretty much run who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   One woman from Nebraska suggested that Oprah Winfrey would make
a good Internet watchdog. The candid and sometimes contradictory
opinions were offered in focus groups held around the country the
last two weeks as the Markle Foundation began taking what may be
the first comprehensive look at public attitudes about the
Internet, its regulation and governance and online privacy and
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The results from the 10 two-hour sessions, with groups of six to
eight people, offered only preliminary insights and were mainly
intended to help the researchers narrow their focus and redefine
their questions before beginning more in-depth surveys.
</P>
<P>
   The sessions were perhaps most significant in underscoring the
complex and tough task facing policy makers around the world as
they seek to govern the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Participants seemed to trust business over government to
regulate the Internet. On privacy and fraud, they echoed the call
of buyer beware. When pressed, however, most seemed to expect some
type of rules or protections. And few knew anything about
consumer-protection programs implemented by Internet companies or
about a new international body that administers the Internet's
system of domain names.
</P>
<P>
   Zoe Baird, president of the New York-based foundation, a
nonprofit organization, said the goal of the six-month survey and
follow-up research was to dig beyond public opinion polls to see
how people really feel about and act on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to conduct a test to figure out if what people
are saying is in response to what they have read and heard or what
they really do,'' Baird said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, polls show that the public is concerned about
whether their privacy is protected on the Internet. Many say they
would never give out private information like credit cards numbers.
But, researchers are asking, would they change their minds when
offered a $20 gift certificate?
</P>
<P>
   The final report, to be published in September, is intended both
to engage the public in Internet policy discussion and to provide a
basis for lawmakers and companies to develop intelligent, long-term
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``As these focus groups are beginning to show, these are very
complicated issues,'' Baird said. ``We hope this will help in
developing and understanding what policies are sustainable.''
</P>
<P>
   The research is being conducted with Greenberg Quinlan Research
Inc., a Washington public policy research firm. To begin the study,
focus groups were held recently in Omaha, Atlanta, Scottsdale,
Ariz., and Syosset, N.Y. Participants included adults between 18
and 75, split between Internet users and nonusers.
</P>
<P>
   Because the focus group participants were promised anonymity,
the foundation provided only first names and ages of participants.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Greenberg, who is leading the research, said he was
struck by the shift in attitudes about whether government should
try to regulate the network. In a study he did two years ago for
the Direct Marketing Association, he said, people were more
inclined to want government to try to regulate things like
pornography.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't understand the Internet as well,'' he said.
``They understand more now about the difficulty of regulation.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even older people who have never used the Internet
seemed hesitant over the prospect of new laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, it's the one thing that government doesn't control,''
said Evaughn, a 69-year-old retired federal worker from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she and others in her group thought there should be some
rules. Evaughn even brought in an e-mail message from someone she
knew that discussed the case of a young girl who had been lured by
an online sexual predator.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for anybody to be in chat rooms,'' she
added, saying they were dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The questions and exercises in the focus groups tried to explore
participants' attitudes about online privacy and to get a sense of
what kind of groups they would want running the global network.
</P>
<P>
   Although initially most people said they were hesitant about
having government involved, many seemed to think that the Federal
Trade Commission's recent request to Congress to pass basic rules
for how companies handle personal information collected online had
some merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have the right to know where your stuff is
going,'' said Kristin, an 18-year-old restaurant worker in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Most participants said they were wary of giving away personal
information. But during simulations, few seemed to recognize the
seal of a popular program called TrustE, begun by the industry to
certify sites that comply with basic privacy standards. And most
acknowledged that they never read the privacy policies posted by
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   During a discussion about information that companies have
compiled on people on the Internet and elsewhere, Donna, a
21-year-old nurse from Long Island, said, ``Everybody can find
anything, so forget about it _ we should all just crawl in a
shell.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, she said she still shops online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should just stop giving stuff out on the Internet, but
it's so convenient,'' she said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   On the topic of Internet regulation, only one person had heard
of the Internet Corp. for Assigned Names and Numbers, or Icann, a
nonprofit group appointed by the Clinton administration to oversee
the administrative functions of the Internet and set rules for its
addressing systems.
</P>
<P>
   Though when asked what kind of group they would appoint to run
the network, most called for a group similar to that Icann is
trying to put together _ one that is international and run by
Internet companies and individual users.
</P>
<P>
   And in nearly every focus group, a top choice to be part of that
board was Gates, the Microsoft Corp. chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Although most groups said the United Nations should be involved,
few wanted any other government representation. But many of the
older women thought the church or a theologian should be involved,
``someone with morals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should put Oprah on there,'' said one middle-aged
woman in Omaha. ``She has a lot of pull. She'd be pulling for all
of us. She has a loud voice with good morals. She's always for the
underdog.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
