<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BALLET-MUSIC-DIRECTOR     06-11 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLET-MUSIC-DIRECTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY BALLET APPOINTS BRITON AS MUSIC DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York City Ballet has named Andrea Quinn, the
music director of the Royal Ballet in London, as its new music
director.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Quinn, 35, a conductor whose experience has
included work with major opera and symphony orchestras as well as
the recording of Paul McCartney's recent composition, ``Tuesday,''
ends an unabashedly public search by the company. In the last two
years 12 guest conductors, including Quinn, have led the City
Ballet's orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to find a music director to succeed Gordon Boelzner,
who has been ill, came in the wake of complaints from the company's
artistic management and members of the public about the
inconsistent quality of the musicians' performances.
</P>
<P>
   A monthlong strike by the orchestra's members last winter was
settled after they agreed to a formal commitment stating that City
Ballet is their primary employer and to new work rules that will
not permit outside engagements to affect rehearsals and performance
at City Ballet as in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, who will join the company officially as music director in
August 2001, went out of her way to call both the dancers and
musicians outstanding. In an interview at the end of last week at
the New York State Theater before she returned to London, she said
she looked forward to the company's range of music and to being
involved in the creation of new works. She also said she hoped the
company could sponsor independent concerts for the musicians in the
way the Royal Opera House does for its musicians.
</P>
<P>
   The works of City Ballet, which has the widest musical repertory
of any ballet company in the world, are frequently set to music,
often difficult, that is most often heard in concert halls, rather
than to scores specifically written for ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn will begin her three-year contract in 2001 after her
contract with the Royal Ballet expires. Until then she will
continue to conduct as a guest at City Ballet, and Boelzner, who
will retire after 41 years with the company, will remain music
director, a post that involves advising Peter Martins, City
Ballet's artistic director, on the choice of music. Hugo Fiorato
will remain principal conductor.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, whose liveliness in the pit is reflected in her
conversation about music, said she had been interested in
conducting since she was a teen-ager. Born in London but brought up
mainly in the town of Leighton Buzzard in Bedfordshire, she began
clarinet lessons at 13. At 15, she heard a recording of Brahms'
First Symphony, and ``that was that,'' she said, explaining that
the music led her to explore ``what is inside a score and find the
heartbeat.'' That, she added, is ``the wonderful part of
conducting.''
</P>
<P>
   After studying music at Nottingham University, Quinn specialized
in conducting at the Royal Academy of Music until 1989 and won two
prizes there. In 1993, she won the Conduct for Dance Competition
and was appointed music director of the London Philharmonic Youth
Orchestra. She was also guest conductor at the Birmingham Royal
Ballet in 1993-94 and became music director of the Royal Ballet in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if some of the musical repertory at City Ballet was new to
her as a conductor, she said she had not previously conducted
Stravinsky's ``Agon,'' which was written by the composer for George
Balanchine, the company's co-founder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Balanchine was so forward looking,'' she said, adding that
while she enjoyed conducting full evening 20th-century story
ballets, their scores were often fashioned out of pieces of music.
City Ballet's respect for the integrity of a score appeals to her:
``These scores are untainted by someone coming in and cutting the
music up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, who has conducted the English National Opera and symphony
orchestras in Europe and Australia, expressed particular interest
in new music. Her preferred contemporary composers are James
MacMillan and Thomas Ades, both British, and Poul Ruders, a Dane.
</P>
<P>
   As City Ballet's fourth music director, she will be its first
female conductor. But she said: ``I hate being talked about as a
woman. I should be considered as a conductor.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn is married to Rod Champ, a doctor, and has two daughters.
Champ expects to qualify to practice in the United States and the
family is to join her in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't think of coming without them,'' Quinn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
