<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0874 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WEB-CONTENT-980(2TAKE     06-11 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-CONTENT-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: NET JOURNALISM TRIES TO REGROUP AFTER LAYOFFS AND
SETBACKS
</HEADLINE>
  By FELICITY BARRINGER and ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Web journalism is usually cast as savior or savage. For some
people, online journalism is a path to interactive enlightenment
and economic liberty. But to the puritans of the old media world,
Web journalists are apostates who have confused liberty with
license and whose delusional disregard for profit can end only in
self-immolation.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard for the puritans not to act smug last week.
</P>
<P>
   The aftershocks of the Nasdaq's April collapse, which had
already shaken the e-commerce world, hit news and information
sites. Salon and CBS.com both announced layoffs. And the crime news
site APBNews.com became an undead dot-com, dismissing its staff of
140, then allowing some to hang on, unpaid, while the bosses sought
new partners to bring the site back to life.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's tremors forced analysts and other Web publishers to
conduct various forms of industry damage assessment _ and consider
what it may take to make surviving sites earthquake resistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to be terribly surprised that this sector of
the industry is going to consolidate,'' predicted Peter Petrusky,
director of new media for the auditing firm PricewaterhouseCoopers.
``The future belongs to those sites that are developing multiple
revenue streams.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mooradian, an Internet analyst at Jupiter Communications,
said that the week's events clearly signaled the more cautious
approach by investors. ``It is mostly a testament to the fact that
capital availability is drying up,'' he said. ``If these guys want
to lessen their burn rates in any substantial way they have to slim
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Burn rate, of course, refers to money up in smoke. And Mooradian
noted that many of the Web companies, including online journalism
sites, had spent lavishly on marketing because they had been
assured that they would be able to raise second rounds of
financing, whether through venture capital investments, strategic
investment or public offerings. But, he said, ``that window has now
closed.''
</P>
<P>
   An exception might seem to be Inside.com, the new, richly
financed media news site led by the author and editor Kurt
Andersen. But because it takes money to burn money, some analysts
wonder how long such a site _ providing expensive, original
reporting _ can withstand budget-minded competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Take MediaNews, the daily roundup assembled by Jim Romenesko.
For a good deal less than $100,000 a year, coffee included,
Romenesko can match much of Inside.com's speed and depth on his
MediaNews site, simply by studding his digest with hyperlinks to
the work of other journalists _ including Inside.com's. ``You're
right, I rely on reporters around the world to give me the good
content, and I'm the editor,'' said Romenesko, who works for an
$80,000 annual salary from the Poynter Institute for Media
Studies..
</P>
<P>
   Even more automated is Moreover.com, founded by a former
newspaper reporter. The site uses technology that monitors content
sites for articles, then lists them as headlines and provides hot
links to originating sites _ including the Web sites of the BBC,
CNN and The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Readers can customize a Moreover.com home page to get the kinds
of news they are most interested in, and other publishers can
arrange links _ as George magazine's Web site (georgemag.com) does
for Moreover's political headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters and Advance.net, the Internet arm of Advance
Publications, which owns Conde Nast, are expected to announce
Monday that, along with Soundview Ventures, they have invested $21
million in Moreover.com.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the aggregation game is not restricted to tiny
upstarts. America Online's news section draws 14 million distinct
visitors monthly, 70 percent more than the nearest old-media news
site, MSNBC.com. America Online offers wire-service dispatches from
Bloomberg News and Reuters; readers can also link to the reports of
other news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   When Editor &AMP; Publisher Online did not include America Online in
a recent analysis of news sites, Gary Kebbel, director of AOL's
news, e-mailed Carl Sullivan, Editor &AMP; Publisher Online's editor,
to take issue. Kebbel contended that in many communities more
people use AOL as an online news source than use the Web sites of
their local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   So what does the trend toward sites that repackage someone
else's journalism mean for online publishers that are intent on
actually reporting, writing and editing their own material?
</P>
<P>
   Slate, the online magazine with probably the highest profile in
online journalism, has the advantage of a giant parent: Microsoft.
After Slate's debut in 1996, its early setbacks were closely
watched by the envious. And after its much-admired editor Michael
Kinsley had to abandon his attempt to lure paying subscribers, for
instance, most others did not even try.
</P>
<P>
   So far, The Wall Street Journal, with its subscription-based
Wall Street Journal Interactive online service, seems to be one of
the few news and information sites finding a steady audience of
paying customers. Meanwhile, Slate now runs promotional
advertorials _ Blue Nile diamonds, anyone? _ in its table of
contents, although the Magazine Publishers of America guidelines
ask print magazines not to do so.
</P>
<P>
   With little hope of subscription revenue, Web sites have
imitated the broadcast TV model, seeking to attract big audiences
and sell them to advertisers. And advertisers have obliged,
increasing their Web spending from $906.5 million in 1997 to $1.9
billion in 1998 and $4.6 billion in 1999, according to the Internet
Advertising Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, of that 1999 total only 8 percent went to news and
information sites, according to a report prepared for the bureau by
Pricewaterhouse. By comparison, search engines and portals, like
Yahoo.com or About.com took in 38 percent of the total.
Technology-related sites took in 18 percent; financial sites, 15
percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In search of other forms of revenue, some online publishers have
turned to licensing deals. CBS's MarketWatch.com, a leading
financial news site, owns a service called Big Chart that creates
financial charts. MarketWatch's chief executive, Larry Kramer,
estimates that while 75 percent of the site's revenue in 2000 will
probably come from advertising, most of the rest is likely to come
from licensing the chart technology to other online publishers.
</P>
<P>
   And not everyone has given up on the subscription model.
Inside.com, for example, plans to charge $217 annually for
subscriptions _ despite the rollback on subscription charges by
other high-maintenance sites with lots of original content.
</P>
<P>
   Inside.com executives contend that readers will be willing to
pay for high-quality material. But Deanna Brown, the chief
operating officer at Inside, said that the expense of the site's
comprehensive coverage was worth the freedom from old-media
constraints. The established media companies have the benefit of
established brands and experienced managers, she said. The
drawback, she said, ``is that they have legacy publications they
have to be concerned with, and they don't offer entrepreneurial
opportunities to talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Established media companies, however, do not necessarily see
their legacy publications as dead weight.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Bart, editor in chief of the entertainment trade
publication Variety, contends that the best efficiencies come from
a new-media offshoot borrowing from and contributing to an
old-media original. Thus does Variety play give-and-take with its
Variety.com Web site. ``The key to the Variety site,'' he said,
``is that it is derived from the basic old brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Bart said that last week he hired four new staff members and
planned to hire 20 more this year. He also plans to expand the Web
site's coverage of raw entertainment industry data, a franchise on
which Inside.com is also placing an emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   So who's winning _ the puritans or the apostates? It may be too
soon to tell, but certainly last week's upheavals were enough to
try a Web journalist's soul.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Ken Layne, a columnist for Online Journalism Review
(www.ojr.org), posted a piece saying, ``Whenever the dot-com
business/media system is bumming me out beyond my ability to type _
generally, every three or four months _ I convene other disgusted
new-economy scribes and present the question, `How in hell did we
end up doing something so gut-wrenchingly stupid?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
