<HEADER>
A0876 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-11 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEB SITE TRACKS PARCELS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a monthly fee of $9.95, a new Web service will track the
status of a customer's FedEx and United Parcel Service shipments,
alerting the sender whenever a package arrives later than the time
guaranteed by the delivery company.
</P>
<P>
   Once alerted, the shipper can then use that information to
demand that the delivery service fulfill its on-time guarantee by
paying a full refund for the cost of shipping the package, which
typically ranges from $10 to $20.
</P>
<P>
   The new service, OnTimeAuditor.com, is aimed at businesses that
send large volumes of packages, typically more than they could
track manually, said Robert Morse, the company's vice president for
marketing and its co-founder.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 million packages that FedEx and UPS ship each day,
more than 5 percent _ about 800,000 _ arrive late, Morse said,
citing industry estimates. Assuming about $12 a package, that would
be $10 million a day in unclaimed refunds.
</P>
<P>
   At OnTimeAuditor.com, customers can total their potential
savings using an onscreen calculator. A company shipping 100
packages a month could save about $1,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The service is based on a program that Michael Harris, a
software entrepreneur, developed in the 1980s to track the arrival
of software packages he shipped to customers. He was frequently
frustrated by customer complaints that packages had arrived late
without the delivery service ever alerting him to the delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just kind of assumed that it got there, and suddenly a
customer would call and say it hadn't,'' Morse said. ``You're
paying for a certain level of service.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, OnTimeAuditor is able to track only FedEx and UPS
shipments, but the company is planning to add other carriers this
year. Morse estimates the entire package-refund market is worth
about $2.5 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   E-SIGNATURES BILL PENDING
</P>
<P>
   Congress is expected to pass legislation this week that would
make electronic signatures and records as legally binding as
pen-and-paper versions. Passage would end a long stalemate over how
far a law should go in freeing financial institutions from current
consumer notification laws.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise bill, approved by a House-Senate conference
committee late last week, would confirm that electronic signatures
and electronic records were legal. It would also provide a way for
banks and insurers to notify consumers of late payments or changes
in credit card or loan contracts by e-mail rather than postal mail,
and it would allow financial institutions to begin keeping more
records electronically.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation incorporates a measure sought by the Clinton
administration, requiring a company to conduct a test e-mailing
with customers before sending any subsequent e-mail notifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good news for both the Internet economy and American
consumers,'' Rep. Thomas Bliley Jr., Republican of Virginia and
chairman of the House Commerce Committee, said.
</P>
<P>
   SITE PROMOTES BANNER ADS
</P>
<P>
   It is an online advertiser's dream: an Internet site consisting
entirely of banner ads, those animated rectangles found at the top
of a Web page that exhort viewers to ``click here'' for sales
information.
</P>
<P>
   But the 70 examples of banner ads found on the new
``clickhere!'' site, www.soulbath.com, do not try to sell products.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, they are selling the concept of banner ads, in a
backhanded answer to the growing perception that the tiny,
billboards are a costly and ineffective way to advertise.
</P>
<P>
   Florian Schmitt, who has a Web-design firm, Hi-Res
(www.hi-res.net) in London, asked fellow designers from around the
industry to submit alternate approaches to banner ads by filling a
400-by-80 pixel space with ``sense or beauty, or both.'' The
results were put on the Web site last week.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the entries are crudely anticommercial or
blatantly self-promotional, many do induce an irrepressible urge to
click.
</P>
<P>
   Mat Poprocki's minimalist offering, for example, is all white
except for the text ``don't click here.'' You just can't help
yourself, even if nothing happens when you inevitably do click.
</P>
<P>
   Others include Ed Burton's ad, a rectangular cage for a series
of squirming geometric creatures. Chris McDermott's banners explode
into shards or sag down the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Maurizio Poletto's ad acts as an actual Web browser, forcing
users to view a page through a banner-size slit. And Andrew
Cherry's entry mimics the on-screen display for a Windows file
transfer but shows money flying out of a wallet, with the message
``Please Wait _ Extracting Cash.''
</P>
<P>
   The site may be an exhibition of antibanners, but, Schmitt said,
``I don't hate banner ads. They're just not as good or as clever as
they could be, so no one watches them anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
