<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-11 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASIER-TO-USE SITES WOULD HELP E-TAILERS CLOSE MORE SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the spring of 1998, Internet retailers were troubled to learn
that, according to a report by Forrester Research, two-thirds of
Web shoppers abandoned their ``shopping carts'' before actually
buying something. At the time, and throughout last year, e-commerce
companies pledged to improve the shopping experience, giving
customers no reason to leave without passing through checkout.
</P>
<P>
   But because investors showed little inclination to penalize
e-tailers for such basic deficiencies as failing to close the sale,
these resolutions were frequently shuffled to the back burner, in
favor of planning television ads and making business development
deals.
</P>
<P>
   And so, consumers are still abandoning their Web shopping carts
at the same rate as they did in 1998, according to a recent report
by Shop.org, an industry trade group. But now, with e-tailers under
increasing pressure to start actually making money, Web merchants
are suddenly getting serious in their efforts to squeeze whatever
cash they can from site visitors.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report planned for release today by Creative
Good, a consulting firm in New York, e-tailers could generate
substantially more revenue by focusing on basic customer needs,
like speed and simplicity. The report estimates that e-commerce
companies could realize an additional $20 billion in sales this
year _ bringing overall Web sales to some $57 million _ by
improving site design, navigation and overall ease of use.
</P>
<P>
   Creative Good's chief executive, Phil Terry, concedes that
prescribing these changes may be much easier than getting sites to
implement them. ``We've seen a real resistance to the basics in the
industry,'' he said, ``which indicates that this is just the tip of
the iceberg.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Terry said, many e-commerce sites still fail to
track their order conversion rates _ the rate at which visitors
become paying customers. Shop.org recently pegged the average
conversion rate at 1.8 percent, but Terry, said e-tailers could
easily raise that rate to 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring such a core statistic, he said, indicates how little
attention many sites are paying to what visitors actually do once
they get to the site. The Creative Good report focuses on a number
of key categories in which merchants typically fail their
customers, including page design, site search and the checkout
process. The report criticized Martha Stewart.com, for instance,
for letting customers add out-of-stock items to the shopping cart
without informing them until reaching the final checkout that the
items are unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Stewart, the chief executive of Martha Stewart Living
Omnimedia, acknowledged this shortcoming, but disputed the notion
that changing it would be easy. ``We're working on that,'' Stewart
said. ``But the coordination between the catalog and the Internet
operations has to be perfect before we can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The company that handles inventory and fulfillment for
MarthaStewart.com, the Time Customer Service unit of Time Warner,
has an older computer system, she said, so it takes a while for the
site to search Time's database for in-stock items. Because of this,
Stewart and her executives decided not to slow things down with a
real-time inventory check of each item as a shopper selects it.
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart said the company was searching for a fulfillment
partner that will enable the site to display real-time inventory
without slowing down the customer. ``It's a minute-to-minute task,
to keep up with technology and customer demands,'' she said. ``It's
a constant thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web is littered with glaring examples of poorly designed
pages and features, of course. The Creative Good report
acknowledges as much, pointing out sites that label products poorly
(or not at all), sites that try to pack too much information onto a
page, and sites that require customers to fill out a lengthy
questionnaire before they can actually browse for goods.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if there is a common criticism from those within the
industry, it is that e-commerce sites may be interesting to look at
or listen to, but they are not easy enough for many customers to
use. And that, says H. Robert Wientzen, president of the Direct
Marketing Association, may be because e-tailers are still
struggling to shed their high-tech habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to a reverence for technology,'' Wientzen said.
``A lot of the people who started these sites are technologists,
and in the beginning, at least, the people who used the sites were
more savvy about technology.'' Now that the Web is more closely
aligned with mainstream culture, he said, the sites must cater to
the capabilities of nontechnical customers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, technology itself is making it easier for Web sites
to be more shopper friendly, according to Ford Cavallari, who heads
the e-business practice for Renaissance Strategy, a consulting firm
in Boston. Cavallari said that in the last year, companies that
made software that helped Web sites create their pages _ ``content
management'' software, in industry argot _ had ``moved forward a
light year from where they were.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Webmasters were always behind the eight ball,'' Cavallari
said. ``They were throwing content together on the page. But as
this software has gotten better, the staff has more time to get
more creative and spend time on value-added activities. So the net
effect will be higher quality sites.''
</P>
<P>
   The new urgency on the part of retailers to make a profit could
be a boon to shoppers. Too often, consumers have been lured to the
Web by the promise of convenience, only to find the experience less
convenient than shopping at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hanners, executive vice president of JCPenney.com, said
competitive pressures had forced his site to become more user
friendly. He said the company planned to introduce a new version of
its site in October _ an overhaul that will have taken a year and
the efforts of about 300 people to create.
</P>
<P>
   Through the redesign, he said, the company has focused on its
average customers: women, ages 25 to 55, with a household income of
$55,000 to $70,000. ``It's the sweet spot of middle America,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And a conclusion from the many customer focus groups the company
has conducted while testing the redesign, Hanners said, is that
middle America is most interested in ``noncluttered'' Web sites.
The challenge in putting this insight to use is that JCPenney.com
has 10,000 product images to display.
</P>
<P>
   Hanners would not disclose specifics of the site's new design.
But he said it would give customers options on how they would like
to shop, although not so many options that they would be confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started the redesign, I thought it'd be easy,'' he
said. ``Then I moved to thinking of it as extremely impossible. Now
I'm somewhere in between. People talk about e-commerce being easy.
Well, I'm an old retailer, and I don't recall ever working this
hard at retail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
