and air-conditioning season unfolds, Americans may watch gasoline
meters spin and utility bills soar and be tempted to think bad
thoughts about energy princes in faraway Arabia. But, as the ditty
dictates, why not blame Canada, which is emerging as the No. 1
energy supplier to the United States. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-INFLUENCES (Austin, Texas) _ Even as he downplays the role
of intellectuals and academics, George W. Bush acknowledges that a
group of writers have influenced his thinking, starting with Myron
Magnet and his book, `The Dream and the Nightmare.'' The book,
which Bush said he read before he first ran for governor, is an
indictment of the attitudes of the 1960s counterculture and its
legacy to the poor. In fact, well before Bush burst on the national
political scene, a loose-knit cadre of thinkers on the right were
trying to come up with a less libertarian form of conservatism that
rejects the welfare state but does not turn its back on poverty and
social ills. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   LAWNMOWER-RACING (Mandan, N.D.) _ Perhaps it is the tedium of
watching the grass grow just to cut it down and watch it grow some
more. Perhaps it's just something about men and their motors. No
one has much of an explanation for why it is happening, other than
that it's cheap, or why now. But all across America, men have
discovered new thrills at the gears of the the riding lawn mower.
From Bergholz and Kisistom, N.Y. to Lubbock and Buda, Texas, men
and the rare woman are off to the races on souped-up, decal-coated
John Deeres, Snappers and Montgomery Wards with their blades
removed and whipping around tracks at speeds routinely exceeding 30
mph and sometimes 60. By Peter T. Kilborn.
