<HEADLINE>
CNBC CHANGES MAY BE MORE THAN COSMETIC  
 NO MORE DOG DAYS OF SUMMER IN TV LAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Changes are afoot at CNBC that could mean more statistics and
data and less Geraldo Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   In one sign of changes in the air, workers began building a new
set at the network's studios in Fort Lee, N.J., over the weekend.
When it is completed, a 47-foot-wide wall of video screens will
stand behind the anchor's desk.
</P>
<P>
   The wall will somewhat resemble the busy electronic data board
used by reporters in the glass Nasdaq market studio in Times
Square. The screens will display either separate bits of
information or a single image, while an anchor or correspondent
addresses viewers.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a correspondent at the New York Stock Exchange
could be shown on the wall while being interviewed by an anchor. Or
producers could use the wall to flash facts or charts of interest
to viewers.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC executives said that it would take some time for them to
become used to the wall and that they had not fully figured out how
to meld it into all their programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fairly complex device,'' said Bruno Cohen, CNBC's
senior vice president for business news. ``No one has built one
before, so we'll have to figure out how to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, it was expected to dominate CNBC's business news
programs eventually. The wall will make its debut in July.
</P>
<P>
   That also happens to be when executives are considering dropping
Geraldo Rivera's ``Upfront Tonight'' program _ which covers the
general news of the day and runs on weeknights at 7:30 _ and
replacing it with more business news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upfront Tonight'' is the lead program of CNBC's evening block
of nonfinancial programming, which also includes ``Hardball with
Chris Matthews,'' Rivera's talk show, ``Geraldo Live,'' and ``The
News with Brian Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   For some time, CNBC executives have been considering expanding
business news into that block. Earlier this year, they said, Rivera
let them know he was less interested in continuing with ``Upfront
Tonight'' and would prefer to concentrate on his talk show and
other projects for NBC, like stand-alone specials.
</P>
<P>
   One executive, however, said that no decision had been made and
that nothing would change until midsummer. Rivera was not available
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   _ JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
<P>
   No More Dog Days of Summer in TV Land
</P>
<P>
   The main thing that the latest television phenomenon, CBS'
``Survivor,'' has in common with the previous television
phenomenon, ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' is not the $1
million ultimate prize.
</P>
<P>
   The main thing is that both started as answers to the question
``What did you do on your summer vacation?''
</P>
<P>
   Summer, which for most of the history of television has been a
desert of reruns and reject programs, has suddenly become maybe the
best place to roll out a new show, especially if it is one that
takes some risks and breaks new ground.
</P>
<P>
   One reason, as numerous television executives have begun to
realize, is that in the summer, competition is all but nonexistent.
But more important, a show with a fresh approach can fill a crying
_ and growing _ need in the rest of the media for something _
anything _ to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   As Stu Bloomberg, the co-chairman of ABC Entertainment put it,
``In summer, if you have a hit, you have all the attention to
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   All the attention means dozens upon dozens of interview shows on
cable channels and radio stations, joke after joke from David
Letterman and Jay Leno and Conan O'Brien, reams of newspaper copy
and endless chat on Web sites. The media have become a ravenous
beast, with a massive maw, that demands to be constantly fed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a show can get all that media to itself, it's much much
easier to become a hit,'' said Steve Sternberg, a senior vice
president with TN Media, a firm that buys television commercial
time for advertisers. ``Just like with `Millionaire,' the media was
all over `Survivor.' It instantly became a water-cooler show. The
idea that people won't watch anything in the summer is nonsense.
Not everyone is on vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   The media wave that has emerged from ``Survivor'' has caught the
attention of one network that had not committed many resources to
summer programming, NBC. Garth Ancier, the president of NBC
Entertainment, acknowledged, ``With `Survivor' grabbing all that
attention, we have to have a different strategy for summer.''
Ancier said NBC had already prepared a new budget for programming
next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll see every network gearing up for next summer,''
Sternberg said, ``especially this kind of escapist programming. The
key to launching new shows may become finding the place where
everybody else is doing repeats.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS already has much of the rest of this summer locked up with
the next iteration of the genre, a broader experiment in
televoyeurism called ``Big Brother,'' set to occupy 90 nights
beginning on July 6.
</P>
<P>
   Sternberg said that one interesting angle to the networks'
sudden interest in summer may be how the surge in viewing affects
cable channels, which have always taken advantage of the networks'
``gone fishing'' attitude toward the summer months.
</P>
<P>
   ``There definitely may be people who watch less cable this
summer because of all this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
