<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, June 12. sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A sharp contrast in weather conditions will be noted between New
England and the Middle Atlantic region. Thunderstorms will mark a
cold front pushing southward from New Jersey and Pennsylvania into
Maryland and northern Virginia. A 150-mile-wide band of low clouds
with patches of drizzle will follow the front covering southern New
England much of the day. Skies will clear across parts of the
interior Northeast, but it will be cool. However, hazy, hot and
humid air will occupy the Southeast as far north as Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   A tropical wave will trigger thundershowers in northwestern
Florida. A stream of humid air from central Texas to the central
Plains will be the focus of afternoon storms. A push of extremely
warm air into the Dakotas will produce several strong storms as the
Northwest turns damp and rather cool. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DALLAS WEEKEND  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive weekend, heavy rain fell on the
Dallas-Forth Worth metropolitan region. A stream of tropical
moisture attendant to a dissipating tropical depression in the
western Gulf of Mexico brought as much as three inches of rain to
the east side of the metroplex. During the previous weekend,
torrents of rain flooded the suburbs of Fort Worth with nearly a
foot of rain. The current wet weather pattern is helping to erase a
long-term deficit in rainfall across eastern Texas. Longer-range
forecasts indicate that another band of tropical showers may reach
the region by next weekend. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
