<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. FOCUS GROUPS GAUGE ATTITUDES ABOUT INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   In what may be the first comprehensive look at public attitudes
about the Internet, results from focus groups around the country by
the nonprofit Markle Foundation showed that participants seemed to
trust business over government to regulate the Internet, echoed the
call of buyer beware when it came to privacy and fraud but also
seemed to expect some type of rules or protections.
</P>
<P>
   The sessions were perhaps most significant in underscoring the
complex and tough task facing policy makers around the world as
they seek to govern the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS TO VOTE ON ELECTRONIC SIGNATURES
</P>
<P>
   Congress is expected to pass legislation this week that would
make electronic signatures and records as legally binding as
pen-and-paper versions.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET COOLDOWN HASN'T HIT JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent sell-off in technology stocks and an
increasing number of failing dot-coms, the search for the best
high-technology employees continues. True high-technology jobs
remain an employee's market, with far more jobs than job
candidates. But what has changed recently is what it takes to lure
away a new senior-level employee: cash. Stock options, particularly
in companies not yet public, have considerably less allure than
they did just a few months ago. Now companies are finding they must
pay more in salary and options as well as a bonus and other perks.
</P>
<P>
   PLEDGES RENEWED TO EASE SHOPPING
</P>
<P>
   A report in 1998 showed that two-thirds of Web shoppers
abandoned their ``shopping carts'' before buying something, and
e-commerce companies pledged to improve the shopping experience.
But because investors showed little inclination to penalize
e-tailers for failing to close the sale, these resolutions were
neglected, and consumers continued to abandon their carts. Now Web
merchants are under pressure to make money, and they are suddenly
getting serious in their efforts to squeeze whatever cash they can
from site visitors.
</P>
<P>
   DIAMOND STOCK LISTING IN QUESTION
</P>
<P>
   Oryx Diamonds, a company with close ties to the governments of
Congo and Zimbabwe, may be thwarted in an effort to trade on the
London Stock Exchange, executives close to the company said.
</P>
<P>
   THE ALL-IN-ONE TELEPHONE NUMBER
</P>
<P>
   A telecommunications engineer has patented a system that would
allow people to have just one phone number for all their
telecommunications devices, reducing the need for longer telephone
numbers and more area codes.
</P>
<P>
   A `GEORGE LUCAS' SLEEPER HIT
</P>
<P>
   ``George Lucas in Love,'' a nine-minute parody of ``Shakespeare
in Love'' in which the lovesick, college-age George Lucas is
surrounded by people recognizable as prototypes for the characters
in his Star Wars series, rapidly became an underground hit last
summer in Hollywood. But it did not end there. In October, the
movie became the debut attraction on Mediatrip.com, a
streaming-video Web site. And in April, it was released on
videotape, sold exclusively through Amazon.com. On April 21, the
film's first day of release, it immediately shot to No. 1 on the
site's sales charts.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER TV BECOMES LESS STAGNANT
</P>
<P>
   Summer, which for most of television history has been a desert
of reruns and rejects, has suddenly become perhaps the best place
to roll out a new show, especially if it takes some risks and
breaks new ground.
</P>
<P>
   MACHINE TOOL ORDERS DECLINE 22 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Orders for machine tools decreased an estimated 22 percent in
April, to $450 million from a revised $577 million in March.
</P>
</TEXT>
