<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMA-CUBANS0612-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMA may ask Florida legislators to abolish the state exam
 &HT;    By Sanjay Bhatt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ As the American Medical Association board
convenes this week, its members could decide to step into a Florida
dispute over the licensing of foreign-trained physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Florida became the only state in the nation to offer
its own medical licensing exam, an alternative to the United States
Medical Licensing Examination.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 450 people, mostly Cubans who arrived in South
Florida in the mid-1980s, were eligible to take it. They have been
unable to produce sufficient documents to obtain licenses here or
to pass the national licensing exam required of all other doctors
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other foreign-trained doctors licensed in Florida, this
group doesn't have to be certified by the Educational Commission
for Foreign Medical Graduates and can skip internship and hospital
residency requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these legal loopholes, Frank Cuneo, a Coral Gables
attorney for a group of doctors who have taken the state's special
exam, says they have been hindered by quirks in testing policy and
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, including the Federation of State Medical Boards and
the Florida Medical Association, disagree and say Florida is
setting a dangerous precedent by licensing the doctors under a
different standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the laughing stock of the nation,'' said Dr. Bernd
Wollschlaeger of Aventura, 42, a member of the FMA's international
medical graduates section. ``The standard of care in Florida is
unsafe if we let politicians gamble with licensure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Medical Association has passed a resolution asking
lawmakers to abolish the state exam and require the doctors to
follow the same rules as other doctors. An AMA committee meeting in
Chicago this weekend passed a similar resolution and has forwarded
it to the AMA's House of Delegates, which is convening there
through Thursday. If it passes, the AMA could throw its weight
behind the FMA in lobbying Florida legislators next year.
</P>
<P>
   A state investigator testified before the Florida Board of
Medicine in April that it should be deeply skeptical of Cuban
doctors seeking Florida licenses.
</P>
<P>
   The last five plastic surgeons arrested for unlicensed activity
were Cuban and all claimed to have trained in a Havana hospital's
burn unit, said investigator Enrique Torres, himself Cuban-born.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be more per capita burn victims in Havana than
any other place in the world,'' he said. ``Their certificates are
questionable and suspect at best.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Cuneo responds, ``Unfortunately, that is some of the
bigotry and bias that is presented against foreigners . . . It is
wholly unfair to label any group simply because a few bad apples
have been discovered.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first two state exams given, more than 90 percent of
test-takers failed. Cuneo blames the state for requiring a higher
passing score than the national exam requires and asking ambiguous
test questions. The state test, he says, focuses too much on basic
science instead of clinical knowledge. Cuneo said his group, known
as the Florida International Medical Association, hasn't ruled out
filing a lawsuit against the state.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 400 people, mostly from Miami-Dade and Broward counties,
registered to take the test again last month in Miami. State law
lets them sit for the exam five times within five years.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Cuban-American lobby failed to get a bill passed
during this year's legislative session that would have gotten rid
of the state exam entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, sponsored by Sen. Mario Diaz-Balart, R-Miami, proposed
giving the doctors full licenses to practice medicine after working
for three years under close supervision of a physician. Diaz-Balart
didn't return calls for this story.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would have changed a 1996 law that requires the doctors
to practice medicine under supervision for two years once they pass
the state or national exam.
</P>
<P>
   Cuneo said Medical Examiners phased out the test for which they
had studied, called FLEX, and replaced it with the USMLE. The two
tests are supposed to be comparable. More than 90 percent of U.S.
and Canadian medical students taking the USMLE for the first time
pass it, compared with about 60 percent of foreign-trained
students, according to the federation. Doctors say the disparity is
because of difficulty with English and differences in how schools
train students to treat patients.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the legislature authorized the creation of a state exam
for doctors who had taken the refresher course. The first state
test was given in May 1999. Of 282 taking it, 14 passed. The state
gave the test again in November, offering it in Spanish for the
first time. Eighty
</P>
</TEXT>
