<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0891 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-UM-DIG0612-COX     06-11 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UM-DIG0612-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientists hurry search for prehistoric human remains threatened
by development
 &HT;    By Stephen Kiehl
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE SALT SPRING, Fla. _ Eighty-five feet down into the cold,
dark water of this secluded gulf coast spring, scientists hope to
find the oldest human remains ever unearthed in the Western
Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Like a prehistoric time capsule, the 220-foot deep Little Salt
Spring has almost perfectly preserved evidence of Florida's first
people _ and the other animals they shared this land with thousands
of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But as University of Miami scientists uncover the spring's
secrets, its purity is threatened by nearby development. So they
are working quickly to find proof that people reached Florida
12,000 years ago _ a discovery that would thrust Little Salt into a
raging debate over who the first Americans were, where they were
from and when they got here.
</P>
<P>
   This week, for the first time, the UM researchers plan to go
into an underwater cave 85 feet below the surface. They hope the
cave holds prehistoric human remains from when the first people,
called Paleo-Indians by scientists, entered Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced there were Paleo-Indians here 12,000 years
ago,'' said John Gifford, 53, a marine archaeology professor who
has been exploring Little Salt since 1983. ``The question is, can
we find anything earlier?''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Gifford and his colleagues have found animal remains,
such as the bones of saber-tooth tigers and mastodons, and wooden
tools that are up to 12,000 years old. They also found a
7,000-year-old human skull with its brain tissue intact.
</P>
<P>
   The sinkhole is like a funnel _ about 200 feet wide at the top,
with a gentle slope that once was above water. That is where people
probably skinned animals and made tools and weapons. The slope
narrows to a sharp drop-off, below which was an oasis of freshwater
for humans and animals.
</P>
<P>
   Little Salt is considered one of the best archaeological sites
in Florida, and even in the United States, because the water is
almost devoid of oxygen, meaning there's no bacteria or other
marine life to destroy the prehistoric treasures the spring holds.
Wooden artifacts that regular water would have eaten up in a few
hundred years have endured thousands of years with little damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This site is exceedingly significant,'' said Steve Koski, a
marine archaeologist who has studied sites throughout the state and
is assisting Gifford here. ``The spring has a wealth of information
for our understanding of Florida's past peoples and environment.''
</P>
<P>
   But now the perfect composition of the water is threatened by
encroaching development in the town of North Port, on Florida's
west coast halfway between Fort Myers and Sarasota. A new high
school is rising from the dust just a few miles from the spring,
which also neighbors a golf course, an elementary school and a new
homes subdivision. The spring and 112 acres around it were donated
to UM by a land developer in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford is worried that pollutants and water runoff from the new
development could alter the chemistry of the spring. An increase in
the water's oxygen level would hasten the decomposition of the
artifacts and human remains.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford will analyze the water and is meeting with local
officials to make sure the site is protected. Meanwhile, he and his
graduate students are moving forward with the spring's excavation.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of June, they are scuba-diving about 30 feet
into the sinkhole, vacuuming up sediment from a 6-foot square and
sifting through the sand for artifacts. They've found burnt wood _
likely from a campfire _ and deer bones.
</P>
<P>
   In 30 years of exploration here, the UM scientists have pieced
together evidence of a Florida much different from today's.
Mastodons, huge white-tailed deer, llamas and giant sloths had the
run of the land, and they came together at the few freshwater
springs like Little Salt.
</P>
<P>
   During the Ice Age, when the sea levels were so low that Florida
was twice its current size, Little Salt was freshwater. But as the
seas rose, the spring became brackish, meaning its salinity is
one-tenth that of saltwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire peninsula was like a dried-out sponge,'' Gifford
said. ``That's why a place like this would have been such a magnet
for all animals _ human and non-human.''
</P>
<P>
   People hunted the animals with tools made from wood, bone and
antler. One object recovered was a 9,500-year-old L-shaped throwing
stick called a ``non-returning boomerang'' used to hunt small game
at a range of 65 yards. People also may have killed animals by
running them into the spring.
</P>
<P>
   On the ledge 85 feet down, Gifford's predecessor found a giant
tortoise with a wooden spear spliting its shell. The spear is
12,000 years old, according to radio-carbon dating. That's
convinced Gifford that people were in Florida then, and the spring
could hold even more evidence. The best artifacts will be sent to
the Historical Museum of Florida in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few days, Gifford and UM's chief diving officer
will dive down to the ledge, where there is a cave 15 feet deep and
6 feet tall. Using a video camera and lights _ it's pitch black at
that depth _ the divers will poke around the ledge and enter the
cave that was last above water at least 12,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   If human remains are found there, they would be the oldest in
the Western Hemisphere. Human bones that are 10,000 years old were
found in Warm Mineral Spring, just 2 miles from Little Salt.
Evidence has also been found in Miami-Dade County that people
reached South Florida 11,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Those discoveries, and others on the Eastern Seaboard, run
counter to the traditional belief that the first Americans came
across the Bering Strait from northeast Asia. Some anthropologists
contend it would have been difficult for those Asians to make their
way to the East Coast 12,000 years ago, when glaciers still covered
much of North America.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative argument, then, is that people also could have
come here from Europe _ crossing from England to Nova Scotia on ice
sheets, then moving down the coast to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   If Gifford and his team are successful in their quest for
12,000-year-old human remains in Little Salt Spring, they would
poke more holes in the traditional theory of human migration. They
would also be the new record-holders in this hemisphere, beating
out by 500 years a skeleton found in Brazil. The oldest North
American so far is a 10,000-year-old skeleton of a woman found in
Buhl, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for the whole shooting match,'' said Gifford, donning
a wet suit and oxygen tank before a dive last week. ``We infer
there were people here, but it would be even better to have the
actual human traces.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he slipped beneath the surface, quickly disappearing into
the still, green water, on another run to another world.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
