<P>
   UM-DIG _ There's a 50-50 chance the oldest human remains ever
discovered in North American will be found in the next two weeks
(June 1-15) in a spring on Florida's Gulf Coast by a University of
Miami marine archaelogist and his graduate students. The 220-foot
deep Little Salt Spring, near Port Charlotte, has already yielded
human remains dating back 7,000 years and evidence of human
activity 12,000 years ago. The 9,000-year-old bones of Kennewick
Man were found in Washington state four years ago. The UM scientist
hopes to find 12,000-year-old remains in Little Salt Spring, which
is devoid of oxygen and so has preserved everything exactly as it
once was, even wooden spears, skin and hair. But now, on the verge
of these great discoveries about Florida's first inhabitants,
encroaching development threatens to damage the spring and what it
holds. (Kiehl, Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
