<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ This city smells terrific. I find
this realization startling. Cities commonly stink, and this city
has its smelly moments. Yet more thLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Dr. Robert
Hatcher is recognized worldwide as an expert in family planning and
population control, but at Emory University in Atlanta his medical
students just call him Captain Condom. (Ezzard, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   LAWRENCE _ ATLANTA _ It was in a New York gallery that I met
Jacob Lawrence, five years ago, just before his powerful Migration
Series opened at the High Museum in Atlanta. He had traveled by
plane from Seattle, as I had from Atlanta. As we sat chatting about
his work, neither of us said anything about the underlying
significance of a couple of plane trips. But, as we talked, two
gray-haired men, I couldn't help thinking of the irony of how our
ordinary travels had become a stark counterpoint to Lawrence's
series, his best-known work and the definitive artistic statement
about the pain and the promise surrounding black people as they
left the Deep South for the industrial North in the 1920s and '30s.
(May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEENS-SUMMERJOBS _ What are the rules for summer jobs for kids
younger than 16? (Thurman, Dayton Daily News). 14. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is Brett Thurman's Legalease column.
</P>
