<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0895 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COX-SYRIA-0612     06-11 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-SYRIA-0612 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A MOURNFUL SYRIA PREPARES FOR RULE BY ASSAD'S SON
 &HT;    500 words &AMP; add
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria A day after his death, Syrians embarked Sunday
on a smooth and speedy transition of power from the late president
Hafez Assad to his 34-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar Assad, who six years ago was studying in London to become
an
</P>
<P>
   eye doctor, was named Sunday as commander of the Syrian
military. It was
</P>
<P>
   the next step in a process that is due to end with his being
named president
</P>
<P>
   in two weeks' time.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, in the streets of this Arab capital, black-clad
residents marched along chanting prayers and slogans while holding
aloft posters of both Assads. They began 40 days of official
mourning for Hafez Assad, highlighted by a state funeral here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the mourners celebrated the rise to power of
his son. ``God, Syria, Bashar Only!'' one group chanted as they
walked in a traffic
</P>
<P>
   circle near the presidential residence.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar Assad is a new face for this country and for the
turbulent region. So far, his fondness for the Internet and singer
Phil Collins are as well known as his plans for a nation that his
father ruled with an iron hand for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   The peace process with Israel, which had faltered before the
longtime leader's sudden death, will likely be on hold for at least
several months while his son seeks to consolidate his position.
</P>
<P>
   ``God willing, he will be like his father,'' 25-year-old Ahlam
Alia said,
</P>
<P>
   with tears in her eyes. ``He was born in the Assad school.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of like-minded marchers spread throughout the
downtown, sometimes banging drums and playing horns. They were
often organized around the youth groups that pervade this rigidly
structured society.
</P>
<P>
   But there also appeared to be a genuine feeling of relief that
Assad's sudden death at age 69 did not immediately to create the
kind of instability that many here had feared.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Assad's rule, Syrian governments changed frequently --
either through bitter political maneuvering or sometimes violent
coups.
</P>
<P>
   Assad governed for a longer time than any ruler here in the
prior 13 centuries. Although he was known to be ailing, his death
nevertheless shocked the country and much of the volatile region.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have problems like this, the whole country acts like
one hand.'','' said Mohammed Khalil, 38, a travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the country prepared to host incoming foreign
dignitaries for
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's funeral. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will
head the U.S. delegation. Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and
Iranian President Mohammed Khatami and French President Jaques
Chirac were also among those expected to attend. Syria effectively
won independence from France in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Khaki-clad units from the Republican Guard, armed with AK-47
assault rifles, cordoned off the hilltop presidential Palace of the
People and the al-Shami Hospital, where the body will remain until
the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   After the funeral, his family will fly with his body to the
small
</P>
<P>
   town of Qardaha, 125 miles to the northwest. There, where he was
born, Assad
</P>
<P>
   will be buried.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bashar Assad remained in seclusion, he accepted
condolences by phone from President Clinton and other world
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A flurry of political activity continued to pave the way for
Bashar Assad's rise to power as the leading Baath Party has
nominated him for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   That nomination is set to be approved when the rubber-stamp
parliament meets June 25. It will be the culmination of an unlikely
rise for a young man who once shied from power.
</P>
<P>
   Assad had spent more than a decade grooming his first son Basil
for the presidency. But Basil Assad died in a car accident on his
way to the Damascus airport in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that Bashar, the second son and third of five Assad
children,
</P>
<P>
   returned from his ophthalmology training abroad.
</P>
<P>
   He is a fluent English speaker in an Arabic country that remains
deeply suspicious of the West. Some people who know him wonder if
he is too gentle to keep the job.
</P>
<P>
   His father crushed descent with brutality and arrests.
</P>
<P>
   After his brother's death, Bashar began a crash course in Syrian
leadership with training as an army officer. Without any formal
government title, he began speaking out for reform of Syria's
stagnant economy while leading a battle against official
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   That fight gained him credibility while silencing potential
rivals. One former prime minister committed suicide under the cloud
of a scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar Assad's most important post was as Syria's point man in
neighboring Lebanon, where this nation keeps more than 30,000
troops. That
</P>
<P>
   position lets him dole out the patronage to Syrian businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kaplow's e-mail address is larryk(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0896 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INTERNATIONAL-COURT-U     06-11 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNATIONAL-COURT-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS SUPPORT GROWS FOR WORLD CRIMINAL COURT, U.S. PUSHES FOR
CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United States, isolated among the nations
of the world, is going into a crucial conference Monday on the
soon-to-be-established International Criminal Court still asking
for changes its charter.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is trying to protect American soldiers and
officials from falling under the court's jurisdiction. But all
members of the European Union and other members of NATO support the
court and have told the United States that there should be no
attempt to reopen debate on how it will work.
</P>
<P>
   Unless some compromise can be found, legal experts say, a major
step in international law will be taken without United States
participation, even though Americans have been at the forefront of
demanding trials for war criminals like Pol Pot and Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has been unable to win support for
the court from the Pentagon and Sen. Jesse Helms, the North
Carolina Republican who is chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee. He has declared that the court treaty would be dead on
arrival if submitted to his panel. So American officials
acknowledge that they are now fighting a rearguard action to try to
exempt countries that do not join from having to face prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The court, which was created by a treaty signed in Rome in July
1998 as a permanent body to try war criminals, may come into
existence by 2002, legal experts say. Its jurisdiction will include
genocide, war crimes and crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   In Rome, 120 nations voted for the court. The United States was
one of seven countries that did not, among them China and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, more than 95 nations have signed the
statute establishing the court and 12 have ratified it, with 60
ratifications needed for the court to begin functioning.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, France became the first permanent member of the
Security Council to ratify the statute. Experts expect the French
example will be followed by a stream of European and other nations.
``France hopes that the required number of ratifications will soon
be reached,'' said a statement from the French government.
</P>
<P>
   William Pace, convenor of the Coalition for an International
Criminal Court, an umbrella group for more than 1,000 human rights
groups and independent legal organizations, called the French
action ``a clear signal to the United States that major nations and
allies are continuing to progress toward completing the
ratification, and they are not willing to reopen the treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Pace called the renewed American effort to change the rules an
``ill-timed and misguided effort.'' Exempting citizens of countries
who have not ratified the treaty, he added, ``would drastically
undermine the effectiveness of the International Criminal Court and
would provide an opening not only for the United States to protect
its officials and soldiers but also for the so-called rogue
countries the court should have as it primary focus. The Pol Pots,
the Saddam Husseins, the Hitlers will not ratify the treaty
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Dicker, counsel for Human Rights Watch, said that legal
experts who support the court are puzzled at the strength of the
opposition to the court, since it gives countries whose citizens
are charged with international crimes the right to try them in
their own courts, as the United States has frequently done through
courts martial when American soldiers are involved in criminal
activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why they seem to be driving this thing over the edge to get
something they don't need is an intriguing question,'' Dicker said
in an interview. ``The treaty has more than enough assurances to
meet their concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Dec. 31, countries can sign the International Criminal
Court treaty and ratify later. After that date, a nation will have
to ratify before being able to join. In a recent interview here,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright indicated that there was no
chance that the United States would sign this year unless the court
statute is changed. The issue is likely to be handed over to the
next administration.
</P>
<P>
   European and other diplomats here say that most nations would
like to find a way to include the United States because the court
would be considerably weakened and undervalued without American
involvement. But the conference ends on June 30 and diplomats are
doubtful that there is enough time, or any flexibility in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the court object to what they say is the legal
authority it would have without an acceptable constitutional base.
John Bolton, a former assistant secretary of state for
international organizations in the Bush administration, calls the
establishment of the court ``a stealth approach to eroding our
constitutionalism'' _ for all branches of American government.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it is for this reason,'' Bolton wrote in The National
Interest last year, ``that whether strong or weak in its actual
operations, the ICC has unacceptable consequences for the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This court is going to happen,'' John L. Washburn, co-chairman
of the independent Washington Working Group on the International
Criminal Court, wrote last month in an Internet column for the
Carnegie Council on Ethics and International Affairs in New York.
``In fact, it is expected to come into being as early as 2002.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. demand tries to reverse a great moral achievement in
international law,'' Washburn wrote. ``The 1945 Nuremberg tribunal
established forever the personal responsibility and accountability
of those who are guilty of the worst of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Power, position and rank cannot absolve them; nor can their
governments. After almost 50 years of lip service and neglect, the
temporary tribunals for Yugoslavia and Rwanda began to enforce this
personal responsibility in real trials that sent real criminals to
real prisons. The ICC will make permanent this enforcement and the
moral commitment it represents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 1807EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0067 </DOCNO>
