<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LUCAS-PARODY-MEDIA-NY     06-11 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCAS-PARODY-MEDIA-NY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET PREMIERE OF 9 MINUTE PARODY LEADS TO VIDEO SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ All Joe Nussbaum wanted was to have his foot in
the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we made this short film last year, me and some old
college friends, trying to get noticed by development executives
and studio executives,'' said Nussbaum, a 27-year-old director.
``We made it as a calling-card film, which hopefully would open the
door for major projects for us. Which it did. Which is great.''
</P>
<P>
   The nine-minute film that Nussbaum directed is ``George Lucas in
Love.'' It is a parody of the Oscar-winning ``Shakespeare in
Love,'' except that instead of Shakespeare working through his
writer's block to create ``Romeo and Juliet,'' it features a young
actor playing the lovesick, college-age George Lucas surrounded by
people recognizable as prototypes for the characters in Lucas'
``Star Wars'' series. As did Nussbaum, Lucas attended the
University of Southern California's film program. So didNussbaum's
co-writer on the film, Daniel Shere.
</P>
<P>
   The film rapidly became an underground hit last summer in
Hollywood, where private videotapes of it were eagerly passed
around, resulting in a burst of national publicity and the
beginnings of a directing career for Nussbaum. But it did not end
there. In October, the movie became the debut attraction on a
streaming-video Web site called Mediatrip.com. In April, it was
released as a video, which is being sold exclusively through
Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   On April 21, the film's first day of release, it immediately
shot to No. 1 on the Amazon sales charts and has been in the top 10
almost every day since. On many of those days, it has even outsold
the heavily promoted video release of Lucas' own ``Star Wars:
Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace.'' Even as recently as late last
week, ``George Lucas in Love'' ($7.99) was No. 3 on the Amazon
sales chart, and ``Episode 1'' ($16.95) was a distant No. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's strange, huh?'' said Austin Harrison, chief executive
of Mediatrip. ``It's No. 3. That just cracks me up.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been much speculation in Hollywood about how the
Internet might prove to be a solid showcase and lucrative marketing
tool for films, like shorts, that never get real theatrical runs.
But ``George Lucas in Love'' is one of the first films actually to
open on the Internet and then have success as a video release.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Levy, the producer and another of Nussbaum's college
friends, said the $25,000 it cost to make the film came out of the
pockets of the director, the producer, the composer, the writers
and others involved in the project. All the money they made selling
the Internet rights to Mediatrip _ about $1,500 _ was plowed back
into the film, Levy said, producing film prints that could be shown
at film festivals. Only now, with the video sales, do the
filmmakers stand to make some money.
</P>
<P>
   Inadvertently, Levy said, the filmmakers seem to have tapped
into the audience of the ``Star Wars'' films and science-fiction
fans, exactly the sort of people who are most likely to watch short
films on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our only intention back when we made it last year was to do
something that would get agents and producers to put the tape into
their VCRs instead of throwing it away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the video is now available only through Amazon,
Harrison said plans are being made to expand distribution to video
stores and other outlets. International rights and sales to
airlines and others are also being discussed. And by the end of the
year, there will be a ``George Lucas in Love'' videodisc that will
include the nine-minute short, profiles of the filmmakers and some
extra features that Harrison was reluctant to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas has been a good sport about it all, praising the film and
even requesting a copy of the poster promoting the movie, which was
promptly sent to him.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Nussbaum said, no thought was given to posting the
film on the Internet. But then, several of the new,
entertainment-oriented dot-coms began calling and making offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like, wow, we certainly didn't make this for the
Internet, but we'd be fools not to put it on the Internet,''
Nussbaum said. ``What is it they say? If three people tell you
you're drunk, you'd better sit down? Well, if four Internet sites
tell you they want your movie, you'd better put it on the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   When the numbers of people watching the movie on Mediatrip grew
into the hundreds of thousands, with active chat rooms about the
film and more than 600 posted reviews, it seemed only natural to
try to release it on videotape, Harrison said. ``People would
literally post on the bulletin board, `When is the video coming
out?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the film had its first burst of publicity last
summer, Nussbaum signed a couple of development deals for films
that were never made.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ended up going the way of many Hollywood movies,'' he
said. ``They dissolved.'' He is not complaining, though. He has
been working regularly, making television commercials and is in the
final stages of negotiating another studio deal for his
feature-film debut. Since the movie came out, meanwhile, Levy has
taken a job creating digital entertainment for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would always say to each other, `How long is our window?'''
Nussbaum said. `` `How long can you be the buzz? How long can you
be the hot thing?' We figured it would be quite short. Of any
industry in the world, Hollywood has been built on flashes in the
pan. We fully expected that if we did well, it would have to be
quick, we'd have to jump on it. But here it is, what, a year later?
And it's still going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
