u i BC-SYRIA-ISRAEL-870-NYT &LR;      06-11 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-ISRAEL-870-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSAD'S DEATH LEAVES ISRAEL CALM BUT UNCERTAIN  
</HEADLINE>
    By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli leaders proclaimed on Sunday that the death
of President Hafez Assad of Syria had ushered in a new era or at
least ushered out an old one in the Middle East. But no one could
predict what that portended beyond a potentially problematic
transition period.
</P>
<P>
   There was no mourning, no celebration of the death and no
re-assessment here of an Arab leader familiar to generations of
Israelis as a sworn enemy of their state, yet one who inspired
sometimes ambivalent feelings as a cunning leader and a worthy
adversary, too.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most agreed with Nahum Barnea, the dean of newspaper
columnists, who wrote Sunday morning: ``We Israelis have no reason
to shed any tears over the death of Hafez Assad. It's a waste of
water.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Israelis expressed the hope that positive change would
prove inevitable. ``Assad's successor is the times and not any one
man,'' said Shimon Peres, Israel's minister for regional affairs.
``Because if his successor doesn't adapt himself to the times,
Syria will remain a very poor and isolated country in a very
difficult situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Some worried aloud that Syria would degenerate into chaos, which
could destabilize Lebanon, and spread violence into Israel. But
more said wishfully that Assad's death could help Syria shed its
insularity, open up to the West and perhaps even lose what is
perceived here as its intransigence in pursuing peace.
</P>
<P>
   They also noted hopefully that Assad's designated successor, his
34-year-old son Bashar, was educated in England, that he heads
Syria's computer society, and that he is not bound by the same
personal entanglements in history. Bashar Assad was just two years
old in 1967, when Syria, with his father as defense minister, lost
the Golan Heights to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the widespread calm here, the Tel Aviv stock
exchange, usually a good barometer of geopolitical anxiety,
registered barely a flutter. And the Israeli military, after a
24-hour alert, reported quiet on Israel's northern borders and said
that no new forces would be deployed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking on the other side, and everything looks as
usual,'' the senior official said. ``Our military estimation is
that the regime will focus internally, on stabilizing itself. We
don't think that the death of Assad will stimulate the area or
light any fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Assad's death almost certainly puts the prospects of regional
peace talks on the back burner until Bashar Assad, if he is indeed
made the new leader, wins over the political and military
establishment, calms ethnic tensions and grows into his authority.
</P>
<P>
   For all his hostility, the Syrian leader did preserve peace on
the border with the Golan Heights for most of his rule. But despite
the fact that Assad had made what he considered a ``strategic
choice'' to pursue peace, he was the oldest hardline skeptic in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   And many here said, again hopefully, that the absence of his
ideological dominance in the Arab world could shift the tenor of
debate. It could also, they added, make it easier for Yasser
Arafat, the Palestinian leader, to make a final deal with Israel
without being accused of selling out. Teams of Palestinian and
Israeli negotiators are to resume talks in the United States this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assad personally was a cloud hanging over the possibility of
reaching a reasonable arrangement in the region,'' said Shlomo Ben
Ami, Israel's security minister and senior peace negotiator with
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Several right-wing leaders used the occasion to promote their
belief that there are grave risks in pursuing peace with aging
leaders in an unstable region. Zalman Shoval, a former ambassador
to the United States and now the spokesman for the rightist Likud
Party, wrote Sunday that Assad's death ``underlines just how
unreasonable was Israel's head-long rush into negotiations'' with
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must realize that what goes for Syria goes for the
Palestinians as well,'' Shoval wrote in the Jerusalem Post. ``In
the Arab Middle East, nothing is permanent and everything is
volatile.''
</P>
<P>
   In his Cabinet meeting Sunday, Barak criticized this line of
thinking, noting that peace lasted with other Arab countries, like
Egypt, even after the death of the peacemaker. He also agreed with
diplomatic analysts who noted Sunday that it was a good thing that
Israel had withdrawn its troops from Lebanon before Assad died.
Pulling out now _ the original withdrawal date was July 7 _ would
have been complicated by the period of uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few decades, Assad's face, on banners, hovered over
Damascus. Here, less explicitly, it had become part of the scenery,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life without Hafez, after all these years, is an unknown, and
we will all have to go through a weaning period,'' Chemi Shalev
wrote Sunday in the Maariv newspaper. ``But along with the worry
there is also room for hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, Assad was a bitter enemy who cast a giant shadow
over the entire Middle East. This morning, now that he's gone, we
can see the sun once more, even if it is blinding at present.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
