<HEADER>
A0905 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     06-11 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AN EMPTY OPEN WITHOUT PAYNE STEWART 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first time the son filled out an entry form for the U.S.
Open, the father, who had played in the 1955 Open, had some words
of advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the national championship,'' the father said. ``When
you send your entry in, you put your real name on the entry form,
your full name.''
</P>
<P>
   For nearly two decades the son did just that, writing ``William
Payne Stewart.'' But for the 100th U.S. Open, which begins Thursday
at Pebble Beach, that name was not on an entry form. The golfer who
won last year's Open with a dramatic 15-foot par putt at Pinehurst
No. 2, died Oct. 25 on a ghostly Learjet that eventually plunged
into a South Dakota field.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a half-century, there will be no defending
champion in the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1949, when Ben Hogan was recuperating from severe
injuries suffered when his Cadillac was crushed by a Greyhound bus
on a Texas highway, has the reigning Open champion not teed off in
defense of the title. And never had the reigning champion died
before the next Open.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, it will be an empty Open without Stewart, who
also won the 1991 Open at Hazeltine National outside Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the defending champion tees off with the British
Open champion and the U.S. Amateur champion in the first two rounds
before the 36-hole cut. Stewart's slot will be filled by Jack
Nicklaus, a four-time Open champion, in a threesome with Scotland's
Paul Lawrie and the Texas amateur David Gossett.
</P>
<P>
   In Stewart's honor, the U.S. Golf Association, which governs all
the national championships, has planned a sunrise service at 7 a.m.
Wednesday near Pebble Beach's 18th tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``In accordance with Tracey's wishes,'' said David Fay, the USGA
executive director, referring to Stewart's widow, ``the service
will be a tribute to Payne, not a memorial.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracey Stewart and their two children, Chelsea and Aaron, also
will attend a Tuesday evening celebration at this 100th U.S. Open
of 24 living Open champions.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart almost won two other Opens, finishing second to Lee
Janzen both in 1993 at Baltusrol and 1998 at Olympic, but his
defining moment occurred at Pinehurst.
</P>
<P>
   In her memoir, ``Payne Stewart: The Authorized Biography
(Broadman and Holman, $24.99), Tracey Stewart, an Australian who
met her husband in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, when he was playing on
the Asian Tour, wrote of a suggestion she made after Saturday's
round. He had shot a spotty 72, mostly because of poor putting. As
she watched, she noticed that when he putted, he made the mistake
of moving his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to keep your head down,'' she told him later.
``You're trying to watch the ball go in rather than keeping your
head down.''
</P>
<P>
   In the dusk at Pinehurst that Saturday night, Stewart spent 45
minutes on the putting green with one thought: not moving his head.
</P>
<P>
   In his duel with Phil Mickelson in Sunday's final round, Stewart
made an undulating 25-foot putt at the 16th hole to tie for the
lead, then took the lead with a 3-foot birdie putt at the short
17th. Minutes later, he sank the winning 15-footer on the 18th
green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it,'' he told Tracey as they hugged. ``I kept my head
down. All day, I did it. I kept my head down.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, other Open champions have thrown the winning
golf ball to the gallery around the 18th green, but after Stewart's
ball clunked into the cup on that 15-foot putt, he grabbed it,
kissed it and slipped it into his pocket. This ball was a keeper.
</P>
<P>
   Other Open champions have eventually donated one of their
Open-winning clubs for display in Golf House, the USGA headquarters
in Far Hills, N.J., as Ben Hogan did with the 1-iron he used at
Merion in his comeback victory in the 1950 Open.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart died too quickly for that, but maybe the putter that
sank the 15-footer, the longest putt to win the Open, will be there
someday.
</P>
<P>
   Hauntingly, before that final round Stewart watched an NBC
television segment on him and his father, Bill Stewart, the
Missouri amateur who shot 83-88 in that 1955 Open at Olympic in San
Francisco, the father who advised the son to put his real name, his
full name, on his Open entry form. The son who would win the Open
twice. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 1822EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
