<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0907 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ETUDES-DANCE-REVIEW-N     06-11 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETUDES-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IN BALLET LAND, AS TOLD BY A CHOREOGRAPHER (RATHER THAN
HOLLYWOOD) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Harald Lander's ``Etudes'' ought to be required
viewing for anyone who believes that the current film ``Center
Stage'' presents an accurate picture of a life in ballet.
</P>
<P>
   The piece, performed by American Ballet Theater last Wednesday
afternoon and evening at the Metropolitan Opera House, is a long
journey through academic ballet training. Spectacular, cornball and
dull in turn, the ballet progresses from the most basic steps
performed by the smallest of small fry to demanding sequences
performed by those who have mastered not just the steps but also
the physical and spiritual discipline the art demands.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's lead cast _ Irina Dvorovenko, Jose Manuel Carreno
and Vladimir Malakhov _ stood out on the whole for the glitter of
its performing. In the afternoon the emphasis was more on
expansiveness and simplicity in a performance headed by Amanda
McKerrow, Marcelo Gomes and Maxim Belotserkovsky. Dvorovenko's
dancing had a weight that made it regal. McKerrow was delicately
lyrical. Lander did not allow for much pyrotechnical ornamentation,
and both Carreno and Malakhov looked uncharacteristically subdued.
The greatest beauty of their dancing was their contrasting
qualities. If Carreno could be said to be earth, Malakhov is air.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon Gomes stood out for his big, unforced approach
to classical technique. Like Dvorovenko, Belotserkovsky has a more
forceful Russian-style attack, mixed here, characteristically, with
a winning clarity of line and shape. The score, composed by
Knudaage Riisager and based on Czerny etudes, was conducted at both
performances by David Lamarche.
</P>
<P>
   The matinee performance also included Malakhov's role debut in
Martha Graham's ``Diversion of Angels,'' dancing with Sandra Brown
as half of the Couple in Red. The purest of classicists, Malakhov
has obviously paid close and devoted attention to the distinctive
shapes and propulsive quality of the Graham modern-dance technique.
</P>
<P>
   His is somewhat airy Graham dancing, but that quality of
devotion keeps him sufficiently tethered to the earth. Isaac
Stappas, who danced the Fourth Man, looked as if he had been born
dancing Graham, in a fine lead cast completed by Stella Abrera,
Gomes, Erica Cornejo and Herman Cornejo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 1829EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0908 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BEE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-11 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEE SEASON': FICTIONAL JEWISH FAMILY'S TROUBLES WITTILY
CHRONICLED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While it may be true, as Tolstoy famously wrote, that every
unhappy family is unhappy in its own way, the unhappiness of the
Naumanns in Myla Goldberg's unusual first novel, ``Bee Season,''
seems so particularly original and intriguing that you almost want
the author to go on denying the family members the fulfillment they
so ardently seek.
</P>
<P>
   Saul Naumann, the father, is a cantor whose feelings of love for
his wife, Miriam, have ebbed ``into gratitude.'' His passion is to
retire to his study and read the great Jewish mystics, although he
knows that he lacks whatever it takes to achieve true communion
with God.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam, a partner in a law firm, spends her hours at home
cleaning and organizing, ``a hummingbird in human form, her wings
too fast to be seen without a stop-motion camera.'' Orphaned while
in college by a car accident, she seeks to heal herself by
occasionally stealing from stores what she thinks of as the missing
pieces of her world.
</P>
<P>
   The Naumanns' oldest child, Aaron, 16, dreams of becoming a
rabbi. Inside his father's synagogue ``he is junior class
president, football captain and star of the school musical.'' But
outside he has few friends and is terrorized by bullies. His
11-year-old sister, Eliza, can't forgive him for failing to resist
during a fight she secretly witnessed. She also suffers from
feeling less smart than Aaron is, from failing to be picked as he
was for her school's talented and gifted program.
</P>
<P>
   Everything changes when Eliza exercises her talent for spelling.
To everyone's surprise, she wins her class, school and district
spelling bees and qualifies for the nationals, to be held in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Her delighted father pitches in to help her study. He begins by
drilling her with Webster's Third International Dictionary. But he
sees in her the potential to be what he cannot be, namely a
practitioner of the teachings of Abraham Abulafia, a 13th-century
cabalist who taught that the key to transcendence is language
itself.
</P>
<P>
   As Saul tells Eliza: ``Abulafia believed that, by concentrating
on letters, the mind could loose itself from its shackles to
commune with a presence greater than itself, what Abraham Abulafia
called shefa, the influx. He believed that barriers separated
personal existence from the larger stream of life, the Divine
Intellect.'' Eliza, Saul is convinced, can achieve shefa, if
properly trained.
</P>
<P>
   While Eliza is thrilled by her father's attention, Aaron suffers
from the loss of it and begins to question his own devotion to
Judaism. Concluding that ``he's bought Judaism without consulting
the side of the box'' it came in, he begins to look at other
religions and eventually falls in with a Hare Krishna group.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Miriam steps up her quest for what she calls
Perfectimundo, feeling that something is ``growing inside her,
waiting for the right moment to make itself known.''
</P>
<P>
   Eliza, sensitive to these changes in the family dynamic, feels
guilty for her part in causing them.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, who has published short stories in various magazines,
does a sensitive and witty job of plotting the back-and-forth
lurches of these seekers after the divine. Aaron, at breakfast on
his first overnight at his Hare Krishna temple, ``longs for cereal
and not prasadam, has his first pang of homesickness at the thought
of Frosted Flakes with sliced banana.'' Miriam longs to match the
Perfectimundo implied by a bubble-gum pink Spalding rubber ball.
</P>
<P>
   As for Eliza, ``her new powers of concentration astound'' her
father. ``He laughs to recall a time when she struggled to ignore
the sounds of television. He has sneaked up behind her during her
chanting and dropped all three volumes of Webster's Universal. She
hasn't moved, as far as he can tell not even hearing its unabridged
collision with the hard floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everything works in ``Bee Season.'' As eloquently as Eliza's
experience is described, there seems something a little forced
about equating Abulafia's prescription of language with the
chanting of children spelling words like propagate and manicotti
and gherkin.
</P>
<P>
   Faintly off-putting, too, is Goldberg's adherence to the new
form of English in which ``like'' substitutes for ``as if,''
``different than'' for ``different from,'' ``lay'' for ``lie,''
``enormity'' for ``enormousness,'' ``disinterest'' for
``uninterest,'' ``access'' for ``get'' and ``a moment in time'' for
``a moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she keeps her story alive with witty modulations of her
characters' feelings. As Eliza approaches the ecstasy of
experiencing God, she also the sees practical advantages in her
encounter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shefa will erase years of average report cards, undo seasons
of unfulfilled expectations, and legitimize Eliza's new place by
her father's side. Shefa will neutralize the guilt she feels when
she sits opposite Aaron at the dinner table. Shefa is Eliza's
national bee backup plan. ... With God on her side, the national
trophy is as good as in her hands.''
</P>
<P>
   As mundane and unmystical as these longings of Eliza's may be,
you never stop caring about whether she will fulfill them.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BEE SEASON'
</P>
<P>
   By Myla Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   275 pages. Doubleday. $22.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
