<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUERTEN STAYS CALM THROUGH FRUSTRATIONS AND WINS THE FRENCH OPEN
TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Roughly 40 minutes had gone by since Gustavo Kuerten had
begun walking merrily toward the net to celebrate his second French
Open title Sunday, roughly 40 minutes since a cross-court backhand
struck by Magnus Norman had been called out only to be overruled by
the chair umpire, Francois Pareau, to Kuerten's stupefaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like I was watching white and he was watching black,''
Kuerten said.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 40 minutes, and the fifth-seeded Brazilian was still on
Center Court, still in the fourth set chasing down Norman's heavy
forehands and trying his best to forget all the match points that
had gone by. He had squandered three in the 10th game; four more in
a marathon 12th game and three more in the ensuing tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   Ten match points lost in all; 10 opportunities to raise his
skinny arms overhead and hug his coach and confidante, Larri
Passos. There was no precedent for this kind of frustration in a
Grand Slam final. Lesser men would have been an emotional wreck,
screaming at the shifting sky and heaping insults on the umpire.
But Kuerten, a lesser man once, stayed calm. At 6-6 in the
tiebreaker, he fired a first serve at Norman's body that the Swede
could not quite handle to earn his 11th match point.
</P>
<P>
   By now, the crowd was shellshocked: worn out, like the players,
from anticipation and lack of resolution. There was not much buzz
as Norman prepared to serve, little emotion from Kuerten as he
stood 12 feet behind the baseline. But when the next rally ended
with Norman hitting a forehand wide, this 3-hour-44-minute match _
as much an ordeal as it was a spectacle _ was over. Kuerten, no
longer a one-Slam wonder, was the winner, 6-2, 6-3, 2-6, 7-6 (6).
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course you start to think, especially because the first
match point I thought the ball was out, so for me it was over,''
said Kuerten, who was seeded fifth. ``Every time I missed another
chance, I was still thinking about that. It was really strange: the
points keep passing and you don't realize if it's going to be OK or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as in 1997, it would turn out beautifully for the man the
Brazilians call Guga. Just as in 1997, he won with his
eightysomething grandmother Olga Schlosser in the stands after she
flew in from Brazil and with his nation's green and yellow flag
fluttering in the stands and a band waiting in the wings. Just as
in 1997, he won by generating remarkable pace and depth from the
baseline and demonstrating slightly surreal endurance.
</P>
<P>
   But this title, like any second Grand Slam title, was a
different psychological challenge. In 1997, Kuerten was ranked
66th, had a room in a two-star hotel and was only a household name
in his beachside Brazilian hometown of Florianopolis. A year later,
he was upset early in singles and ended up being disqualified from
the doubles after throwing his racquet in frustration and narrowly
missing the chair umpire's head. A tearful Kuerten later issued a
written apology.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, there would be no such melodrama, and he was on
the very short list of favorites from the beginning. He has
improved his serve considerably since 1997 and was undisputably the
most consistent clay-court player over the last two seasons. Last
month, he lost to Norman in the final in Rome and then beat him en
route to winning the title in Hamburg a week later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this shows that I'm really one of the top players _ a
guy who will stay around,'' Kuerten said in his pleasantly
fractured English. ``People maybe thought I'd win one time and be
finished. So I think right now with my name again here in the
history, I think I put myself as one of the players who can stay
for a long time in the tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuerten has also reached the quarterfinals at the United States
Open and, more surprisingly because of his grip changes and long
backswings, Wimbledon. He also reached the final in Key Biscayne
earlier this year, losing in a tight match to Pete Sampras. But
clay is where he remains the most dangeorus.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Kuerten won three five-set matches on his way to the
trophy. This time, despite a suspect back that bothered him earlier
in the claycourts season, he stared down defeat against Yevgeny
Kafelnikov in the quarterfinals and Juan Carlos Ferrero in the
semifinals, rallying from two-set-to-one deficits in both
instances. Against Kafelnikov he was down 2-4, 15-40 in the fourth
set, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kafelnikov was my worst nightmare, I can say,'' Kuerten said.
``I was not feeling my game. He was controlling the match. Somehow
things changed.''
</P>
<P>
   They would change on Sunday, as well, and this time Kuerten
would be the one whose lead would start to erode. For two sets,
Norman played far less than his best and occasionally threw his
racquet, making this final between the two top players in the
yearlong points race anticlimactic. With shot after shot striking
the net, Norman kept twisting away and bellowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know I wanted it so much,'' said Norman, the Swede who was
playing in his first Grand Slam final. ``I was standing on my back
foot when I played the forehand today. The other matches I've been
going through the ball. Today I was playing too defensive in the
beginning. I didn't feel good out there. I was not nervous. Things
just didn't go my way.''
</P>
<P>
   That would change in the third set and early in the fourth, when
Norman broke Kuerten in the first game and took a 2-0 lead. But
Guga would soon even the score and they would trade breaks and
groundstrokes with great intensity, if not always great efficiency,
until the end.
</P>
<P>
   It was hardly a great match, but the way it finished (and did
not finish) was unquestionably great theater. With Norman serving
at 4-5 in the final set, he soon fell behind by 15-40. On the
second match point, after Pareau had overruled on the first,
Kuerten knocked a forehand long, with Norman shouting ``Come on''
before it even landed.
</P>
<P>
   The Swede would save another match point that game and then
dodge four more on his next service game, which would stretch to
nine deuces and last for 21 minutes. But after making up a 3-6
deficit in the tiebreaker, Norman's great escape finally came to an
end along with his lead in the points race. Kuerten is the new
number one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the feeling I could win all the time until the last
point, until I saw the forehand go out,'' Norman said. ``I still
feel like if I could play the match again.''
</P>
<P>
   His voice trailed off and as it did, a group of Brazilian fans
kept thumping drums in the distance as they danced a victory lap
around the stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
