<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FINALLY, THE DEVILS `SKATE THE CUP' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Along with enthusiasm for their Stars and friendly
manners toward visitors, the hockey fans of Texas show a
sophistication about the sport that belies their recent arrival in
the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Devils won the Stanley Cup late Saturday night with
a 2-1 victory in the second overtime, a group of men and women in
Stars jerseys gathered near the glass as the Devils players posed
for pictures with the trophy for about a half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skate the cup!'' they chanted, some of them with cameras in
their hands. ``Skate the cup!'' It is a modern tradition for teams
to take the silver prize in a long, slow procession, holding it
high, passing it from hands to hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, clinching on the road before subdued applause, had
simply forgotten. Finally, with about 2,000 people left in Reunion
arena, somebody remembered to start the parade and the Devils went
one, tired lap to the respectful applause of their gracious hosts.
</P>
<P>
   You could excuse their temporary amnesia regarding protocol.
Jason Arnott's goal, at 8 minutes 20 seconds of the second extra
session, had ended a grueling six-game series that seemed longer.
Game 5, a 1-0 Dallas victory, had ended in the third overtime on
Friday morning. So the two teams had played more than nine full
periods _ more than three full regulation games _ in a span of
about 52 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott, who beat Eddie Belfour from close range after a setup
from Patrik Elias Saturday night, had left Game 4 after being
struck by the stick-clenching gloves of Dallas defenseman Derian
Hatcher. ``I had headaches,'' Arnott said. ``I was a little hazy,
but there wasn't anything that was going to stop me. I was going to
go through a brick wall if I had to play. Nothing was going to keep
me out.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnott and Elias had extra motivation Saturday because their
linemate, Petr Sykora, finished the game in a local hospital bed.
He had left the ice on a stretcher in the first period after
Hatcher flattened him with a hard check to the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hearts went out to him,'' Arnott said of Sykora. ``To see
him get carried off like that was tough. Especially for Patty. They
are so close. Patty and I looked at each other and said, `We've got
to do this for our boy.' That goal was for him.''
</P>
<P>
   It also helped people forget about Arnott's cross-checking
penalty, late in the first overtime, that gave Dallas a power play
that extended into the second overtime. ``I didn't want my
teammates to jump on me,'' Arnott said. ``I kind of said it was a
bad penalty and kill it off for me, boys, and we'll see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened was the second tournament championship for the
franchise in six seasons and the end of an era. The Dallas fans,
who had celebrated the championship last season, stood near the
glass and watched the sincere and sentimental celebration of the
Devils players. Claude Lemieux, the veteran, had tears as he hugged
Scott Gomez, the rookie. Elias lay on the ice, near the spot of
Sykora's injury, with Sykora's jersey draped over his chest, as he
talked on a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   The four Russian players _ Vladimir Malakhov, Sergei Nemchinov,
Alexander Mogilny and Sergei Brylin _ gathered around the cup and
posed for a photographer. Scott Stevens, the captain, had two
trophies to hoist and trouble doing it. He also won the Conn Smythe
trophy as most valuable player in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's heavy,'' he said of the cup, ``and I've got a bad
shoulder. So it was tough to lift it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Daneyko, the other veteran defenseman, stood in the corridor
outside the locker room for more than an hour, wearing his full
uniform, with pads and skates. He is 36 and the senior Devil,
having joined the team in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Daneyko wants to play next season but, with an expansion draft
later this month and inevitable churn of a roster, there is no
guarantee he will ever again wear the Devils uniform. He used words
like ``cherish'' and ``grateful'' and ``heart'' when telling of
what this meant to him.
</P>
<P>
   Along with players, much else might change for the Devils. John
McMullen, the owner, is selling the team to the Yankees-Nets
combine. Although General Manager Lou Lamoriello and Coach Larry
Robinson will be asked to return, it is not a sure thing that they
will be back. As hockey people often do in times like these,
Robinson spoke of family, especially of his first grandson, born
during the playoffs. Now, he finally gets a chance to see the baby.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to other subjects, he spoke of the incredible tension of
the final two games. ``I think hockey can be really, really proud
of the last two games,'' Robinson said. ``I don't think you are
ever going to see two buildings that are more tense, with people
sitting on the edge of their seats.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson reflected on his coaching career, which saw him leave
Los Angeles last summer after four undistinguished seasons as a
head coach. He returned to New Jersey as an assistant to Robbie
Ftorek and replaced the fired Ftorek with eight games remaining in
the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, could Robinson have imagined this scene?
</P>
<P>
   ``Dream on,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
