<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENETICALLY ALTERED FOOD CAN'T COMPETE WITH GENETICALLY ALTERED
TEENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't worry a lot about genetically altered foods and I'll
tell you why.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're talking about radishes or rainbow trout, I don't
eat anything that is still alive. And if the genes have already
expired by the time you serve them for dinner, it's a dead issue.
</P>
<P>
   It's the live genes you have to be concerned about. And that
provokes another question.
</P>
<P>
   Who robbed the human gene bank of common sense? Well, ``human''
may be the wrong word because I'm really referring to teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody or some thing has drastically altered teenage genes
since I used up my quota.
</P>
<P>
   In those days we were genetically engineered to keep our pants
on in public. If the pants were too long, our mothers shortened
them. If our Levi's had holes in the knees, our mothers patched
them.
</P>
<P>
   These days, teenage boys shove their trousers down below their
hip pads. Their pants cuffs scrape along the sidewalk, their bony
knees project from designer holes in the legs and as a consequence
young Americans are at a distinct disadvantage if they are trying
to run in the Olympics or flee from muggers.
</P>
<P>
   Human genes did not equip us with Foster Grants in place of
eyeballs. So if we were playing in a sandlot baseball game we wore
baseball caps, and we pulled the bills down low so we wouldn't be
blinded by the sun.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence of the aforementioned gene alteration,
teenagers today think they've got eyes in their rear ends. They
wear their baseball caps reversed. When the sun is glaring they
can't see where they're going. In fact they are walking backward
through life. And they shouldn't be surprised if fate drills them
with a fastball in the middle of the back.
</P>
<P>
   Sagging pants are a humiliation. Backward baseball caps are an
inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a far greater menace to the future of mankind.
</P>
<P>
   Although their numbers are still low, more and more teenagers
are choosing to have their lips and tongues pierced with sharp
metal objects.
</P>
<P>
   How are you going to put away a meal of spare ribs and
corn-on-the-cob with a pin in your tongue or a hoop through the
lips?
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, these genetically damaged teens are only able to gum
down Gerbers pureed vegetables and must eat beef steak through a
straw.
</P>
<P>
   Their muscles will atrophy, their pants will fall off but they
won't even notice because the sun will be shining in their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that just means there will be more enchiladas or
cheeseburger pie for the rest of us to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Cheeseburger Pie
</P>
<P>
   1 9-inch deep dish frozen pie shell
</P>
<P>
   1 pound lean ground beef
</P>
<P>
   \ cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   { cup sliced fresh mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 small (5-ounce) can evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced jalapeno peppers (optional)
</P>
<P>
   You can make your own pie crust if you wish. That's what our
mothers did. But if your genes have been altered you probably
won't, in which case you should let that frozen crust sit at room
temperature for 10 minutes. Then prick the bottom and sides with a
fork, and bake in a preheated, 400-degree oven for five minutes.
Remove crust and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   In a skillet brown the meat and onion. Pour off any fat. Add to
the pan the salt, pepper, garlic powder, chili powder and if you
want to make things more interesting toss in two teaspoons of
jalapeno peppers, or more if your internal thermometer can handle
it.
</P>
<P>
   When the meat mixture has cooled, spoon it into the crust.
Distribute the mushroom slices over the top. Scatter with the
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Beat together the eggs and milk and pour this sludge over the
pie.
</P>
<P>
   Bake the pie in a 400-degree oven for 20 minutes. Reduce heat to
350 degrees and cook another 20 to 25 minutes. The last 10 minutes
you may want to cover the crust with strips of foil.
</P>
<P>
   Let the pie stand 10 minutes before carving. This will serve
four.
</P>
<P>
   Genealogical Enchiladas
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 can (three ounces) diced green chilies
</P>
<P>
   1 cup white sauce (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   2{ cups cooked chicken, diced
</P>
<P>
   6 large flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups grated jack cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 or 2 avocados, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   Sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Most enchiladas ooze gloop from every corner. These are
genetically engineered to produce a non-gloopy version.
</P>
<P>
   In a skillet saute the onion and garlic in the hot oil until the
onion softens. Stir in the chopped chilies, the white sauce and the
chicken. Stir once or twice.
</P>
<P>
   Lay out the tortillas and divide the chicken filling down the
center of each. Top each tortilla with 2 tablespoons of jack
cheese. Roll the tortillas up and place in a lightly oiled oven
dish, seam side down.
</P>
<P>
   Shove the dish into a 350-degree oven for 25 minutes. Remove,
serve and let each diner top the tortillas as they choose with
avocado slices and sour cream.
</P>
<P>
   White Sauce: Melt 2 tablespoons of butter in a small saucepan.
Stir in 2 tablespoons of flour. Cook for a minute then add a cup of
milk in a slow dribble, stirring. Keep stirring over medium heat
until the sauce thickens. Add a pinch of salt and a sprinkle of
nutmeg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
