<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0920 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AUCTION-ANTITRUST-2TA     06-11 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUCTION-ANTITRUST-2TAKES(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADLINE BEARING DOWN ON PROSECUTORS IN AUCTION HOUSE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RALPH BLUMENTHAL and CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Facing an important deadline next month, Justice
Department prosecutors are redoubling their efforts to prove that
Sotheby's and Christie's, the world's most powerful auction houses,
hatched a scheme to fix the prices they charged buyers and sellers
and that the collusion began as early as 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors are racing to beat a July 18 deadline, set by
the court hearing civil suits in the case, that could expose the
best kept secrets of their long antitrust investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks the prosecutors have made calls to more than a
dozen present and former auction house employees, said potential
witnesses and lawyers, asking them for voluntary interviews and
testimony before a grand jury. They have been striving to back up
claims of collusion as far back as 1991 made late last year by
Christie's former chief executive, Christopher M. Davidge, in
particular over commissions charged to buyers.
</P>
<P>
   While the prosecutors are said to feel they have a good case
that the two houses conspired to fix sellers' commissions in 1995,
evidence of earlier collusion directed at buyers' fees is largely
confined to Davidge's allegations, backed up by documents he has
provided that in some instances are not dated.
</P>
<P>
   What prosecutors are most eager to keep secret, lawyers said, is
what exactly is spelled out in a dozen documents that Davidge, who
abruptly resigned on Christmas Eve, turned over to Christie's
lawyers. The lawyers then gave them to the government in exchange
for a conditional amnesty from prosecution for Christie's, a
tradeoff that sent the lagging federal investigation into high
gear.
</P>
<P>
   On May 12 the government's chief antitrust prosecutor in New
York, John J. Greene, argued in favor of keeping the documents out
of the hands of lawyers suing Sotheby's and Christie's to maintain
the secrecy of its grand jury investigation _ now almost three
years old _ through at least August. But Judge Lewis A. Kaplan of
U.S. District Court in Manhattan, who is hearing a civil class
action lawsuit by auction house customers who claim they were
cheated by collusive practices, voiced impatience with the
government's pace. The following week, he ordered Davidge's
documents to be made available starting on July 18 to the lawyers,
who are suing on behalf of dozens if not hundreds of complainants.
The judge could, however, still modify his order and delay the
document turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the 60 or more law firms handling the plaintiffs' suits
is the firm of David Boies, who is fresh from his victory as the
government's special counsel in the lawsuit to break up Microsoft.
The firm, Boies, Schiller &AMP; Flexner, of Armonk, N.Y., was named
lead counsel by Judge Kaplan on May 26 through an unusual bidding
process he devised. The process was intended to determine which
lawyers would offer plaintiffs the greatest share of a settlement
by holding down legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the criminal penalties, if the Justice Department is
successful in establishing that the price-fixing dates back nine
years, civil awards could cripple both companies, lawyers
representing various parties in the tangled case agreed. One lawyer
suing the auction houses said that the damages could run well into
the hundreds of millions of dollars, which, when tripled under
provisions in such cases, could mean combined losses to Sotheby's
and Christie's of close to $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Several people close to the case, who spoke on condition of
anonymity citing the continuing investigation, said that
prosecutors seem specifically focused on gathering facts regarding
1991 and 1992. Those were the years both companies made the
decision to change the fees they charge buyers from a flat rate of
10 percent of the purchase price to 15 percent of the first $50,000
and 10 percent of the rest. Sotheby's announced the change in
November 1992, and Christie's followed with an identical fee
structure a little over a month later.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they did not collude on setting the fees originally,
they could be in violation of federal antitrust statutes if in
subsequent years they simply discussed maintaining the fee
structure, said an experienced antitrust lawyer. Lawyers and others
close to the case have said that the government has evidence that
Sotheby's and Christie's exchanged lists of important collectors
who were to be exempt from sellers' fees.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People close to the investigation say the Justice Department has
also asked witnesses about whether other topics came up in
conversations between Davidge and Diana D. Brooks, Sotheby's chief
executive, who resigned on Feb. 21. These include whether they
worked out a policy not to poach each other's staffs and whether
they had spoken about how to negotiate with the French government
about opening the Paris auction business to non-French companies.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for queries about these matters are unclear,
although experienced antitrust lawyers said that in some
circumstances ``no poaching'' agreements may have antitrust
implications and that in other antitrust cases conversations about
benign topics, akin to negotiating with the French over auction
laws, have turned to questionable issues that figured heavily in
prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to examining Rolodexes, diaries and telephone logs,
prosecutors have asked auction house employees _ including present
and former art and antiques experts and a former in-house lawyer _
about what they may know of any discussions between the two houses.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Whether the government is trying to run down additional leads in
an already strong case or buttress a weak one is not clear, said
lawyers representing parties in the civil and antitrust actions.
The government already believes it has substantial proof that the
people who were then chief executives and chairmen of the two
companies _ Brooks and A. Alfred Taubman at Sotheby's, and Davidge
and Anthony Tennant at Christie's _ conspired to raise sellers'
fees in 1995, people close to the investigation say.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers involved in the case believe the prosecution has not
been able to establish a case that four years earlier Sotheby's and
Christie's executives also agreed to fix the prices they charged
buyers. The allegations of early collusion are potentially far more
costly to both companies because, if substantiated, they would open
a new class of plaintiffs that is far larger than the number of
sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the documents from Davidge that Christie's law firm,
Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom, provided to federal
prosecutors in December are memorandums Davidge wrote to Tennant,
lawyers involved in the case said. They said the memorandums
detailed the progress of meetings he had with Brooks to set the new
commission fees.
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with the documents but who spoke only on
condition of anonymity because of the continuing investigation,
said that the documents contain references to collusion over the
buyers' fees in the 1991-92 period. But some of the documents are
not dated, people familiar with them said. As a result, the
government has been seeking confirming testimony from other
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Davidge said that it was Tennant, chairman of Christie's from
1993 to '96, who asked him to meet with Brooks, his counterpart at
Sotheby's, to agree on fixing its buyers' and sellers' charges,
people familiar with his allegations say. A person close to Brooks
said she has let prosecutors know that under certain conditions of
immunity from prosecution, she would be prepared to testify that
Sotheby's chairman, Taubman (who resigned as chairman the same day
she did as chief executive), had asked her to meet with Davidge
over sellers' fees. But the person close to Brooks was unable to
confirm any talks involving buyers' fees starting in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks kept no records of the secret meetings she had with
Davidge, people familiar with the case say.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Brooks said that prosecutors were pressing her
for admissions that carried grave penalties, including possible
prison time.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the investigation lawyers close to
Sotheby's have said while Taubman did meet with Tennant in the
early to mid-1990's, the conversations were innocent and had
nothing to do with a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, the chief prosecutor in the case, said he would not
comment on the investigation in any way.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Levander, a Manhattan lawyer who has been hired by
Sotheby's to represent some of its employees who are being
contacted by the government, declined to comment on whether he was
involved in the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
