<HEADER>
A0923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RAC-LEMONDROPKID-NYT &LR;      06-11 0272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-LEMONDROPKID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEMON DROP KID RALLIES TO WIN BROOKLYN HANDICAP 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ After 38 starts at 20 tracks in six countries and
three races in the last three weeks, Running Stag probably had to
stop running sometime. And he did stop Sunday when Lemon Drop Kid
rallied to win the 112th Brooklyn Handicap by seven and a quarter
lengths in the heat of Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid, who won the Belmont Stakes and the Travers last
year and ran third last month in the Pimlico Special, changed his
pattern by contesting the lead from the start. After three-quarters
of a mile, he was second to Running Stag, the favorite, and then
took the lead in the homestretch and extended it while Running Stag
faded to sixth place.
</P>
<P>
   It took a crowded photo to separate the next five horses: Lager
by a head for second place, Down the Aisle by a head for third,
Almutawakel by a neck for fourth and Ghost Story by a head for
fifth over Running Stag.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid, owned by Jeanne Vance and trained by Scotty
Schulhofer, ran the mile and an eighth under Edgar Prado in 1:49
4/5, returned $6.20 for a $2 bet to win and earned $150,000,
boosting his career winnings past $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around the track for a long time,'' Schulhofer said,
``and this is the first time in my life that tears came to my eyes
when he crossed the finish line because he means so much to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Mitchell, who trains Running Stag, said: ``The heat and
not a fast enough early pace both worked against him. He's had
three races close together, but that's the route we were given.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
