u s BC-RAC-BELMONT-LUKAS-NYT     06-11 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-LUKAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST 3-YEAR-OLD WILL NOT BE DECIDED UNTIL LATE SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last week D. Wayne Lukas sat down with a legal pad,
made columns for his competition in the Belmont Stakes and listed
the pros and cons of each horse winning the third leg of the Triple
Crown. The upside of Hugh Hefner, for example, was that the colt
was the lone speed in the race. The downside: He could not carry it
a mile and a half.
</P>
<P>
   The favorite Aptitude? He would be too far back and have too
much to do. When the columns were toted, Lukas believed his colt
Commendable had a shot of winning for a sole reason. ``He could run
his natural race with his tactical speed and have a say in the
outcome,'' Lukas said Sunday. ``Everyone else had to change their
running styles.''
</P>
<P>
   Both scouting reports turned out to be true. Commendable tracked
the front-running Hugh Hefner to the mile mark, scooted past him on
the final turn. Aptitude, meanwhile, was in 10th place and indeed
too far back to run down Pat Day and Commendable in the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Triple Crown is completed with three different
horses owning a piece of it, Lukas, as well as horse racing
enthusiasts, might as well get out that legal pad again. About the
only thing the spring classics proved this time around was that the
3-year-old champion would not be decided until late summer or next
season.
</P>
<P>
   As spectacular as Fusaichi Pegasus looked in the Kentucky Derby,
he looked just as ordinary losing to Red Bullet in the Preakness.
As professional as Red Bullet looked in the Preakness, he looked
merely competent finishing second to Fusaichi Pegasus in the Wood.
Only because both horses were withheld from the Derby was
Commendable _ a horse that had sandwiched a fifth-place, four
fourth places and a 17th place between his maiden victory and the
Belmont score _ can have a claim (at least on paper) to being the
best in his generation.
</P>
<P>
   Now what? The trainer of Red Bullet, Joe Orseno, tossed off a
challenge to his competitors Sunday. He said his colt, a victor in
four of five starts, was headed to the Grade II Dwyer at Belmont on
July 9, the Grade I Haskell at Monmouth on Aug. 6 and on to the
summer showcase for 3-year-olds, the Grade I Travers, on Aug. 26 at
Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where we're going to be if they want to come,'' Orseno
said.
</P>
<P>
   One horse that Orseno and Red Bullet will hook amid that
campaign is More Than Ready _ the Blue Grass runner-up whose
fourth-place Kentucky Derby finish was remarkable in light of the
blistering pace he helped press. The trainer Todd Pletcher says he
will use the mile-and-a-sixteenth Dwyer as a prep for the
mile-and-an-eighth Haskell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his speed is suited to that distance,'' said Pletcher,
who will wait and see how More Than Ready performs before deciding
on the mile-and-a-quarter Travers.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas says Commendable also is a likely starter in the Haskell.
Somewhere in that trio of races Red Bullet could also see the Peter
Pan winner Postponed and the Belmont's third-place finisher
Unshaded. Unshaded's trainer, Carl Nafzger, believes his late
blooming gelding is suited for the Travers and will decide between
the Haskell and the Jim Dandy, which is run on the same weekend at
Saratoga. His owner, James Tafel, anted up $100,000 supplemental
fee to get in the Belmont only to watch Unshaded's big move in the
final turn to be sapped by mild heat exhaustion. The gelding
wobbled past the finish line and was immediately treated with water
and ice. He was fine Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Travers is the race I've wanted since before the Kentucky
Derby,'' Nafzger said.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is just as muddled out west, where Fusaichi
Pegasus, the Santa Anita Derby winner The Deputy, and Lukas' top
horse and the Blue Grass winner High Yield are based.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas says High Yield is likely to start in the Swaps on July 23
at Hollywood Park. The Deputy and War Chant _ trained by Neil
Drysdale _ are also probable starters in the Swaps. The trainer
Bobby Frankel says Aptitude, the Derby and Belmont runner up, will
stay in New York until he decides where to run him.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Drysdale has not decided where his big horse,
Fusaichi Pegasus, will run next. The Derby winner was scratched
from the Belmont last week after sustaining a minor cut in an
accident in his stall.
</P>
<P>
   The colt's trainer and owner, Fusao Sekiguchi, will meet this
week in Los Angeles and map out a campaign aimed at winning the $4
million Breeders' Cup Classic on the first weekend in November at
Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale will not say for certain, but he may skip the
3-year-old skirmishes of the summer and wait until the fall to prep
against older horses _ perhaps in the Woodward, a $500,000 race on
Sept. 16 and the $1 million The Jockey Club Gold Cup on Oct. 14.
Both are Grade I races at Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's premature, but if Sekiguchi is thinking about the Dubai
World Cup next spring,'' Drysdale, by phone from California, said
Sunday of the $5 million race, ``we'll probably not race in the
summer. It would be too much on the horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this time, the Lukas-trained Charismatic had
captured the Derby, the Preakness and finished third at the Belmont
despite injuring a foreleg in the far turn. The colt was surgically
repaired, retired and eventually named 3-year-old champion. The
Hall of Fame trainer whose third-string colt gave him his 13th
Triple Crown victory concedes this year that the spring classics
are a wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is decided,'' he said. ``In the second season or
summer season, we're all going to have to face each other and sort
it out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
