u w BC-SECURITY-ADVISER-PROF     06-11 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECURITY-ADVISER-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPUTY SECURITY ADVISER EXCHANGES WHITE HOUSE FOR BIG APPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He works out of a cubicle not much bigger than a
prison cell, but his ambit is the world.
</P>
<P>
   James Steinberg, the White House's deputy national security
adviser, is less visible than his boss, Sandy Berger, who works in
a sunlit corner office a few steps away in the West Wing.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg seldom appears on television, gives few on-the-record
briefings and tends to remain in the background at public
appearances of the president.
</P>
<P>
   But his influence has been widely felt in the administration
through his role as chairman of the committee of deputies of the
government's national security agencies. And Steinberg has often
colored press coverage of administration foreign policy by offering
burnished versions of events to a few favored reporters. Some dare
call it spin.
</P>
<P>
   In Steinberg's eyes, President Clinton's meetings with foreign
leaders are never tense, they are ``businesslike.'' Interagency
discussions are never argumentative, they are ``lively.'' One of
his standing orders to staff members is that they never put
anything sensitive on paper; paper trails lead to subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   To outsiders, Steinberg gives the impression of being a
friendly, relaxed sort, but associates know, and occasionally fear,
his intensity. His temper has scared away potential colleagues from
other agencies and shortened the tenures of several assistants.
</P>
<P>
   He is so single-minded that when a reporter once phoned his
office seeking comment on Bosnia, he called back _ from his
honeymoon.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday was as close to a typical day as there is for
someone at the vortex of U.S. foreign policy. At 7 a.m., Steinberg
met with the heads of the State Department, Department of Defense,
Department of Justice, the FBI and the CIA. The subject was a
sensitive international law enforcement matter about which
Steinberg would say no more.
</P>
<P>
   At 8 a.m., Steinberg briefed the president for a telephone call
that Clinton was to make to Vladimir Putin, the Russian president,
a few minutes later. At 8:30 a.m., Steinberg attended the senior
staff meeting chaired by Steve Ricchetti, the deputy White House
chief of staff, to discuss financing for antidrug efforts in
Colombia and the Pentagon budget, among other matters. That was
followed by a conference call with officials at the State
Department to talk about a British peacekeeping mission to Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg then briefed Clinton for his meeting with President
Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico in the Oval Office at 12:45 p.m. After
that, the Middle East, reparations for Holocaust survivors, the
Northern Ireland peace process, the war between Ethiopia and
Eritrea, the Congo, preparations for the Group of 8 industrialized
nations.
</P>
<P>
   It is a heady life for someone who started in the Clinton
administration in 1993 as a deputy assistant secretary of state in
the relatively obscure Bureau of Intelligence and Research. But
Steinberg had a mentor in Secretary of State Warren Christopher,
for whom he had worked in the Carter administration.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher elevated him to the chief of policy planning, the
State Department's internal research center, a position Steinberg
described as ``the best foreign policy job anywhere.'' When the
national security adviser, Anthony Lake, left after Clinton's
re-election, Berger moved up and Steinberg moved into Berger's
deputy slot, a position held in the past by the likes of Colin
Powell, Alexander Haig, David Aaron and Robert McFarlane.
</P>
<P>
   But Steinberg, 47, is leaving all that behind. Later this
summer, he will join the Markle Foundation in New York to work on a
$100 million project to study the impact of the digital revolution
on international relations and economic development. Steinberg has
known the foundation's director, Zoe Baird, since the Carter
administration, in which they served as lawyers, she at the White
House, he at the Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Baird was Clinton's first choice for attorney general, but
withdrew from consideration after it was disclosed that she had not
paid taxes for a baby sitter.
</P>
<P>
   The Markle project addresses many of the issues that have
preoccupied Steinberg over the past seven years: the march of
technology, the globalization of markets, the ubiquity of the
Internet and the social and security concerns they raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you create a governance structure for what is basically
a private sector function?'' Steinberg asked. ``Government can't do
this. But how can private entities bring the benefits of the
networked society to developing countries?''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg cut his teeth in local politics in his native Boston
where he grew up as the son of a jeweler. He worked for Mayor Kevin
White of Boston in the 1970s and on the congressional campaigns of
the Rev. Robert Drinan. Steinberg has a law degree from Yale. He
worked on the staff of Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., for the
1988 presidential campaign of Michael Dukakis, and for the Rand
Corp. Steinberg identified the Balkans and the evolution of
relations between the United States and China as the two areas that
have engaged him most deeply in the past seven years. He was one of
the architects of Clinton's decision in 1994 to sever the link
between human rights and trade with China. That policy remains a
sore point between Clinton and many Democrats in Congress, as well
as unions and human rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg defends the administration's record on Bosnia and on
Kosovo, but said that the unfinished business of the Balkans
remains his biggest regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't have a stable southeastern Europe,'' he said, ``until
the problem of Serbia is resolved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
