<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYORS-CONFERENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFFORDABLE HOUSING SHORTAGE IN CITIES PROMPTS $30 BILLION AID
BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's expanding economy has produced an unintended
downside, rapidly increasing housing costs that are denying many
working-class wage earners an affordable place to live, especially
in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   The growing gap is a major finding of the Clinton
administration's fourth annual State of the Cities report, an
assessment of the nation's economic health that otherwise reflects
favorably on cities and suburbs that are now enjoying overall low
unemployment and high rates of home ownership.
</P>
<P>
   But economic growth that administration officials say has led to
22 million new jobs in the last seven years has helped push up
housing costs beyond the reach of many workers. The report found
that the shortage of affordable houses and rental units is
particularly acute in cities like Denver and San Francisco, where
high-tech companies have led the boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have become a victim of our own success,'' Housing
Secretary Andrew Cuomo said in an interview. ``We have a great
economy, and I hope it keeps going. But we also have to manage the
downside of good economic times.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo is scheduled to present the report Monday in Seattle at a
meeting of the National Conference of Mayors.
</P>
<P>
   The report suggests that the federal government can help close
the housing gap by providing more financial assistance in the form
of vouchers that could be applied toward rent and, for the first
time, mortgage costs.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, the report more than points out a problem: It
also supports the administration's housing budget request for
fiscal year 2001, a $32.1 billion proposal that represents a 23
percent increase over last year and would be the largest housing
budget in two decades. Last week, the House Appropriations
Committee approved all but $2.5 billion of the administration's
request.
</P>
<P>
   The report concludes that the economic health of cities, in
general, has continued to improve in recent years, spurred by job
creation in high-tech industries that is three times the growth
rate for jobs in other industries. The combination has resulted in
a 4.7 percent population increase in the nation's 331 largest
metropolitan areas between 1990 and 1998, compared with an overall
decline of 3.1 percent from 1970 to 1980.
</P>
<P>
   While that swing has infused cities with a new vitality through
ethnic and racial diversity, as the report states, it has helped
drive up housing costs at a rate far beyond inflation. In cities
like New York, Denver and San Francisco, competition for even small
apartment units has led to monthly rental costs of $2,000 and more.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, job growth in cities and a growing disdain for long
commutes from the suburbs have led many people to seek housing
closer to their city jobs, only to find that prices in many
neighborhoods are increasing at annual rates of 20 percent and
more.
</P>
<P>
   The result, the report says, is a record number of ``worst case
needs,'' which represents families who pay more than half of their
income for housing or families who live in inadequate housing. In
1997, the last year for which statistics are available, the number
of these families reached 5.4 million, a 12 percent increase over
the same group of people in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make matters worse,'' the report states, ``the number of
affordable housing units is shrinking just when it needs to
expand.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said that the challenge for the Clinton administration in
its final months would be to help moderate wage-earners gain access
to better housing while doing nothing that interrupts overall
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   What could make the efforts easier, he said, was what he
perceives as a new willingness by Republicans to seek answers to
the same problems. He recalled that four years ago Sen. Bob Dole,
the Republican challenger to President Clinton, favored eliminating
the Housing Department.
</P>
<P>
   But after Cuomo's address Monday to the mayors, a majority of
whom are Democrats, the Republican presidential candidate, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, plans to lay out his plans for housing and
economic development in a speech to the same group, addressing the
conference by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come a long way in four years,'' Cuomo said. ``Four
years after Republicans wanted to get rid of us, Gov. Bush has a
competing plan. I'd say that was progress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
