<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HACK-A-SHAQ'S FREE-THROW SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Forget Hack-a-Shaq. The Pacers' Jalen Rose may
have stumbled upon a real ratings gimmick when he suggested that
equally difficult to beat would be Shaq and four hacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the same team with you four guys standing out there,''
Rose told a small gathering of reporters the other day. ``As long
as they've got Shaq in the paint.''
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to the hobbled Kobe Bryant, that would be
an excellent vantage point from which to cover the National
Basketball Association finals _ from the left wing, making the
entry pass to Shaquille O'Neal, before flipping open the laptop to
record his latest adventure at the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   Is that what they mean when they talk about the interactive
newspaper?
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen years ago, on the eve of the finals, Moses Malone
claimed that he and four buddies from the playgrounds of
Petersburg, Va., could handle the Boston Celtics. Given the
opportunity with a supporting cast that wasn't much of an upgrade,
Malone and his Houston Rockets surrendered in six games. Larry
Bird, of course, was playing in that series, as opposed to coaching
the victory-starved Indiana Pacers in Game 3 Sunday night at
Conseco Fieldhouse, reduced to sending Rik Smits and other
unequipped and outclassed big men who are closing in on retirement
to cower in the presence of O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Before we go any further, I know what most Knicks fans were
thinking after watching Shaq win the first two games of the series
in Los Angeles, and my advice is, forget it. If you think the
Knicks' front line would have been a better match, consider that it
was physically obscured in the Eastern Conference finals by one
Dale Davis, who in Los Angeles looked like a kid riding Shaq
piggy-back.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, Jeff Van Gundy's lovable louts would not have
been content to play Hack-a-Shaq either. It would have been more
whack, smack and thwack. Kurt Thomas in his face, Charlie Ward at
his knees. That's all the league would have needed in this playoff
season of the viewers' discontent, more tasteless posturing and a
few more technical fouls and more free throws for these teams to
shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Say this for the maturing Shaq, who used to get frustrated by
the hacking and would occasionally threaten retaliatory mayhem.
Throughout these playoffs, he has taken the tactical taunting for
what it is, the last desperate act before concession, and just
marched professionally to the line to do his best. He missed 21
free throws in Game 2 and but got better as the night wore on and
still scored 40. The game dragged like five sets in Paris but, as
Bird later drawled: ``Well, I don't worry about ratings. I'm trying
to win a ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not classic basketball, or television, but then, the
All-Star Game is a freewheeling dunkathon every year and it is
stultifying to the point of being unwatchable. These games are at
least the result of honest competition. If the Devils and the
Dallas Stars resort to conservative hockey to avoid making that one
killer mistake and take the final Stanley Cup games into the wee
hours, well, that's sport, in nonscripted splendor. If the NBA is
so concerned about stoppages of play and length of the game, maybe
it can pressure the network to take fewer commercial breaks, and
allow for some sense of continuity to be established in the game.
Or go the other way completely, and start awarding Shaq prize money
for every free throw he hits, adding to the pot as the game moves
along and the shots mean more.
</P>
<P>
   There's been talk that the league might tinker again with the
rules to further discourage the Hack-a-Shaq, but the sport begins
to look fake when it modifies its game to accommodate a particular
player. Make your free throws. End of story. For my money, there
are serious concessions being made by any coach who puts O'Neal at
the line, consistently hoping to trade one point for two. For one
thing, he is guaranteeing even more possessions for the Lakers. For
another, he is conceding even the possibility of a turnover, a
basket in transition, and allowing O'Neal and the Lakers to set up
their defense.
</P>
<P>
   As dominating a force as O'Neal was in Los Angeles on offense,
he also had a profound effect in the Lakers' success on defense.
Out of respect for _ and fear of _ O'Neal, the Pacers have
established almost no low-post offense, putting too much pressure
on their jump shooters. A perimeter shooting team that can't force
a double-team in the paint and make the defense rotate is a team
that can generally be counted on to shoot 40 percent (the Pacers
were at 39.5 after the first two games).
</P>
<P>
   Well, as someone once said _ Pat Riley or James Naismith _ no
playoff statement is really made until someone wins on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we have five men on the floor, we're OK,'' Ron
Harper said, presumably counting Shaq among them. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
