<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0939 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-CANADA-U.S.-ENERGY &LR;      06-11 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-U.S.-ENERGY </SLUG>
  
 CALGARY, Alberta: climactic extremes . 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the East Coast, North Atlantic developments off Nova Scotia
and Newfoundland are turning the Maritime provinces into a major
oil and gas producing area. The United States is the sole export
market.
</P>
<P>
   The region's first major oil project, Newfoundland's Hibernia,
started production in November 1997. This May, Exxon Mobil
announced plans to increase production by 30 percent this year, to
65 million barrels a day. The province's second large project,
Terra Nova, is to begin production early next year. With four other
oil projects in the planning stage, a recent government study
increased Newfoundland's offshore oil reserves by almost a third,
to 2.1 billion barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Off the coast of Nova Scotia, Sable Offshore Energy Inc., which
was started in January to pump natural gas to New England, is
bringing the first piped gas to Maine in a pipeline that goes to
Boston. In addition, gas companies are spending $400 million more
to explore offshore tracts around the Sable development.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Canada's West, the energy action is moving north.
</P>
<P>
   While Alberta's oil production dropped 6 percent last year, it
is expected to rebound in coming years as $25 billion worth of
investments in northern Alberta's oil sands starts to pay off.
These reserves of thick oil, estimated in size to rival those of
Saudi Arabia, were largely untouched. But new technologies,
including some that use steam and hot water, now render about 15
percent of the deposits _ 5 billion barrels _ recoverable at a cost
of $10 or less a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Over this decade, the oil sands portion of Canada's oil
production is expected to double, hitting 50 percent by 2005. In
Fort McMurray, the northern Alberta epicenter of oil sands mining,
there is such a labor shortage that doughnut shops and fast-food
shops have had to cut back service until new workers can be brought
up from the south.
</P>
<P>
   Oil sands and North Atlantic production will allow Canada to
increase its oil exports to the United States by about 50 percent
over this decade. With this increase, Canada will probably surpass
Venezuela to become the United States' most important source of
imported oil. This expansion takes place in an international
economy where low oil prices have allowed world oil consumption to
double since 1970, approaching 80 million barrels a day by the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week, I saw a stretched-out Humvee in New York; the week
before I saw a Range Rover without a speck of mud driving around
London,'' said Martin P. Molyneaux, managing director for research
at First Energy Capital, an oil and gas brokerage firm based in
Calgary. ``Consumption per vehicle is high. World consumption keeps
going northward.''
</P>
<P>
   On the natural gas front, growing American demand and higher
prices are pushing Canada's production frontier north of the Arctic
Circle. For years, bad economics, local American Indian reluctance,
and environmental opposition blocked development of massive
reserves in the Mackenzie River delta and Beaufort Sea area. The
deposits, some of the largest in the world, were only viable for
development when natural gas prices surpassed $2.50 per million
British thermal units. But now with North American gas prices
hovering around $4, everyone here is looking north.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, nobody was talking about the far north,'' said
Pierre R. Alvarez, president of the Canadian Association of
Petroleum Producers. ``But now the price has moved substantially,
and people are working on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gas developers are drawing maps for multibillion-dollar
pipelines, negotiating with local Indians for participation and
discussing environmental safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   At stake are the largest known natural gas reserves in North
America below the Beaufort Sea. The Mackenzie Delta area is
believed to hold 9 trillion cubic feet of gas, roughly equal to the
gas reserves off the coast of Nova Scotia. To the west of the
Mackenzie, Alaska's Prudhoe Bay is believed to hold 25 trillion to
30 trillion cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   One proposed 5,000-mile pipeline would run from Prudhoe Bay,
potentially underwater to minimize environmental impacts, then
south along the Mackenzie River into Northern Alberta to connect
with pipelines to the United States. Unlike oil, natural gas is
easier to pump cold.
</P>
<P>
   This line could carry 3.5 billion cubic feet of American and
Canadian gas, a 40 percent jump over Canada's current export level
to the United States. This October, when the $3 billion Alliance
pipeline opens from here to Chicago, Western Canada will have
excess pipeline capacity into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Energy experts believe consumer pressure will prevail over any
environmentalist opposition, and that Canada's Arctic will be
opened to gas production by the end of this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. and Canadian utilities are running scared now, almost
everybody has overestimated supply and underestimated demand,''
Molyneaux, the energy analyst, said. He noted that in the last five
years 75 percent of new electricity generation in the United States
went to natural gas. ``If your energy bills go up by 30 percent,
you are not going to be happy about it,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
