<SLUG> BC-MONTENEGRO-ELECTION-725-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIDDEN WITHIN MONTENEGRO ELECTION, A REFERENDUM ON MILOSEVIC  
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Montenegro _ Montenegrins voted in two local
elections on Sunday that were being closely watched as a barometer
of relations between this small Western-leaning republic and
President Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, voters in the Montenegrin capital, Podgorica, and in
the seaside town of Herceg Novi were simply electing new mayors and
local assemblies.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the vote was effectively a poll on who wants to stay
with Milosevic and Yugoslavia _ which now consists only of Serbia
and Montenegro _ and who prefers the more independent course of
Montenegro's leader, Milo Djukanovic.
</P>
<P>
   Western ministers and diplomats have leaned heavily on
Djukanovic in recent months to avoid a complete break with Belgrade
and to postpone any referendum on independence. It is also not
clear that the president and his ruling coalition would win
sufficient support; opinion polls indicate a fairly even split
among Montenegro's 600,000 people between staying with the Serbs
and breaking ties.
</P>
<P>
   Both outsiders and residents of this small republic fear any
outright rupture with Belgrade would cause another in the series of
Balkan wars that have erupted since the old communist Yugoslavia
began splitting apart a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic's coalition _ called ``For a Better Life'' _ was
expected to win in the capital, Podgorica, with a much closer
ballot predicted in Herceg Novi.
</P>
<P>
   A slip at the polls for the government coalition here, coupled
with a strengthening of Milosevic's allies, could tempt Belgrade to
challenge Djukanovic's hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   Violence has already begun to color the politics of Montenegro,
where the atmosphere remains uneasy 10 days after a close aide of
Djukanovic was killed in what appears to have been a political
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav army presence remains a persistent cause for
concern for Montenegro, as do political supporters of Belgrade, who
have threatened to take to the streets if they lose in the
elections.
</P>
<P>
   There were few local issues raised during the boisterous
flag-waving rallies this past week.
</P>
<P>
   The government coalition kept to its familiar slogan and the
name of the president, offering a program of democratic reform and
openness to Europe and the West and a hint towards independence.
``We have never sold our authority, and will never sell our
country. That's what we want for Montenegro and our future,''
Djukanovic said at a rally in the capital last week.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Belgrade opposition, led by Yugoslav Prime Minister
Momir Bulatovic and local leader Predrag Bulatovic (who is no
relation to Momir), ran with the simple message ``Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Predrag Bulatovic has emphasized that Montenegro and Serbia are
equal partners in the union, yet he has been forced into a
coalition with both the most radical Serbian nationalist party and
its leader Vojislav Seselj, and the leftist party run by
Milosevic's wife, Mira Markovic. Both that alliance and televised
footage of his meeting with Milosevic in May to discuss these
elections undermined Predrag Bulatovic's claim to equal
partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The small Liberal Alliance, which caused these elections by
withdrawing from the government coalitions in both cities, has
slipped from view behind the larger parties. The most vocal
supporter for independence, and a critic of the Djukanovic
government, it hoped to win a larger part of the vote in new
elections, but has been drowned out by the greater confrontation
with Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in the capital were clear about their choice. Supporters
of the government said they voted for democracy, for modernity,
openness to the West and a future inside Europe. ``It is the only
choice with perspective,'' said one student who gave his name only
as Aco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted `For a better life.' No one wants to live worse,''
said Milisav Miuskovic, a school janitor, quoting the government
coalition slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the pro-Belgrade coalition were often reluctant to
talk to a Western journalist or declined to give their names. When
they did, their arguments were direct.
</P>
<P>
   ''I voted for Momir,'' said Rada, a saleswoman who declined to
give her full name. ``I am for Yugoslavia, I do not want to
separate from Serbia. The people will not let it happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
