<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-645&AMP;AD     06-11 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE GOP TO PUSH ITS MEDICARE DRUG PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans will flesh out their proposal for
Medicare drug benefits this week and try to push it through two
House committees in three days, despite fierce objections from many
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said Sunday that they would combine their drug plan
with a proposal to give more money to health-maintenance
organizations _ perhaps $4 billion over five years _ in hopes of
halting the exodus of HMOs from Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, HMOs pulling out of Medicare have
disrupted insurance arrangements for more than 700,000 elderly
people, and many more health plans are expected to withdraw this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Documents prepared by senior House Republicans show that they
would increase Medicare payments to HMOs, especially those in rural
areas, which now receive the lowest payments.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said such increases were needed to keep HMOs in
Medicare and to attract them to markets they have avoided. But some
Democrats, like Rep. Pete Stark of California, said the increases
were unjustified because many health plans were overpaid.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Republican proposal, the government would subsidize
private insurance to cover pharmaceutical costs for Medicare
beneficiaries. Such insurance, covering only drug costs, is now
unavailable, and insurance companies say they do not intend to sell
it, but the Republicans have set aside up to $40 billion over the
next five years to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   A summary of the House Republican plan says the government would
guarantee access to drug coverage if private insurers did not offer
it. ``All beneficiaries, regardless of where they live, would have
the choice of at least two plans, one of which must be a
prescription-drug plan'' for people in Medicare's original
fee-for-service program, the document says.
</P>
<P>
   Trent D. Duffy, a spokesman for Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who
is chairman of the Ways and Means Committee, said: ``Whether you
live in rural Kansas or downtown New York, you will have the option
to buy drug coverage. The government would be the insurer of last
resort in the unlikely event that private plans are not
available.''
</P>
<P>
   Duffy said the premiums would probably average $30 to $40 a
month. But, Republicans said, premiums, deductibles, co-payments
and details of the benefit packages would vary among plans.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans said they expected to win approval for their
proposal at meetings of the Ways and Means Committee and the
Commerce Committee on Wednesday, Thursday and Friday. They want the
full House to pass it this month, before the Fourth of July recess,
to counter Democratic charges that Congress has done nothing on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   One feature of the House Republican plan is sure to infuriate
Clinton administration officials: It would create an agency in the
Department of Health and Human Services to administer drug benefits
and the HMO program for Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The new agency would be known as the Medicare Oversight and
Management Administration. Republicans said it was needed because
Medicare officials had been biased against HMOs and had imposed too
much regulation on health-care providers. The new agency, as
envisioned by House Republicans, would have more of a free-market
orientation and would encourage private health plans to compete for
Medicare business.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans acknowledge that drug companies often charge
higher prices in the United States than in other countries. But
rather than limiting prices here, they would direct the U.S. trade
representative to negotiate with other countries to ``eliminate
price controls'' on drugs in Canada and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Bolger, a pollster who advises House Republicans on the
politics of the prescription-drug issue, said: ``It's very
important that Republicans stick together and pass a bill. If they
don't pass a bill, they'll pay a price at the ballot box.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For political purposes, some Republicans said, the fact that
they have a plan and are trying to pass it is more important than
the content of the plan or whether it actually becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   Here are details of the House Republican plan, as described in
documents obtained from Republican leaders:
</P>
<P>
   _ Medicare beneficiaries would be encouraged to enroll in a
drug-insurance plan before they became sick. They would initially
have six months to enroll. They could change plans once a year, but
``must maintain continuous drug coverage'' through HMOs,
prescription-drug plans or a former employer's health plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prescription-drug plans would aggressively negotiate with drug
companies to secure discounts for Medicare beneficiaries. Insurers
would have to cover ``all major therapeutic classes of drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The government would pay premiums and all other costs except
modest co-payments _ say, $5 a prescription _ for people with
incomes up to 35 percent above the poverty level. The government
would provide smaller subsidies for people with incomes from 35
percent to 50 percent above the poverty level. (A couple is
classified as poor if they have income of less than $11,250 this
year.)
</P>
<P>
   _ The government would help insurance companies by paying most
of the drug costs incurred by Medicare beneficiaries with the
highest costs. An insurance plan with a typical mix of patients
would receive a subsidy for 25 percent to 30 percent of all its
pharmaceutical costs, ``making insurance more affordable for all
beneficiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican bill would increase the basic payments that
HMOs receive for providing services to Medicare beneficiaries. It
would also, for the first time, allow HMOs to negotiate with the
government to obtain even more money, if they could prove that
their costs justified such payments. The new Medicare agency could
grant increases up to a maximum matching the growth of premiums in
the private insurance market.
</P>
<P>
   Private insurance costs have been rising more than twice as fast
as Medicare payments to many HMOs: 4.8 percent a year, as against 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans will also try to ``recoup government
investments in the research and development of prescription
drugs,'' their documents say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
