u i BC-EXP-MONTENEGRO-ELECTI     06-11 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXP-MONTENEGRO-ELECTION-725-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIDDEN WITHIN MONTENEGRO ELECTION, A REFERENDUM ON MILOSEVIC  
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This article is part of TIMES EXPRESS. It is a condensed
version of a story that will appear in tomorrow's New York Times.) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Montenegro _ Montenegrins voted in two local
elections on Sunday that were being closely watched as a barometer
of relations between this small Western-leaning republic and
President Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, voters in the Montenegrin capital, Podgorica, and in
the seaside town of Herceg Novi were simply electing new mayors and
local assemblies.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the vote was effectively a poll on who wants to stay
with Milosevic and Yugoslavia _ which now consists only of Serbia
and Montenegro _ and who prefers the more independent course of
Montenegro's leader, Milo Djukanovic.
</P>
<P>
   Western ministers and diplomats have leaned heavily on
Djukanovic in recent months to avoid a complete break with Belgrade
and to postpone any referendum on independence. It is also not
clear that the president and his ruling coalition would win; polls
indicate a fairly even split among Montenegro's 600,000 people
between staying with the Serbs and breaking ties.
</P>
<P>
   The fear is that an outright rupture with Belgrade would cause
another of the Balkan wars that have erupted since communist
Yugoslavia began splitting apart a decade ago. Violence has already
begun to color the politics of Montenegro, where the atmosphere
remains uneasy 10 days after a close aide of Djukanovic was killed
in what appears to have been a political assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic's coalition _ called ``For a Better Life'' _ was
expected to win in the capital, Podgorica, with a much closer
ballot predicted in Herceg Novi. The government coalition kept to
its slogan and the name of the president, offering a program of
democratic reform and openness to the West and a hint towards
independence.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Belgrade opposition, led by Yugoslav Prime Minister
Momir Bulatovic and local leader Predrag Bulatovic (who is no
relation to Momir), ran with the simple message ``Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   The small Liberal Alliance, which caused these elections by
withdrawing from the government coalitions in both cities, has
slipped from view behind the larger parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
