u s BC-HKN-STARS-SUDDENDEATH     06-11 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SUDDENDEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' MOODS SWING ON ONE PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ ``They call it sudden death,'' a weary Mike Modano said
early Sunday morning. ``And it feels like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a mood swing. Two days earlier, Modano, the Dallas
Stars' center, had scored in the third overtime in New Jersey to
extend the Stanley Cup finals to a sixth game. Sunday morning,
Modano and the rest of the Stars knew exactly how the Devils had
felt.
</P>
<P>
   The tension mounting with each successive rush up and down the
ice late Saturday night, the Devils' Jason Arnott finally finished
off the defending champion Stars with the cup-clinching goal at 8
minutes 20 seconds of the second overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott's overtime goal was the 15th in history to clinch a
Stanley Cup. The Devils won their second cup in franchise history,
and first since 1995, while preventing the Stars from repeating as
champions of the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1993 had consecutive games in the finals gone to
overtime. Then, Montreal defeated Los Angeles in extra time in
Games 2, 3 and 4, while taking the series in five games.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1951, when Toronto defeated Montreal, four games to
one, with all five games going to overtime, had the last two games
of a finals series gone past regulation.
</P>
<P>
   And not since Games 2 and 3 of the 1931 Finals, then played
under a three-of-five-game format had there been consecutive
multiple overtimes in the finals. Montreal shook off losses to
Chicago in both those games and took the Cup, three games to two.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Stars and the Devils played a combined 83 minutes
11 seconds of overtime _ nearly an hour and a half _ over parts of
five periods since Thursday night. It was no wonder they were
physically beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in overtime, it only takes one play and the series is
over,'' Derian Hatcher, the Dallas captain, said. ``That's what
happened tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher had ended the series for Petr Sykora much earlier _
12:08 into the game _ with an vicious elbow that necessitated a
stretcher to take Sykora off the ice. Sykora spent the night in a
hospital, cheering the Devils on.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher, who could barely walk after Game 6, displayed no
remorse for the hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared when he didn't get up for a while,'' Hatcher
said. ``But someone said he was moving and talking. Those were the
real important things.''
</P>
<P>
   Sykora made the trip back to New Jersey, and the Devils, who won
all three games on Dallas ice, were able to avoid a Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both goaltenders were really good,'' said Dallas' 40-year-old
center Guy Carbonneau, who may have played the final game of his
career. Carbonneau was referring to his teammate Ed Belfour, who
stopped 91 of 93 shots over Games 5 and 6, including 43 of 45 on
Saturday night, and the Devils' Martin Brodeur, who turned aside 70
of the 72 shots fired his way the final two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can always look at we had three games at home and we
lost three games,'' Carbonneau said. ``That hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were able to make the series memorable, however, after
falling behind three games to one, and that seemed to take some of
the sting out of the loss. The Stars were plagued by serious
injuries all season. Few had predicted they would make it as far as
they did as they tried to defend the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is upset that we lost,'' Carbonneau said. ``But if
you look back on our season, we did some unbelievable things to
come two games within winning the Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars saved some of their most unbelievable things for Games
5 and 6 of the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were just two unbelievable games,'' Coach Ken Hitchcock
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
