u s BC-SOC-U.S.-MEXICO-NYT &LR;      06-11 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-MEXICO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH AN ASSIST FROM THE DENTIST, AMERICANS WIN U.S. CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ A few days earlier, Earnie Stewart's
face had swelled like a balloon, his diet had been reduced to
bananas and his noted fear of flying had been matched by the
universal nightmare of repeat visits to the dentist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost sent him home,'' said Bruce Arena, coach of the
United States men's soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, the fleet winger who had a solid season in Holland this
year, had taken an elbow to the face on June 3 against South Africa
in the opening round of the U.S. Cup. Nerve damage to a tooth
required three visits to the dentist for a root canal, a new
filling and drainage of fluid that had left the right side of his
face as puffy as pastry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a lot of pain,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   The pain and swelling subsided, which was good news for the
American men, who defeated a severely weakened Mexico team, 3-0,
Sunday to win the U.S. Cup. Stewart showed cool professionalism in
the wilting heat at Giants Stadium, setting up the first goal for
Brian McBride, nearly scoring twice himself and demonstrating the
possibility of creative, intricate combinations with the blistering
Cobi Jones as the United States begins qualifying next month for
the 2002 World Cup that will be in Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans expect to open the semifinal round of qualifying
in the North American, Central American and Caribbean region on
July 16 at Guatemala or Antigua. For the Americans, erasure of the
debacle that was the 1998 World Cup in France cannot begin quickly
enough.
</P>
<P>
   The United States finished 32nd out of 32 teams in France,
collapsing from deficient play on the field, indecisive coaching by
Steve Sampson and internal finger-pointing by the players. There is
a new coach and a seemingly new attitude among the Americans, who
appear joined by a common purpose instead of being divided by
malignant cliques.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say much about it, but it's a lot better now,''
Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   There are many questions still to be answered during World Cup
qualifying. Four players missing Sunday because of injury _ forward
Joe-Max Moore, midfielder Eddie Lewis and defenders Robin Fraser
and Eddie Pope _ could make the starting lineup. And Tony Sanneh
still has to learn that he is now playing right back, not
cornerback, on defense.
</P>
<P>
   But Arena has repaired the tattered communication lines between
coaches and players, who appear to have a clear sense of what is
expected of them, when they must conform, when they have freedom.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Stewart appeared to waste much of his time on the
wing with aimless running. But there is a new purpose to his game,
which could be troublesome to opponents as he continues his
interchangeable shifting with Jones from midfield to forward and
back again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any problem substituting back and forth,'' Jones
said. ``He can go up front a while, and I'll go wide, then he can
go wide and I'll go up front. We've played together through two or
three coaches, we're roommates on the road, pretty good friends.
There's a natural knowledge of each other.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 33rd minute Sunday, a magnificent three-pass combination
put the Americans up, 1-0. Stewart played a ball from 30 yards out
toward Jones in the middle of the field. Jones tapped it back to
Stewart, who charged the penalty area, dribbled to the end line and
crossed a pass to McBride for a wide-open shot from six yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce has given them to freedom to roam the field,'' the
playmaker Claudio Reyna said of Stewart and Jones. ``When you have
players who are allowed to roam with that kind of speed, it makes
it difficult for defenders. Bruce gives them the chance to do what
they do best. He doesn't stick them in one position. That creates a
lot of danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's opponent was essentially the Mexican club team, Pumas,
not the Mexican national team. From the beginning, the Mexicans
were overmatched. In the 70th minute, defender Christian Ramirez
received his second yellow card for dragging Jones down on a
breakaway and was ejected. Playing a man up the final 20 minutes,
the Americans scored twice more as Frankie Hejduk tipped in a Jones
shot that deflected off the post and Ante Razov stole a sloppy back
pass and slipped a left-footed shot into the net.
</P>
<P>
   A tired Stewart was replaced by Hejduk in the 76th minute, but
he had played impressively with his quiet leadership and clamorous
speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you always stay in the same position, it's a lot easier for
defenses to zone,'' Stewart said. ``If you're switching, it
confuses defenses and you get guys open.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
