u a BC-SCHOOLS-CHEATING-2TAK     06-11 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-CHEATING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARYLAND SCHOOL CHEATING INCIDENT RENEWS CONCERNS ABOUT TESTING 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POTOMAC, Md. _ Six students here at the highly regarded Potomac
Elementary School, suspicious about the way their fifth-grade state
achievement tests were administered last month, bothered to
complain at home about some odd things they noticed.
</P>
<P>
   They thereby precipitated the resignation of the school
principal, the suspension of a teacher, and the discovery of what
officials describe as substantial evidence of administrative
cheating on a test that lends ranking and, inevitably, cachet to
the best schools across the state.
</P>
<P>
   The test incident catapulted Potomac Elementary, one of the
highest rated schools in the affluent, competitive suburbs of the
Washington Beltway, into the national debate about whether high
intensity standardization tests _ driven by politicians' and
parents' demands for firmer evidence of school improvement _ risks
skewing education as much as helping it. The Potomac setting
differs from most other cheating scandals because the school
already was in the upper echelon of achievement, even as
supervisors pressed for it to do better.
</P>
<P>
   ``These tests were never designed for setting real estate values
or for politicians to use as a way to lever their campaigns,''
cautioned Jerry D. Weast, the Montgomery County school system
superintendent that is investigating Potomac Elementary. Weast
called for a better understanding that the new tests of school
standards being increasingly employed across the country present a
needed, but limited, tool for curriculum and quality control, one
which can be abused by the simplistic ``public display'' of
relative rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, school ratings remain as feverishly consulted as
tax tables by home buyers looking for strong schools that put their
children on firm university and career tracks. The current
presidential hustings resonates daily with fresh promises of
tougher education standards for voters' children.
</P>
<P>
   Other cheating problems lately include New York City, where 32
schools and dozens of teachers are under investigation, and Houston
and 10 other Texas school districts where evidence surfaced of
patterns of extraordinary test erasures and corrective editing.
Officials at the highly regarded schools in Fairfax County, Va.,
another Washington suburb, are looking into charges of improper
coaching at a middle school by a teacher who allegedly helped his
students compete by availing himself of advance notice of test
questions. Another school, Eastgate Elementary in Columbus, Ohio,
was hit with a scandal about cheating in the fourth grade a few
weeks after President Clinton paid a visit to showcase its progress
in meeting standards.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of achievement testing contend that Potomac and similar
scandals around the nation suggest basic education is being
subsumed by a process of relentless testing and ranking of schools
based on values that veer far from scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools are turning into test coaching centers, caught up in
this frenzy of trying to look their best,'' said Monty Neill,
director of FairTest, a private education group in Boston opposed
to SATs and other standardized exams. Neill maintains that these
exams undermine, not bolster, the quality of education in a process
that invites cheating. ``There's no way to tell how much cheating
there actually is, but I get the sense nobody is looking too hard
for abuses,'' he said of the school districts' push to demonstrate
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland education officials said that the Potomac incident is
an aberration in such an affluent district and that the tests, one
of the early drives for credible statewide school standards, have
been well policed. Since the tests introduction in 1991, there have
been perhaps five or six minor complaints a year in the state's
1,400 schools, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel we have politicized education too much,'' said the
education superintendent of Maryland, Nancy S. Grasmick, while
defending the testing as a responsible means for educators to
target problems and tailor remedies. ``The political part of
education today does not offer stability,'' she warned, finding too
many candidates offering voters ``silver bullet'' panaceas for
difficult classroom problems.
</P>
<P>
   Weast concedes Potomac Elementary, ranked first in the prized
Montgomery County system and third in the state, ``has become a
poster child for the testing debate.'' But he said that the
incident, while alarming and deserving thorough investigation,
involves only one or two professionals at a single school in a
system of 9,500 classroom teachers and 189 schools.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the incident is confronting parents and professionals
here with the question of how to best govern the competitive
pressures that modern education puts on teachers and students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out of balance,'' said Janyce Speier, co-chair of the
Potomac Parent Teachers Association. ``I find teachers are
frustrated with the amount of time they spend on testing and would
rather be with their kids doing other things. I salute
accountability, but maybe you can push that envelope too far.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue has sparked concern that ``the battle for performance
dollars between schools finally may have taken their toll,'' as one
resident wrote to the Montgomery Journal. Another complained that
as schools compete head to head through the state's testing of
their students ``the value of their parents' property is tied to
the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   After parents alerted state officials about their children's
testing suspicions, the Potomac principal, Karen Karch, resigned in
the face of allegations that she improperly allowed students extra
time and coached them to change incorrect answers on the state
School Assessment Performance Program. The program is a rigorous
examination series in which third- and fifth-graders are tested
across parts of five school days to produce a composite
understanding of where a school stands in meeting state standards.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For all its proven record of excellence, Potomac Elementary had
been criticized earlier by district supervisors as failing to
produce its full potential in some areas. The critique is resented
in retrospect by some parents who feel it needlessly compounded the
competitive pressures. But district officials say it was fair
comment within the community's high expectations and the school's
outstanding reputation in pioneering such programs as a Mandarin
Chinese immersion course.
</P>
<P>
   ``My resignation is not an admission of guilt,'' Karch, a
professional of 30 years experience, declared in a parting
statement. ``I exercised poor judgment in some of my decisions,''
she said while declining to answer news media questions in ``a
situation that is already out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   A great deal more than prestige can be riding on the results of
the test competition among schools, from salary rewards to school
favoritism, said Bob Chase, president of the National Education
Association, the 2.5-million member teachers union that is the
largest in the nation. ``If a school doesn't get to a certain point
in the tests the financial rewards might not be there,'' he said,
describing the resultant pressures on teachers and administrators
as unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Potomac is not alone in this,'' Chase said. ``The cheating
allegations point to a bigger issue _ to make sure the use and
overuse of testing does not negatively impact something positive
like the standards movement.''
</P>
<P>
   While awaiting the results of the inquiry, the community here
has rallied round its premier school. Parents organized a vote of
confidence for the school staff by having all 634 students bring
bouquets to class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, at least it's encouraging that character building is
working at Potomac,'' said a beleaguered parent in praise of the
students who decided they had to speak up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
