<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0957 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-PUERTO-RICO-PARADE     06-11 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PUERTO-RICO-PARADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL SIGNS JOIN CULTURAL PRIDE AT PUERTO RICAN DAY PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Politicians and protesters vied for attention at
Sunday's National Puerto Rican Day Parade. But there was no
mistaking what drew the hundreds of thousands who jammed the
sidewalks for a 40-block stretch of Fifth Avenue: a chance for yet
another high-spirited celebration of Puerto Rican culture, music
and ethnic pride.
</P>
<P>
   The parade, traditionally one of the city's largest and most
boisterous, turned the Upper East Side into a undulating sea of
red, white and blue Puerto Rican flags displayed on everything from
T-shirts, to bandannas, to nail polish, necklaces and even
dog-covering capes.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rick Lazio, New York's candidates for
the U.S. Senate, were there with a long list of other state and
local politicians. Hundreds of marchers and spectators held signs
urging the United States Navy to stop using the Puerto Rican island
of Vieques as a bombing range. Still others rallied in memory of
Pedro Albizu Campos, a figure in Puerto Rico's separatist movement
who called for islanders to start an armed struggle.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the dancers, the competing salsa and merengue bands
and the floats sponsored by towns and villages from the Caribbean
island that drew the biggest roars from the crowds. So too did the
various tributes to Tito Puente, the Puerto Rican-American jazz
musician who died May 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about Puerto Rican people being together, proud of being
Puerto Rican and celebrating our day,'' said Violet Colon, 49, from
the Bronx. ``I am just happy to be here, proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani marched alongside Lazio, who replaced him
last month as the Republican candidate for the Senate. Clinton was
escorted by Fernando Ferrer, the Bronx borough president, with whom
she broke into dance at one point, as the two passed a 12-man salsa
band.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Clinton was intensely jeered and booed as she
marched up Fifth Avenue in the Salute to Israel Day Parade, in part
because of her previous support for an independent Palestinian
state. But Sunday, it was Giuliani who drew the heckles and
occasional rude gestures, evidence of his decline in popularity
among the city's Latino population since first being elected mayor
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani seemed impervious to the often bitter response, rushing
back and forth to the sidewalks to greet spectators even when he
was being booed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a better reception than I usually get,'' said Giuliani,
a reference to the heckling he had received at recent Puerto Rican
Day parades. ``I think it is wonderful. I think more people
applauded for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton clearly relished the turnaround that a week had brought.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is democracy in action,'' she said, of the reversal from
last Sunday. ``We are so blessed to live in a country where
everyone is free to express their opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   The parade _ which at times seemed to extend throughout much of
Manhattan, with the streams of cars and motorcycles festooned with
Puerto Rican flags _ illustrated the growing economic force of
Latinos in the United States economy.
</P>
<P>
   There were, of course, floats sponsored by traditional
Latino-oriented products, like Cafe Bustelo coffee and Corona, the
Mexican beer. But Showtime cable network was also there, promoting
its new television series ``Resurrection Blvd.,'' which features a
Latino family in East Los Angeles. There were also floats sponsored
by several Latino-oriented Internet sites, such as Latino.com and
LaMusica.com, as well as major retailers and consumer product
companies such as Sears and Palmolive.
</P>
<P>
   What most of these and other promotions had in common, though,
was music, pulsating, rhythmic and loud, loud, loud, such as the
Mazola Corn Oil float, which feverishly rocked back and forth to
the tunes of Los Barrio Boyzz, a performance that had the young
girls in the crowd swooning. Actors Jimmy Smits and Rosie Perez
also drew intense cheers, as did boxer Felix Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   The dedication of the parade to Pedro Albizu Campos, the
Harvard-educated lawyer and leader of the Puerto Rican Nationalist
who was imprisoned in the 1950s for trying to overthrow the U.S.
government, drew much less attention than the effort to convince
the government to stopping bombing Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are being invade,'' said Brinitte Gonazalez, 30, of the
Bronx, one of many who held a ``Peace for Vieques'' sign. ``It is
our island. I just want them to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even some of the demonstrators acknowledged that the
expression of ethnic pride and celebration of Puerto Rican cultural
that most drew them to the parade Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't come here to start a revolution,'' said Juan
Santiago, 38, of Queens, who carried a flag of Puerto Rico with the
words ``U.S. Navy out of Vieques,'' written on its white band.
``They came here to have a good time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
