<HEADER>
A0958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     06-11 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BOYS OF MIDNIGHT BRING HOME THE CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ They are moving toward Islanders
territory, having roared right through Ranger domain.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Devils were not necessarily going to get their
due merely for winning a second Stanley Cup in six seasons, gained
in the wee small hours of Sunday morning, with millions of
captivated fans and strangers paying rapt attention.
</P>
<P>
   Then at the end, the Devils hoisted above their shaggy, sweaty
heads the grandest sporting trophy in North America, the Stanley
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh, the way the Devils did it, struggling in two straight
epic games, one a loss in the third overtime Thursday night and
then the victory on the road, beating the Dallas Stars, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils never wanted to cut it this fine, but what they lost
in suffering they will gain in fame. In two straight gripping
games, they gave viewers compelling overtimes with no commercial
timeouts, gripping back-and-forth hockey that anybody could
appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils are now in their own category. If the old Dodgers of
urban Brooklyn were the Boys of Summer (courtesy of the writer
Roger Kahn) and the Islanders of the suburbs were the Boys of
Winter, then the Devils are now the Boys of Midnight.
</P>
<P>
   They flew home Sunday afternoon and deposited the Stanley Cup in
the foyer of their arena, looking surprisingly refreshed for men
who had played a long and terrifying game the night before. They
had come somewhat farther than the distance between Dallas and New
Jersey. They had now traveled into dynasty country.
</P>
<P>
   It is not exactly true that the Devils operate in a vacuum.
Hockey people have known, even before that 1995 Stanley Cup, that
Lou Lamoriello runs a good ship _ a little secretive, a little
frugal, a little tense, but a sound ship nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Lamoriello was not afraid to ship out players who did not want
to play at his prices, but he knew enough to recognize keepers _
Ken Daneyko, Martin Brodeur, Scott Stevens, the backbone.
</P>
<P>
   The real insult for the Devils, just as it was for the
Islanders, has been the anonymity conferred on them by playing in
the suburbs. The Islanders won four straight Stanley Cups from 1980
through 1983, one of the best New York teams ever for character and
skill, but they never knew the thrill of riding through the Wall
Street canyons and hearing the roars. When they won, it was
Hempstead Turnpike and a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers won one stinking Stanley Cup in 1994 and the
celebration was so great you would have thought somebody had
finally fixed all the broken parking meters.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had the mystique and the Islanders had their Stanley
Cups, but all the Devils had was the Mickey Mouse label hung on
them by that raging motormouth of controversy, Wayne Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   They can hang up the mouse ears permanently. What with free
agency and international scouting, it is harder than ever to put up
a hockey dynasty. All of us of a certain age lament when the
Montreal Canadiens were automatic finalists, but it's not going to
happen anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says the first cup is the most difficult _ and it is,
until you do it,'' Lamoriello said. ``But I say the second one is
more difficult because you are expected to win every year.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night the Devils wanted to clinch at home for their
loyal fans with red-and-black draped and slathered all over them,
but the Devils frittered away a third-period power play and
ultimately lost at 46 minutes 21 seconds of overtime. They were not
the resourceful Islanders, not that night.
</P>
<P>
   However, on Saturday night, fighting to avoid a seventh game,
the Devils came up with their own heroes, their own images. There
was Jason Arnott, playing the role of Bob Nystrom (the Islanders'
overtime hero of the first cup), scoring the winning goal at 8:21
of the fifth period. And there was Larry Robinson, the stalwart
Hall of Fame defender, now the coach, pulling on the No. 17 jersey
of his wounded forward, Petr Sykora, during the celebration on the
ice.
</P>
<P>
   These images, flickering in dens and bedrooms and bars wherever
hockey is shown, propelled these Devils into a higher league. Even
the dour Lamoriello had a sense that his competent franchise had
touched some nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it's been done,'' he said Sunday, back home. ``The
interest of the people. It's been tremendous for hockey, and great
for our area.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to go on the road and take the Stanley Cup away from
the defending champions is just great,'' said Lamoriello, who is
not prone to gush. ``It was a great battle, and it could have gone
either way.''
</P>
<P>
   He praised Robinson, who replaced the high-strung Robbie Ftorek
with eight games left in the regular season, and he praised his
young players, but mostly he praised the nine players who remain
from that 1995 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very seldom do you see so many players stay around that
long,'' Lamoriello said.
</P>
<P>
   Now the public has put a face next to the name. Daneyko's
battered mug. Stevens' gunfighter eyes. Brodeur's smile. Bobby
Holik's intensity. And the nastiness of Claude Lemieux, digging in
his skates, sending a shower of ice chips into the opposing
goalie's mask just for the meanness of it.
</P>
<P>
   These guys were slow to captivate the area, almost never selling
out a game, but they have gotten everybody's attention with those
extra periods, those bonus hours, those Peril-of-Pauline stands in
the goalmouth.
</P>
<P>
   Now the team is being sold by John McMullen to a chap named
Steinbrenner, who is known for rebuilding the Yankees. The new
owner may want to remember that the Devils are Stanley Cup
champions, with a whole new cadre of fans who can only hope he does
not mess up what has been handed to him, a contemporary dynasty of
sorts, the Boys of Midnight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
