u f BC-MINING-STOCK-SUSPENSI     06-11 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINING-STOCK-SUSPENSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH POLICY DERAILS DIAMOND MINING STOCK LISTING 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A diamond-mining company with close ties to the
governments of Congo and Zimbabwe may be thwarted in an effort to
trade on the London Stock Exchange after reports of British
government opposition to its plans, executives close to the company
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Oryx Diamonds Ltd., registered in the Cayman Islands, had
planned to seek a listing on the Alternative Investment Market,
which is part of the London exchange, on Tuesday. The company is
the result of a $75 million merger between Oryx Natural Resources
and Petra Diamonds Ltd., a South African company that already
trades on the same market.
</P>
<P>
   The planned listing on the London exchange has generated
increasing public debate since the company said it intended to
exploit a $1 billion diamond concession granted to it by a Congo
government decree at a time when the British government is
campaigning to halt the trade in so-called conflict diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey White, Oryx's deputy managing director, said that,
despite the debate surrounding the company's plans, he and other
executives thought their attempt to list shares on the London
exchange was proceeding on track until soon after markets closed on
Friday. At that time, trading in Petra Diamonds was formally
suspended in accordance with merger rules and its new listing as
Oryx Diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, however, White said in a telephone interview,
Oryx's advisers, the British accounting company Grant Thornton,
informed the company that it had unspecified concerns about the
deal and would resign if shareholders approved it at a meeting
scheduled on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   White said that, without a nominated adviser, the company would
not be permitted under stock market rules to list under its new
name and resume trading.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not know what was behind the company's change of
plan and declined to comment on British newspaper reports Sunday
that the British Foreign Office _ which is leading the government's
campaign against ``blood diamonds'' used to prolong African wars _
had put pressure on the advisers. Grant Thornton executives were
not immediately available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   White said Oryx planned to proceed with its shareholders'
meeting on Monday and would press Grant Thornton to explain its
apparent shift at that gathering.
</P>
<P>
   While Oryx denies that its concession is in a war zone, it has
acknowledged that the diamond field, south of the diamond-mining
center of Mbuji-Mayi, is guarded by some of the 11,000 Zimbabwean
troops who have been in the Congo since 1998 supporting President
Laurent Kabila against rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has forced one nonexecutive director, Moses Anafu, to
quit a high-ranking job with the 54-nation Commonwealth after his
involvement with Oryx was publicized. At the time, Anafu was
leading a Commonwealth delegation to Zimbabwe, where senior
government and military officials are linked to Oryx through at
least two Zimbabwe-registered companies, according to diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Another nonexecutive director of Oryx, Frances Cook, is a former
United States ambassador to Oman, where many of Oryx's managers,
including its chief executive, are based. She has said repeatedly
that she regards Oryx as a commercial venture that will benefit
Africans in the concession area. Oryx says she will be entitled to
a $100,000 annual fee plus stock options.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
