u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-COLUMN-NYT     06-11 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRODEUR ALSO CELEBRATES A STANLEY CUP PLAYOFFS RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ An hour earlier, Commissioner Gary Bettman had handed
the Stanley Cup to the Devils, winners over the Dallas Stars in two
overtime periods.
</P>
<P>
   Now Martin Brodeur had plunged into a chair in front of his
locker in the visitor's dressing room and had taken a deep breath.
He had a victory cigar in his left hand and his right arm wrapped
around his wife, Melanie.
</P>
<P>
   The goaltender whom some call the franchise had won his second
Stanley Cup in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some bumps along the way, but I'm so happy it's
over and I'm glad we're on the good side of it,'' Brodeur said.
``It was a great feeling that it took us five years to get back to
where we were supposed to be. Winning the cup every five years is
not so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for a few uninspiring moments, Brodeur was simply
brilliant in the playoffs, especially in the finals against Dallas.
Some thought that Brodeur, along with Jason Arnott, was as
deserving the Conn Smythe trophy, which goes to the most valuable
player in the tournament, as much Scott Stevens, the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur was so brilliant in the last four games _ the last two
in overtime _ against Dallas that he allowed only four goals while
facing 112 shots. His goaltending duel with Ed Belfour in Game 5,
which went into triple overtime, will go down as one of the best in
the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   With his 16 victories in the Stanley Cup playoffs, Brodeur tied
the record Philadelphia's Bernie Parent set in 1973-74 for most
victories in a season with 59.
</P>
<P>
   He was almost as happy about that accomplishment as winning the
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a statistic I will treasure,'' Brodeur said. ``You've
to to play a lot of games. It took me a lot of games to get to that
and number and I'm glad it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur played 72 games in the regular season, winning 43. He
played every minute in 23 playoff games and got his 16th victory
with a brilliant performance in Game 6. He also erased the stigma
of having previously lost all of his overtime playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing I didn't see it,'' Brodeur said of his 0-7
record, which was often flashed on television screens. ``I knew
about it, though, and I wanted to get it over with,'' he said.
``This is a great way to end it, by winning the Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur also played well in the sweep of Florida in the first
round and the elimination of Toronto in the second round, but he
struggled in the Eastern Conference finals against Philadelphia,
when the Devils rallied from being down by three games to one.
</P>
<P>
   SYKORA RETURNS WITH TEAM
</P>
<P>
   Petr Sykora came home with the team Sunday, after spending the
night in the hospital and recovering from a harrowing hit by Derian
Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   In the first period, Hatcher checked Sykora with so much
ferocity that the Czech forward lay on the ice motionless for
several minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart went out for him,'' said Jason Arnott, who scored the
game-winner in overtime. The players later brought the cup to
Sykora's room at Baylor University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora underwent a CAT scan that proved normal Saturday night,
but he was kept overnight for observation.
</P>
<P>
   After another CAT scan Sunday morning, Sykora was released and
allowed to travel to New Jersey with the team.
</P>
<P>
   After a charter flight to Teterboro Airport, the Devils went to
their Continental Arena offices Sunday afternoon to show the
Stanley Cup to family, friends and front-office personnel who did
not make the trip to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   LAMORIELLO QUIET ON FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   Lou Lamoriello, the Devils' president and general manager,
refused to answer specific questions about his future with the
team, which has been sold by John McMullen to YankeeNets for $175
million _ plus a $1 million bonus for winning the cup _ but he made
it clear he would stay with the team through the entry draft later
this month.
</P>
<P>
   The YankeeNets will officially take over the team on July 12 and
that group has expressed willingness to keep Lamoriello.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had not decided whose names would appear on the
Stanley Cup. He did say that Robbie Ftorek, who was replaced as
coach with eight games left in the regular season, was part of the
team and he deserved some praise. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
