watching the grass grow just to cut it down and watch it grow some
more. Perhaps it's just something about men and their motors. No
one has much of an explanation for why it is happening, other than
that it's cheap. But all across America, men have discovered new
thrills at the gears of the the riding lawn mower. From Bergholz
and Kisistom, N.Y. to Lubbock and Buda, Texas, men and the rare
woman are off to the races on souped-up, decal-coated John Deeres,
Snappers and Montgomery Wards with their blades removed and
whipping around tracks at speeds routinely exceeding 30 mph and
sometimes 60. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
