<SLUG> BC-CANADA-U.S.-ENERGY-888(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS LOOK NORTH AS ENERGY PRICES SOAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Alberta, Mass., Maine, N.Y.)   By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ As this summer's driving and air-conditioning
season unfolds, Americans may watch gasoline meters spin and
utility bills soar and be tempted to think bad thoughts about
energy princes in faraway Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the ditty dictates, why not blame Canada? Or, more
precisely, blame Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   With the deferential surreptitiousness that some Americans now
associate with their northern neighbor, Canada in the last decade
nearly doubled its oil exports and nearly tripled its natural gas
exports to the United States. Now Canada is definitively emerging
as the No. 1 energy supplier to the United States, the world's
largest energy importer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada is the largest total energy supplier to the United
States, greater than Saudi Arabia, Venezuela or Mexico,'' Gordon
Giffin, the U.S. ambassador to Canada, said here recently in a
speech to the Canadian Association of Petroleum Producers, an
industry group. The ambassador diplomatically did not note that oil
and gas imports this year account for a big part of the rising U.S.
trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
   With oil and natural gas prices doubling over the last year,
there are no apologies for $30 barrels of oil here in Alberta,
Canada's largest oil and gas producing province.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, this city, Canada's energy capital, is now
welcoming the World Petroleum Congress, a 54-nation association of
oil producing and consuming countries that is a forum for industry
leaders and energy technology experts. The five-day affair is
drawing 3,000 delegates and journalists, as well as protesters
against global warming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically our turn; commodity prices have been down for a
long time now,'' said J.C. Anderson, chief executive of Anderson
Exploration Ltd., a major gas producer. His voice carries not a
hint of apology, and his rural Nebraska twang reflects the new,
almost seamless North American energy market. ``This business has
become a continental game. That border is kaput,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   For the last decade, low prices depressed the profitability and
value of investments in Canada's oil patch. But in a radical
turnaround in the first quarter of this year, profits for Canada's
six largest oil and gas producers leaped 130-fold, hitting nearly
$500 million.
</P>
<P>
   With the oil and gas prices that are posted daily on front pages
here expected to remain strong through the winter, North America's
energy industry is slowly moving out of the shadow of the dot-com
high-technology economy. As investors rediscover that the Western
world still moves on oil and gas, takeover frenzy has swept this
city of corporate headquarters. In one week alone in April, there
were three takeover bids for energy companies here. With the United
States' capital markets about 40 times the size of Canada's, the
United States is pumping billions of new dollars into Canada's
energy industry.
</P>
<P>
   In Alberta, the highest natural gas prices in memory are helping
gas dethrone oil as the top fuel for exploration, production and
provincial royalty revenue.
</P>
<P>
   While oil is shuttled around the world in ships, natural gas
remains a ``terrestrial commodity,'' economically transported by
pipeline. A clean-burning fuel that produces less carbon dioxide
than coal or oil, natural gas is making Americans look north with
new respect.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly the fuel of choice for heating American homes,
natural gas is also the preferred fuel for electricity generation
instead of coal and nuclear power. Long bottled up here, Alberta
natural gas now flows through four new pipelines into the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to the end of that pipe, and it's the Brooklyn Navy
Yard,'' said Ralph Klein, Alberta's premier, whose government now
earns three times as much from natural gas royalties as from oil.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to a Con Edison gas-fueled electricity generating
plant, he added: ``Unbeknownst to most New Yorkers, New York is lit
up with Alberta natural gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Over this decade, American consumption of natural gas is
expected to increase by about 50 percent, to 33 trillion cubic feet
a year. For electricity generation alone, it is expected to double.
The hitch is that American natural gas production has declined by
about 5 percent since 1998. To the south, Mexico's state oil
company, Pemex, barely satisfies growing local use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be so tight on natural gas this summer that
people are going to say, `What are we going to do?''' said Thomas
A. Petrie, a Denver-based investment banker in the energy field.
``It's going to create a scramble for gas projects. We are going to
look all over the lower 48, but the big projects are going to be in
Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Anderson put it from his corner office in a
steel-and-glass tower here: ``We are going to have to drill the
pants off this basin. Then, we are going to have to go north.''
</P>
<P>
   American demand is growing so steadily that even if Canada's gas
exports increase 50 percent this decade, as forecast, Canada will
only be pacing American growth. And, even though the number of
exploration rigs in Alberta is jumping 50 percent this year,
geologists say that, after half a century of pumping from the Rocky
Mountain foothills, there is no more low-hanging fruit. The future
of North American gas production now lies in Canada's geographic
and climactic extremes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
