<HEADLINE>
CORA MAY BE SPARED TRIP TO MINORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers may have a way to solve their roster
crunch problems, at least for the short-term, without sending
promising young shortstop Alex Cora back to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   It centers around the improving health of Todd Hollandsworth.
Before the weekend, it appeared bleak Hollandsworth would return
for the Arizona series, but after a pair of very good recovery days
the outfielder believes he can return from his pulled right
hamstring Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   If Hollandsworth can return in the next few days, it changes the
Dodgers' thinking, a club official said. They're operating with
four healthy outfielders, and Hollandsworth's return would afford
the Dodgers the opportunity to send Shawn Gilbert back to Triple-A
Albuquerque when third baseman Adrian Beltre is activated, allowing
the Dodgers to remain with four outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre said his healing curve is leveling off, and he's hoping
for a mid-week activation from the 15-day disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not frustrated, but it's not like I feel better than
(Saturday), or the day before,'' said Beltre, who pulled his right
hamstring. ``It'staking a little longer.''The Dodgers want to keep
Cora around because he's playing so well. He had one hit against
the A's, is batting .309 and playing very well defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more prepared,'' Cora said. ``When I got sent down (May
20), Ifeel I gained the respect of my peers and teammates and the
repsect of the organization. I'm going to keep that. I'm not here
to be a band-aid.I'm here to do a job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are also expected to recall right-hander Orel
Hershiser from the minors during the Arizona series and place him
in the bullpen. Forgotten lefty Onan Masaoka, who threw two innings
in his first outing since June 3 Sunday against Oakland, could be
headed for Triple-A Albuquerque for the third time this season to
make room for Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all the rumblings surrounding Hershiser and his future
with the Dodgers, club officials are deadset with keeping him
around because of the impending suspensions. The cases will be
heard June 20-22 in Houston. Though appeals are in for everyone,
Chan Ho Park, Darren Dreifort and Eric Gagne are each slated to
serve three-game suspensions and Carlos Perez has a five-game
suspension hovering above him.
</P>
<P>
   Looking left: When the Dodgers were swept three games in Arizona
in May, the lack of a left-hander in the bullpen was an enormous
issue since the Diamondbacks lineup is filled with left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   In a 15-7 loss, manager Davey Johnson didn't have a lefty to
pitch in long relief and keep the score close. In the next two
games, the Dodgers were either tied or leading late only to watch
the right-handed bullpen eventually lose it. The bullpen was 0-2
with an 18.00 ERA in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Dodgers, Arizona left-handers feasted. Steve Finley
(5 for 13), Luis Gonzalez (7 for 13), Travis Lee (5 for 9) and Tony
Womack (5 for 17) hit a combined .423 with three homers, 16 RBI and
15 runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Dodgers didn't have right-hander Mike Fetters, who
is veryeffective against lefties, in that series. His availability
this time around, along with little-used lefty Onan Masaoka, could
help the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the reason I went on the disabled list, because
watching that series , we were undermanned,'' said Fetters, who's
allowed one hit in 22 at-bats against lefties. ``Because I can get
lefties out, Davey was probably pulling his hair out because he
couldn't use me.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Right-hander Gregg Olson will throw another
bullpen session today and is hoping to go on a rehab assignment
later this week. ...The Dodgers will pass the one million mark in
attendance today. After 38,733 attended Sunday's series finale with
Oakland, the season's attendance mark was 997,439.
</P>
</TEXT>
