 PERSONALS: The Fine Arts of Science and Technology 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news
file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
What kind of product would you like to see invented during the 21st
century? the Boyzone Web site asks  &UR; Shane Lynch &LR; , a member of the
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't tell you,'' he answers. ``The more inventions there
are, the lazier we get, in terms of everything being done for you.
You lose all your skills. I'm not too up for anything more being
invented, I don't think.''
</P>
<P>
   And what's the best invention of your lifetime? the 22-year-old
is asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most definitely the likes of entertainment, stuff like the
television, radio, that kind of stuff. Boyzone would have been in
trouble if those things hadn't been invented, I think. Other than
that, nothing really stands out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MELANCHOLY BABY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; rt, &LR; 10p10 _ ``What health or beauty aid would you take to
jail?'' Allure magazine asked.
</P>
