<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ETHIOPIA-MUSEUM-ART-6     06-11 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIA-MUSEUM-ART-695&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD MAN'S MUSEUM, STUFFED WITH MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia _ Some time when Sebatu Gebre Yesus was
young _ he cannot remember when _ he began collecting things. This
is unusual for at least two reasons. First, not many Ethiopians are
collectors. At 79, he claims to be the only one.
</P>
<P>
   Second, he is a collector who makes no distinction between the
priceless and the trashy. A pair of Baccarat chandeliers from the
palace of Emperor Haile Selassie sit not far from a souvenir
thermometer larded with a fat Napoleon. Bronzes from Benin, worth a
small fortune, are near a bongo with a split drumhead. He owns a
Monet, along with bizarre portraits of unknown children. He will
take orphaned runt or purebred, and love it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Favorites?'' asks Gebre Yesus, a trim man with a white goatee
and a neat gray suit that has three buttons. ``No difference to me.
I respect them all as good friends. But no preferences, like with
my children.''
</P>
<P>
   This makes a tour though Gebre Yesus' new museum _ opened to the
public in May after a lifetime in the making _ an eclectic
experience.
</P>
<P>
   It is apparently the only private collection in Ethiopia open to
the public, and if it were only a collection of Gebre Yesus'
fancies it would still be an interesting, certainly idiosyncratic,
addition to Ethiopia's heritage. (The steps leading to the museum,
for instance, are decorated with six bombs _ dressed up as planters
_ from the struggle with the Italians.)
</P>
<P>
   But the place has an emotional center: Gebre Yesus' troubled
relationship with the emperor, who was deposed in 1974, feeble and,
some say, senile, but who was considered a deity in parts of the
Caribbean. Gebre Yesus obtained the bed the emperor had _ it is
made of iron and gilt and is maybe 9 feet tall _ before he took the
crown in 1930. He has the emperor's lawn furniture, his bamboo
rocking chair, the heraldic regalia worn by his horse.
</P>
<P>
   And in the first room of the museum is a painting, which Gebre
Yesus recently commissioned, of himself standing in a courtroom
before the emperor. The room also has a series of works on
Ethiopia's defeat of the Italian army on the battlefield in 1896,
but this painting is definitely not about victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never on my side _ never,'' Gebre Yesus said, standing in
front of the painting. ``But still he used my services all the
time. It was a terrible time for me. Financially I was crushed. He
did it deliberately.''
</P>
<P>
   He had known the emperor since boyhood, because his sister was
married to the emperor's chauffeur. So the emperor made sure all
the children in the family were educated, and Gebre Yesus as a boy
had what he calls an ``active mind.'' He loved languages, and
learned English, French and Italian. He said the emperor begged him
to join the government but he refused. Still, he translated several
books _ one on English common law _ for the emperor.
</P>
<P>
   What he loved most was plants, and he became a landscaper (his
work is on display at the new and truly sumptuous Sheraton hotel in
Addis Ababa). He had a garden, where he bred the best-quality
plants and where the emperor went to relax, as documented in Gebre
Yesus' collection of photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Gebre Yesus, with eight children to feed, also dabbled in real
estate _ and that led to the problem with the emperor. The people
around Haile Selassie wanted Gebre Yesus' land and slowly, though
the machinery of the emperor's autocratic and centralized state, he
lost his holdings. The painting documents one of the legal
disputes, presided over by the emperor. Gebre Yesus lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me education, of course, and we had good family
relations,'' he said. ``But at the later stage he was a danger for
me. He was very unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gebre Yesus lived much longer, bought some of the emperor's
possessions _ including his baroque living-room furniture _ and now
is charging a token admission price for people to see it. Most of
the emperor's belongings, bought at auction here, are in the
Ethiopian heritage section _ one of 10 different parts of the
museum. The others include porcelain, household ornaments,
paintings, African art and Western art.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nearly every section is a tribute to the high and the low. There
are four dozen or so clocks, some ornately carved antiques, some
bland plastic. There are Ethiopian manuscripts and fine paintings
by modern Ethiopian artists, as well as a shelf with two stuffed
crocodiles, a lizard and a dusty hyena. He likes hats, coins,
miniatures, silverware, musical instruments, old Ethiopian crosses,
busts, books, maps, photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Gebre Yesus has an aversion to debt, so the museum was built
slowly over the last four and a half years. The house, built the
same slow way, is distinctive: a fortress with passageways, a
replica of an Ethiopian obelisk and a sculpture of Gebre Yesus
perched on a second story.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do it yourself, you can play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His collection came together over decades and followed no
particular course. He bought whatever he fancied, from the
Ethiopian countryside, from merchants, from markets in England or
France or West Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always very much interested in anything that attracted
my mind,'' he said. ``I never cared if it was precious or not, as
long as I liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   He is baffled that he has never met another Ethiopian with his
passion for collecting things. Around Africa, where most people are
poor, collecting is a rare pastime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wondered why other people didn't follow me in this
matter,'' he said. ``Not even my friends, my closest friends. They
don't care how much pleasure I feel in this. It is really
unbelievable, but they don't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a habit,'' he said on a tour of the museum. ``I can't
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   He can pause, however, and did so at an old phonograph with a
wooden crank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me show you,'' he said. He wound the crank. He had to
replace the needle, and his hands had trouble putting it into the
arm. After some work, the turntable began to move, the new needle
dropped and the voice of Nat King Cole, singing ``Too Young,'' spun
out of the phonograph horn at 78 rpm.
</P>
<P>
   Gebre Yesus smiled. The music was old and crackly, but lovely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
