<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-SUMMIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH KOREA STILL EXPECTS SUMMIT MEETING WITH NORTH TO PROCEED 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ South Korean officials remained confident
on Monday that the first-ever summit meeting with North Korea would
proceed normally on Tuesday after an unexpected 24-hour delay by
Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   North Korean officials surprised their southern counterparts on
Sunday with a request for the delay of the three-day meeting for
unspecified ``minor technical reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   The postponement set off rife speculation over the cause, with
analysts here focusing on security arrangements, the death of
President Hafez Assad in Syria, a longtime ally, or matters as
mundane as the erratic electricity supply and telecommunications
networks in the North Korean capital, Pyongyang, where the meeting
is to be held.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a half-century of military hostilities and fierce
ideological competition between the two countries, not to mention
the north's renowned unpredictability, officials here said they had
few doubts that the delay would prove to be only a momentary
setback.
</P>
<P>
   Among other reasons for this confidence, they cited the presence
of a 30-member advance team already in North Korea. ``We will
definitely go on Tuesday,'' said Moon Chung-in, an academic who is
part of the official southern delegation. ``There is no major
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's first leader, Kim Il Sung, died in July 1994, just
days before the only other previously scheduled summit meeting
between the two countries, and the gulf between the two countries
widened dramatically in the ensuing years. Just last year, the two
countries engaged in a fierce naval skirmish in the Yellow Sea
raising anew the prospect of war across the world's most heavily
armed border.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said, though, that the uncharacteristically intense
recent diplomatic activity by North Korea was the best gauge of its
seriousness about engaging the south, and lifting the country's
reclusive veil.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the North Korean president, Kim Jong Il paid
a surprise visit to China, his first trip to another country since
he succeeded his father. Since then, Kim has invited the Russian
leader, Vladimir Putin, for a visit to Pyongyang that is expected
to take place in July.
</P>
<P>
   Pyongyang has also been busy recently establishing diplomatic
relations with a wide-range of non-traditional partners, ranging
from Italy to Australia. Talks aimed at restoring or establishing
ties with other countries are proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the summit, Washington announced that it could
soon lift most of the economic sanctions that remain in place
against North Korea, most of which are tied to the country's
status, according the State Department, as a supporter of terrorist
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that something important is going on here, and the
North-South meeting is obviously the centerpiece,'' said one senior
Western diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to say just how far or how fast this will all
proceed, but to not have spoken to someone for 50 years, and then
be seated at the same table is itself historic.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, a major concern of the South Korean government in
recent days has been controlling high public expectations over the
first meeting between leaders of the divided country.
</P>
<P>
   In briefing after briefing, South Korean officials have stressed
that the summit meeting should be seen as only the beginning of
what they hope will be regular, high-level contacts between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The two presidents, Kim Dae-jung and Kim Jong Il, are expected
to meet at least twice during the three-day summit, and there have
been persistent but unconfirmed reports of a reciprocal visit by
the North Korean leader to Seoul in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   In a reflection of the huge differences that separate the
countries, the agenda for the talks has been left deliberately
vague. The South Korean leadership would like to achieve something
that lowers military tensions on the peninsula, ultimately
including a pledge by Pyongyang to foreswear nuclear weapons
development.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Seoul's main allies, the United States and Japan,
have pressed for emphasis on reducing the threat from North Korea's
ballistic missile program.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions in this regard rose sharply in 1998, when Pyongyang
made a surprise test launch of a long-range Taepodong II missile
that overflew the main Japanese island of Honshu.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, North Korea can be expected to make renewed
demands for the withdrawal of the approximately 37,000 American
troops based in the south.
</P>
<P>
   After suffering years of disastrous shrinking of its economy
following the loss of its Soviet-bloc allies, Pyongyang is also
eager to receive a large increase in economic assistance and
investment from the far richer south.
</P>
<P>
   Seoul has already promised large amounts of development
assistance to Pyongyang in exchange for a real detente. And
southern companies, many of whose leaders are flying to Pyongyang
in the 130-member presidential delegation, are eager to expand
their presence in the north.
</P>
<P>
   To do so dramatically, however, will require new agreements on
everything from technology transfer and legal protections from
expropriation to monetary exchange and ordinary banking procedures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
