u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-PLAYERS-NY     06-11 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PLAYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYKORA'S ALARMING SCREAM IN HOSPITAL IS ONE OF JOY  

</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Devils Coach Larry Robinson made his way
off the bus and through the crowd at the Meadowlands, carrying the
Stanley Cup in front of him like a battering ram as pushed through
the doors to the Devils offices. He was also dragging a Neiman
Marcus bag, the spoils of an enjoyable trip to Dallas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robinson propped the cup on the reception desk, where it
immediately became the gathering spot for pictures as members of
the Devils' organization posed next to the prize. But no players
stepped inside, instead descending from the bus, exhausted, most
rushing to the their cars and the exit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few lingered, like Scott Stevens, who stood in the middle of
the traffic, holding his Conn Smythe Trophy while the small crowd
of fans, friends and family congratulated him and posed for
pictures, too. But most of the players just seemed to want to get
home after an exhausting finish to the Stanley Cup Finals in the
early morning hours with a 2-1 double-overtime victory over the
Dallas Stars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had gotten little sleep, reveling in the joy of their
second Stanley Cup in five years as they celebrated. Jason Arnott,
who scored the game-winning goal, hoisted the cup one more time
when the team plane landed at Teterboro Airport. As cars rushed by,
he was the last to leave Sunday. Asked how exhausting the last
stretch of the season had been, with a triple-overtime game on
Thursday, a flight to Dallas, and then the double-overtime victory,
he laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't even want to know,'' Arnott said. ``Now it's time to
kick our feet up.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arnott was one of a few players who took the celebration to a
Dallas hospital hours after the game was over, carrying the Cup to
teammate Petr Sykora, who had been injured in the first period on
Saturday night and was kept overnight for observation.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora's seemed fine as a CAT scan conducted when he arrived at
the hospital, as well as another one he received Sunday morning,
showed no problems other than the headache he still had as he got
into his black Corvette and drove away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fine,'' said Devils General Manager Lou Lamoriello.
``Larry and I went right after the game to see him. A little story
which I think is great; when we got there, they had him monitored
and he was left quiet, but he had a television watching the game.
When we scored in overtime, he screamed and they all went running
to the room. They thought something was the matter and he woke up
everyone around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent some time with him, then we left and a half-dozen
players took the cup to the hospital.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The small, but enthusiastic crowd gathered outside the Devils
offices Sunday, lining the walkway to the door and spreading into
the parking lot as the players made their getaway. Some, mostly the
veterans who knew just how special this moment was, stayed to enjoy
it as long as they could. It was most likely no coincidence that
two of the last players to leave were Stevens and Ken Daneyko, who
had been among the nine players who were also part of the Devils
other Stanley Cup Champion team in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good core of fans that really support our team,''
Stevens said. ``They're always there for us, which is nice.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daneyko added: ``I think this one is a little bit sweeter. The
first one a whirlwind. You don't know how to react. It's just very
tiring. Besides playing into overtime, there was a lot of
celebrating. The guys had a great time, a lot of fun together. It
was something special, something I'll treasure the rest of my life.
I really appreciate it the second time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty fortunate, along with eight other guys on this club
who've won it twice in two tries. And to win it in grueling fashion
after losing in three overtimes is special. We have a lot of heart
and soul guys.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the players will likely reconvene with a similar group for
the start of camp next year, with only one player _ Claude Lemieux
_ an unrestricted free agent, just who will be guiding them is
uncertain. The team has already been sold by owner John McMullen to
the YankeeNets group, a transaction that will be final next month.
McMullen, who will get an additional $1 million on the sale price
of the Devils for winning the Stanley Cup, was unable to accompany
the team to Dallas because of a back problem, but greeted them on
the tarmac at Teterboro. And Lamoriello has not stated yet whether
he will remain with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, what I'd like to do is enjoy what we've
accomplished right now,'' Lamoriello said. ``And then we'll look at
this team at the appropriate time. Everybody is a part of what's
transpired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes decisions and focuses are in one individual area,
but this is an organization that belongs to the players and
everyone involved. There's not one MVP.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
