<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASE-GOODEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PITCHING SHORTAGE BENEFITS GOODEN  

</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ And for their next magic act, the Yankees will
resurrect Dwight Gooden and turn him into a major league pitcher
again.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden, George Steinbrenner's latest reclamation project, has
signed a minor league contract to continue playing baseball after
the Houston Astros sent him to Tampa Bay this season and the Devil
Rays released him.
</P>
<P>
   Some players would take the hint and find another means of
employment or recreation. Gooden, however, is convinced he can
still pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess Doc feels he can still do it, especially the way
pitching is now in baseball,'' John Franco, the Mets' relief
pitcher and a former teammate, said Sunday. ``It's so scarce and
not so good. Can't be any worse than what's out there already.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco spoke before the Mets and the Yankees concluded the Bronx
half of their interleague and intracity competition. Gooden played
for both teams, starring for the Mets, pitching creditably at times
for the Yankees. The Mets did not see any reason to prolong his
career. The Yankees' owner is always ready to give a guy another
chance, a last chance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As deftly as he locates his pitches on a good day, Franco put
his finger precisely on why the Dwight Goodens are dragged off
baseball's scrap heap and tossed back into the arena like so many
ancient gladiators. Baseball is suffering from so serious a
pitching shortage that teams will try anything and anyone. It used
to be that left-handed pitchers were the ones who seemed to have a
lifetime guarantee of a job in the major leagues. Now right-handers
are getting their share of jobs because of the desperate need that
teams have for pitching.
</P>
<P>
   By signing Gooden to a minor league contract, the Yankees don't
really risk anything. He can take classes at their Tampa complex,
then undergo tests in minor league games. There they can experiment
with him pitching out of the bullpen, an experience that he
basically has avoided in his 16-year career, relieving only seven
times in his 412-game career.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a question that maybe we'll answer, either in Tampa or
Columbus,'' Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, said.
``I'm not sure. Just looking at it from my standpoint, I think it
would be worthwhile finding out.''
</P>
<P>
   It's what Gooden can do at all that is in serious question. Both
the Astros and the Devil Rays are managed by former pitchers, one
who also served as pitching coach for the 1997 World Series
champion Florida Marlins. If Larry Dierker and Larry Rothschild
thought Gooden could still pitch effectively in the major leagues,
he would not be taking remedial courses in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I saw was average stuff,'' Dierker said Sunday by
telephone from San Diego, ``the kind of stuff if you're going to
pitch at the major league level, you have to have good control. You
see guys like Bob Tewksbury not throwing real hard and not having
great sinking action but placing the ball where they want it and
having good off-speed stuff. If he gets to the point where he has
that kind of command, he can be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Devil Rays, said a member of their organization, Gooden
was not the ``same pitcher that everyone remembers.'' But then, he
hasn't been since early in the 90s with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a good breaking ball; his slider had really improved,''
the Tampa Bay employee said. ``But he lost power off his hard
curveball and that made his fastball less effective. He just
couldn't get away with any mistakes. The home runs were pretty
pronounced.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooden gave up 15 home runs in 40 2/3 innings innings with the
two teams, including 9 in his last 15 2/3 for the Devil Rays. The
Yankees clubbed three home runs against him in 4 1/3 innings last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made mistakes and we got him for a couple three-run
homers,'' Stottlemyre said. ``But it looks like he still has
something in his arm.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gooden allowed 17.5 base runners per nine innings in nine starts
with the Astros and the Devil Rays and emerged with a career-high
6.86 earned run average. Opposing teams battered him for a .319
batting average and a .645 slugging percentage. If the 35-year-old
right-hander doesn't make it back to the majors with the benevolent
Yankees or any other team grasping onto the nearest experienced
arm, those will be the final figures on his year-by-year record.
</P>
<P>
   Are players embarrassed by such performances, or can they shrug
them off as simply having a few bad games that a little more work
would overcome?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a time and a place for a player at a certain age to
step back and say, `Hey, I've had enough and that's it,''' Franco
said. ``But it's hard to walk away when you're so used to doing
something for 12, 15 years. Sometimes it might take an
embarrassment to say, `I've had enough.'''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't passing judgment on Gooden or commenting on his desire
to continue pitching, just explaining the way a player in Gooden's
circumstance thinks and acts. What Franco didn't say was that often
the player is the last one to know he is finished. These days, on
the other hand, teams don't always know it either.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about the possibility of sending Gooden to the minors
when he was with the Astros, Dierker said: ``I don't think we could
have gotten him to the minor leagues. With the pitching shortage
that exists, we probably would have put him on release waivers and
somebody would have claimed him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
