<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-SPOOF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY, CARPETBAG IN HAND, GETS LAST WORD AT PRESS DINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ After months of being skewered for moving to New
York to run for the U.S. Senate, Hillary Rodham Clinton _ carpetbag
in hand _ joined in on the joke on Saturday during an evening of
satirical skits and songs.
</P>
<P>
   The night of political spoofing, held by the Albany press corps,
included a sketch that, sung to the tune of ``The Lady Is a
Tramp,'' satirized Clinton's decision to run for office in New
York: ``She changes viewpoints like three times an hour. Her only
interest is grabbing some power.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton had the last word at the annual Legislative
Correspondents Association dinner, a black-tie affair during which
some of the state's prominent politicians take some brutal ribbing
from the news reporters who cover them daily.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton took the stage at the end, carrying a carpetbag. ``I'm
just like every other New Yorker with Secret Service protection,''
the first lady told an audience of more than 500 people who
frequently broke out in laughter during her 20-minute rebuttal
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who moved into the Westchester community of Chappaqua a
few months ago, then presented a slide show of her life titled
``The Woman From Chappaqua.'' In each frame _ whether as an infant
or as an adult meeting Pope John Paul II _ Clinton was pictured
wearing a New York Yankees cap.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislative Correspondents Association, composed of scores
of the state capital's current and former reporters, has put on the
show every year since 1900. The event is usually off the record,
but this year, the organization's members voted to put it on the
record because of the intense interest in Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is looking to fill the seat that is being vacated this
year by Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat who is retiring. Her
Republican opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island, attended the
show as well, but did not speak.
</P>
<P>
   His aides said his late entry into the race _ which came after
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York dropped out of the campaign last
month to undergo treatment for prostate cancer _ had left them with
insufficient time to prepare remarks for the appearance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0146 </DOCNO>
