<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-REPUBLICANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEELING VULNERABLE, REPUBLICANS NUDGE N.Y. SENATE TO LEFT  

</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Joseph L. Bruno, the Republican majority leader,
struggled to explain why the State Senate was about to pass a
hate-crimes bill, which he and his colleagues had blocked since the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno dismissed the bill as symbolism, a measure that would do
nothing to fight crime, though he acknowledged its popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we're in a business where times change,'' he said.
``We're contemplating doing something with gun safety, and you
know, three months ago, or a year ago, or three years ago, that's
not anything we would contemplate. Times change, and I think we
have to stay flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   No faction in New York politics has changed more of late than
the State Senate. The Senate Republicans, a bulwark of the state
machinery that has had a vise grip for decades, look on this year's
election with greater fear than they have felt since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   They see a presidential election in which most polls show Al
Gore swamping George W. Bush in New York. They see an entire state,
and some battleground districts, that have become more heavily
Democratic. They see a voter rebellion against the Republican Party
in Nassau County. And they see the Senate Democrats, long a
punching bag who often failed to muster opponents to Republican
incumbents in swing districts, fielding the strongest team of
challengers in memory.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several months, the Senate Republicans, long a
redoubt of conservatism in a liberal state, have made a march
leftward, approving legislation that it would have been hard to
imagine them accepting a few years ago. Each measure appealed to
moderate and liberal voters in New York City and its suburbs, where
the most vulnerable Republican senators are, or placated crucial
interest groups like labor unions or the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, for the first time, the Senate passed a bill
providing increased penalties for crimes motivated by hatred of any
of several groups, with 24 of 36 Republicans voting in favor. Among
the protected classes of victims listed in the bill are gays and
lesbians, a step that Bruno and many of his colleagues had said
they would not take.
</P>
<P>
   Since last fall, the Senate has passed a bill making it a crime
to block access to abortion clinics, a bill creating a major new
health-care entitlement program for the working poor, a
55-cents-a-pack increase in the cigarette tax, a bill requiring
that all cigarettes meet fire safety standards, and a bill
restricting companies' ability to sell air pollution ``credits''
that, in effect, give polluters the right to violate clean air
standards.
</P>
<P>
   In recent budget talks, it was the Senate Republicans who
championed state-subsidized prescription drugs for the elderly and
an important tax credit for the poor. And with just a few days left
in this year's legislative session, Senate leaders are seriously
considering passing a broad package of gun controls, approving an
increase in the state minimum wage from $5.15 to $6.75, and giving
retired government workers automatic annual pension increases for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the new left-wing Senate,'' said Sen. Martin Connor of
Brooklyn, the Democratic minority leader. ``The mood across the
aisle seems pretty grim. They're really worried about their
survival, and the legislative result is they're rushing to adopt
the Democratic agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican senators have privately teased each other about their
new liberal credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see them acting very nervously, and I see them making a lot
of mistakes because of it,'' said Michael L. Long, chairman of the
state's Conservative Party. ``In their fear and their desire to
stay in control, they're acting like there's no difference between
Republicans and Democrats, and passing a lot of far-left
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes in control of the Senate are enormous. With Democrats
firmly in control of the assembly, a Democratic majority in the
Senate could form a unified legislative front in taking on Gov.
George E. Pataki, a Republican, over budgets and other issues. They
could begin sending the governor bills, like an overhaul of the
campaign finance laws, that have been bottled up in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate majority controls several hundred patronage jobs, and
many of those people become campaign foot soldiers when it is time
to circulate petitions, arrange rallies and get out the vote. Those
jobs also provide a breeding ground for candidates for local and
legislative offices.
</P>
<P>
   This year's elections are particularly crucial because the next
Senate will draw the district lines for the next decade. In a state
where registered Democrats outnumber Republicans 5 million to 3.1
million, the Republicans have maintained control of the Senate
largely through the power to carve out as many favorable districts
as possible themselves. Political analysts say nonpartisan or
pro-Democrat redistricting would give Democrats solid control of
the chamber for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hold a 36-to-25 edge in the Senate, and even the
Democrats acknowledge they have no better than an outside shot of
picking up the six seats needed to take control. A shift in power
is rare; the Assembly last changed hands in the Democrats'
post-Watergate sweep of 1974, and the Senate has had a Republican
majority for all but one year since 1938.
</P>
<P>
   But even knocking off three Republican senators could make it
hard for Bruno to control legislation on which there are a few
dissenters in his party. It could also persuade political
contributors who now heavily favor Republicans to start hedging
their bets and give to Democrats, too.
</P>
<P>
   The great wild card in this year's races is Nassau County, where
Republicans outnumber Democrats by a wide margin. Will voter anger
last until November, and will it spill over from local contests to
state races? At this point, no one can do more than guess.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Pataki, a fellow Republican, has helped put the Senate
Republicans on the spot, siding with legislation opposed by
conservatives, rather than giving them a powerful ally in a united
front. He was a major architect of the health-care program and the
cigarette tax, and he has called for gun control and hate-crimes
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are also worried about the loss of Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani as their party's candidate for the United States Senate.
Giuliani had been expected to fare well in the city and its
suburbs, which could have helped Republicans down the ticket, and
it remains to be seen how Rep. Rick A. Lazio will do as his
replacement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
