<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-BUICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAULSON ENDS HIS LONG WAIT WITH A VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ After four holes of a sudden-death playoff, a
47-minute weather delay and 102 starts on the PGA Tour without a
victory, Dennis Paulson finally tasted triumph Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Making a superb up-and-down on the final hole, Paulson won the
Buick Classic on the fourth playoff hole, sinking a 4-foot putt to
win after David Duval missed a 5-footer. Paulson's first career
victory came the hard way, against a star-studded leader board on a
demanding Westchester Country Club course that served as a prelude
to this week's United States Open.
</P>
<P>
   It ended on the par-4, 374-yard 17th hole, when Paulson turned
the tables on Duval. Duval reached the front of the green in two
shots, as Paulson's second shot went long, into the deep rough
behind the green. But after Duval lagged his first putt 5 feet from
the hole, Paulson hit a magnificent chip to 4 feet, and Duval then
missed his putt. That opened the door for Paulson, who made his par
put to win the first-place check worth $540,000.
</P>
<P>
   Paulson (65-68-75-68), who started the day two strokes off the
lead, and Duval (70-67-70-69) were eight under for the tournament
(276), one stroke ahead of Sergio Garcia of Spain, who finished
third after losing a three-shot lead on the back nine. Greg Norman
was fourth at six under, his best finish since last year's British
Open.
</P>
<P>
   But for Paulson, who lost last year's Buick Classic in a playoff
with Duffy Waldorf, the feeling of victory was almost
indescribable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still hasn't hit me yet,'' said Paulson, a 37-year-old
Californian who spent years playing on the Asian and Nike tours.
``It's going to be fun going to Pebble Beach and to be a bigger
part of the story, instead of just another guy teeing up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a difficult loss for Duval, the world's No. 2-ranked
player, who has not won since April 1999. He said he was not sure
what happened on his final putt, the missed 5-footer. ``I don't
know if I pulled it, or just hit a bad putt, or if it just broke
more than I thought,'' he said. ``I just missed.''
</P>
<P>
   On the third playoff hole, Duval made a terrific putt, a
40-footer uphill for birdie on the par-5, 526-yard No. 18 that
nearly won the tournament. But Paulson answered with a pressure
putt, a 6-footer for birdie that forced play to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Paulson's putter was good to him all day. He earned his way into
the playoff by making a sensational 35-foot putt for birdie during
regulation at No. 18, which put him in the clubhouse at eight under
par before the 47-minute delay. Duval was two groups behind
Paulson, still on the course at eight under. But he missed birdie
opportunities on the final two holes of regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Duval missed a 10-foot putt for birdie at No. 17. Then, after
his tee shot at No. 18 landed in the fairway, the horn blew to
suspend play because of lightning. After resuming play, Duval hit
his second shot at No. 18, a 3-iron that hit the rock-hard green
and bounced into the deep rough. Duval failed to get up-and-down
from there, settled for par and headed into the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   The day started with Waldorf leading at seven under par, a
stroke ahead of seven players: Phil Mickelson, Ernie Els, Chris
Perry, John Cook, Joey Sindelar, Skip Kendall and Duval. But most
of those contenders faltered on the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Garcia was in excellent position, storming to a
three-stroke lead after 10 holes by making five birdies. He drove
the green on two par-4 holes _ the 326-yard No. 7 and the 314-yard
No. 10. Both of those prodigious drives led to two-putt birdies,
and Garcia left the 10th green three strokes ahead of Duval, Perry
and Sindelar.
</P>
<P>
   But at No. 10, momentum began to swing from the 20-year-old
Garcia and toward Paulson and Duval. Garcia had a 12-foot putt for
eagle at No. 10 but was distracted by a photographer's camera just
as he was about to strike the ball. He backed away and glared at
the cameraman, then missed the putt and settled for a birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Things soon got worse for Garcia. He pulled his tee shot well
left at No. 11, into the rough and under a tree. Instead of playing
a safer shot and chipping back into the fairway, Garcia tried to
hit a low 5-iron under the trees toward the hole. His club clipped
a branch on his backswing, and he advanced the ball only about 40
yards, still in the deep rough. His next shot landed just short of
the green, and after chipping 8 feet right of the hole, Garcia
missed the putt and double-bogeyed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Paulson made a 22-footer for birdie at No. 11,
pulling him into a tie for the lead with Garcia. Garcia made a
costly bogey at No. 17 to fall to six under, and even a birdie at
No. 18 kept him one hole out of the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Garcia, who shot a 65 Saturday and a 68 Sunday after
barely making the cut, was pleased with his best finish of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows I'm still the same guy as last year,'' said Garcia,
the runner-up at last year's PGA Championship by one stroke to
Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time in his career, Paulson won an event on
the tour. Asked what it meant, Paulson had a ready answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' he said, ``that I'm going to be able to move into my
new house now, no problem.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
