<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN AFFAIRS: UNFINISHED BUSINESS IN SYRIA 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is Hafez Assad's legacy? How should his epitaph read?
That's an easy one. His gravestone should read: ``Hafez Assad,
feared and ferocious President of Syria: He stayed too long and he
died too soon.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Hafez Assad _ for years the Middle East leader most
incapable of change, and then, finally, when he realized that
change was mandatory if he wanted to turn over a stable Syria to
his son, Bashar, he bowed out before getting the really hard stuff
done.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look closely at Assad's ambiguous reign. What do we mean
he stayed too long? Well, in the fall of 1977, just before going to
Jerusalem, President Anwar Sadat of Egypt went to Damascus to meet
with Assad and encourage him to follow Egypt's lead with Israel.
Assad refused, and he spent the next 23 years resisting the
Egyptian approach, and then trying to prove that he could get more
from Israel and give less.
</P>
<P>
   And what does Assad have to show for those 23 years? Not much.
At best he will remembered for what he didn't do, not for any
positive accomplishments: He did not, in his eyes, ``sell out'' to
Israel. He did not meet the embarrassing end of other Soviet-era
dictators who were toppled by popular movements. With his brutal
fist, he did not let ethnically divided Syria fall into civil war
like Lebanon. He did not, like Saddam Hussein, allow himself to be
sucked into a devastating war with the world's only superpower. He
did not lose Syria's grip over Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   So many ``He did nots.'' But not a lot of ``He dids.'' By any
normal criteria, Assad would have to be judged one of the most
overrated leaders ever. Economically, Syria today is a backwater _
the last country in the Middle East to introduce fax machines and
the Internet, a country with a crumbling industrial base, a
corrupt, 19th-century banking system, an utterly backward
educational system and not a single world-class export of any
product or service. If Syria were in Asia, it would be called North
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, though, Assad finally got the message _ that he
had to modernize and open the country. And one of the people
whispering that most often to him was his son and designated heir,
Bashar. So Assad started bulldozing the road, but he left three
huge boulders _ boulders that would have been difficult for even
him to move, but will be even harder for his son, an eye doctor,
who starts with much less legitimacy and none of his father's
godfather-like skills at destroying enemies without mercy.
</P>
<P>
   The first and biggest boulder left for Bashar is modernizing
Syria and shifting the base of Syrian unity from the war with
Israel to building a 21st-century state. President Assad had begun
that task last year with a series of internal purges, but it was
slow going. Assad was ambivalent about opening Syria's windows, and
he had created so many competing power centers, spying agencies and
military units _ all of which reported to him and all of which he
played against one another _ that when he initially tried to turn
things over to his son, some of those power centers resisted. So
father and son started purging: Former Prime Minister Mahmoud Zubi
killed himself last month after being sent for trial on corruption
charges. Former army chief Hikmat Chehabi also was targeted on
corruption charges. But this is an unfinished war, and Bashar will
not consolidate his rule, or be able to push his reform agenda,
without winning some cock fights with other Syrian roosters.
</P>
<P>
   The second bit of unfinished business is the peace with Israel.
Assad refused any compromise with Israel on the Golan, even when
only 200 yards were left in dispute. He also refused to show any
warmth to the Israeli people. Will Bashar be able to summon the
strength and legitimacy to offer compromises his father would not,
but which are essential for any deal with Israel?
</P>
<P>
   The last bit of unfinished business was Lebanon. Israel's
unilateral pullout from south Lebanon has naturally triggered
questions in Lebanon: If the Israelis are gone, why is the Syrian
army still here? Bashar will eventually have to work out a new
basis for Syria's continued presence in Lebanon. Not easy.
</P>
<P>
   It is rather fitting that Hafez Assad died in mid-conversation
on the phone with the president of Lebanon. Because in many ways he
was also in mid-conversation with the people of Syria and Israel as
well. These were conversations too late in coming. Bashar will now
have to finish the calls. I wonder what he'll say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
