<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESSAY: THE REJECTIONIST 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If you want to make a list of the Syrian dictator
Hafez Assad's good deeds, begin with this: He was an enemy of
Iraq's Saddam Hussein. That's where the list ends.
</P>
<P>
   On the debit side of his life's ledger can be included his eager
alliance with Soviet Communism; his slaughter of thousands of
dissident Syrians in Hama; his avid support of terrorists
worldwide; his military occupation of neighboring Lebanon; and most
consuming of all, his abiding hatred of Israel, which made Assad
the Arab world's most relentless rejectionist.
</P>
<P>
   At his funeral Tuesday, crocodile tears will flow from Yasser
Arafat, long the object of Assad's contempt, who must be delighted
at having outlived his tormentor.
</P>
<P>
   Western leaders will proclaim respect for ``stability'' provided
by such dictators-for-life. Groping for ways not to speak ill of
the dead, they will note that once Assad grudgingly made an
agreement, he ``kept his word'' by sealing his side of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Wisely, Bill Clinton decided to bypass this chance at wearing
his inimitable lip-biting mournful look, and won't dispatch Vice
President Al Gore, his normal substitute, to Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because three months ago, at a much-touted meeting in
Geneva, Clinton presented Assad with the Golan Heights on a silver
platter. The Syrian then humiliated the supplicating American by
refusing to take yes for an answer, making fresh demands for
control of Galilee that embarrassed not only Clinton but even the
most appeasement-prone doves in Jerusalem. Assad scuttled
negotiations in the most dramatic way possible.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, an unelected official, the secretary of state, will
represent the United States at the state funeral of a world figure;
That deliberate diplomatic slight will not be lost on Middle East
leaders or American voters.
</P>
<P>
   Does the dictator's demise help or harm the processing of peace?
It helps.
</P>
<P>
   Short-term, this week's attempt to transfer power to his son,
Bashar, means that the ``Syrian track'' is derailed for at least
this year. That delay is not a matter for hand-wringing. On the
contrary, the implacable Hafez was pressing the Israeli prime
minister, Ehud Barak, into a corner that might have resulted in
Israelis, in a referendum, voting to turn down a deal that would
deliver the high ground in return for treaty promises.
</P>
<P>
   Longer-term, the absence of Assad will help because the dictator
was driven by pride to recapture in negotiation every inch of land
he lost in foolish early aggressions. That intensely personal
motive for self-justification is gone. Several scenarios now
present themselves:
</P>
<P>
   1.  &UR; Worst case: anarchy in Syria. &LR;  The Assads come from a
religious minority, the Alawites; the majority Sunnis may want to
take over. The dictator also struck a balance among his military,
his spy service and his political party; his 34-year old son,
figurehead of the regime's insiders, may not have the manipulative
cunning of a father who in the end could be expected to make
neither peace nor war. Anarchy could lead to coups, riots, a
reckless lashing-out at Israel, rapprochement with Saddam. Hebrew
University president Itamar Rabinovich, expert on Syria, tells me
he's concerned that ``the days of predictability may be over.''
</P>
<P>
   2.  &UR; Less bad case: a balance of internal powers behind a
dictator who needs to make peace to survive. &LR;  If not Bashar, this
could be a militarist or politician able to establish internal
order _ ``stability'' _ without Hama-style massacres. Economic
incentives might induce him to bring home 30,000 troops from
Lebanon as Iran's Hezbollah is induced to leave.
</P>
<P>
   3.  &UR; Best case: The young man leads angry, backward Syria into
the modern world. &LR;  Bashar is an ophthalmologist, educated by London
eye doctors. He heads the computer society in a socialist land too
worried about dissent to permit Internet access to anybody beyond
the elite. With initial investment from Saudis and the emirates,
and with a little canniness and a lot of luck, he could introduce
the rudiments of market reform and prosperity to a freedom-parched
land. It's wishful thinking, but that's how a real peace could take
hold.
</P>
<P>
   As newscasters learn to pronounce ``ophthalmologist'' (first two
syllables are ``ahf'' and ``thal'') Syrians will adjust to life
after Hafez. To succeed, whoever follows him must reject a life of
rejection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
