<SLUG> BC-EXP-SYRIA-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSAD'S DEATH LEAVES ISRAEL CALM BUT UNCERTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
    (EDS: This article is part of TIMES EXPRESS. It is a condensed
version of a story that will appear in tomorrow's New York Times.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli leaders proclaimed on Sunday that the death
of President Hafez Assad of Syria had ushered in a new era or at
least ushered out an old one in the Middle East. But no one could
predict what that portended beyond a potentially problematic
transition period.
</P>
<P>
   There was no mourning, no celebration of the death and no
re-assessment here of an Arab leader familiar to generations of
Israelis as a sworn enemy of their state, yet one who inspired
sometimes ambivalent feelings as a cunning leader and a worthy
adversary, too.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most agreed with Nahum Barnea, the dean of newspaper
columnists, who wrote Sunday morning: ``We Israelis have no reason
to shed any tears over the death of Hafez Assad. It's a waste of
water.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Israelis expressed the hope that positive change would
prove inevitable. ``Assad's successor is the times and not any one
man,'' said Shimon Peres, Israel's minister for regional affairs.
``Because if his successor doesn't adapt himself to the times,
Syria will remain a very poor and isolated country in a very
difficult situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Some worried aloud that Syria would degenerate into chaos, which
could destabilize Lebanon, and spread violence into Israel. But
more said wishfully that Assad's death could help Syria shed its
insularity, open up to the West and perhaps even lose what is
perceived here as its intransigence in pursuing peace.
</P>
<P>
   They also noted hopefully that Assad's designated successor, his
34-year-old son Bashar, was educated in England, that he heads
Syria's computer society, and that he is not bound by the same
personal entanglements in history. Bashar Assad was just two years
old in 1967, when Syria, with his father as defense minister, lost
the Golan Heights to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the widespread calm here, the Tel Aviv stock
exchange, usually a good barometer of geopolitical anxiety,
registered barely a flutter. And the Israeli military, after a
24-hour alert, reported quiet on Israel's northern borders and said
that no new forces would be deployed.
</P>
<P>
   In the Maariv newspaper on Sunday, Chemi Shalev wrote: ``Life
without Hafez, after all these years, is an unknown, and we will
all have to go through a weaning period. But along with the worry
there is also room for hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, Assad was a bitter enemy who cast a giant shadow
over the entire Middle East. This morning, now that he's gone, we
can see the sun once more, even if it is blinding at present.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
