<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ENID NEMY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   Recently my French-born son-in-law, Hubert Laisney, accompanied
by our daughter Julie, went to Cadman Plaza in Brooklyn for his
swearing-in ceremony for American citizenship. My wife and I were
asked to baby-sit for our grandchildren _ Luke, 4, and Cybele, 15
months _ to whom Hubert always speaks in French. We entertained
Luke by repeatedly reminding him that his father was on a very
important mission, that he was to become an American on that day.
</P>
<P>
   We prepared a celebration in the evening and even hung an
American flag in the window. When Hubert arrived and greeted his
son, Luke turned to us and said in complete astonishment, ``But he
still speaks French!''
</P>
<P>
   _ JOSEPH A. SKALA
</P>
<P>
   How to get a taxi, sometimes: Susan Crowley-Gerame, visiting
midtown Manhattan, took the advice of friends and went to Eighth
Avenue to get a taxi to the airport. After 35 minutes of vainly
searching for a cab, she gave up and proceeded to plan B. She
crossed to a side street and analyzed the passengers in cabs that
were stopping for a light.
</P>
<P>
   One cab held what she considered the perfect person, a
well-dressed woman who, Crowley-Gerame guessed _ correctly, it
turned out _ was going only a short distance. She knocked on the
window, the woman rolled it down and Crowley-Gerame put forth her
proposition. If she could jump in the cab, Crowley-Gerame would pay
the woman's fare to her destination and then proceed to the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   The woman agreed but, apparently unwilling to take advantage,
insisted on paying the meter's $7 as she was about to get out.
Crowley-Gerame refused to accept the money, but just before the
door closed, the original passenger thrust a $5 bill at her and
waved goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley-Gerame made her shuttle to Washington in good time.
</P>
<P>
   DELANCEY STREET
</P>
<P>
   Papa landed here 100 years ago
</P>
<P>
   an island of cobblestones horses tenements
</P>
<P>
   pushcart peddlers hawking on raucous streets
</P>
<P>
   Mama with two little boys in steerage _ later
</P>
<P>
   for Statue's Promise schools food for growing brood.
</P>
<P>
   This brisk sunny Sunday morning their grandson
</P>
<P>
   drives his aged parents past din of cars
</P>
<P>
   past clatter of sidewalk chatter
</P>
<P>
   Ratner's beckons pea soup blintzes borscht
</P>
<P>
   warm onion rolls blase waiters bearing strudels
</P>
<P>
   Like greenhorns we hear the city
</P>
<P>
   chime melodies scaling skyscraper sky
</P>
<P>
   shielding shabby walk-up flats.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh faces and feet surge ahead again
</P>
<P>
   the day's adventure a reminder of our debt
</P>
<P>
   to this land
</P>
<P>
   for Statue's Promise kept.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROSE KIRCHMAN
</P>
<P>
   With June and its weddings once more upon us, Lee Stokes Hilton
recalled her June wedding day almost a quarter of a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Jim, were leaving their reception when they
realized they had not arranged for a car to take them to the
airport. A cab was summoned and her suitcase was put in the trunk.
As they waved goodbye to their friends, she discovered that,
perhaps because of the flurry of wedding plans, something else had
been overlooked. The groom had forgotten to pack a case.
</P>
<P>
   The address of his bachelor apartment was given, and on arrival,
Jim Hilton dashed out of the cab to pack some things, promising to
be right back. The sequence of events wasn't lost on the cabby.
``You two just get married?'' he asked. Yes, Lee Hilton replied,
adding, ``We're going on our honeymoon, I hope.''
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes of silence, the driver said, ``You wait
here,'' jumped out of the cab and trotted off.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Jim Hilton reappeared. ``Where's the
driver?'' he asked, and Lee Hilton admitted that she didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   But before another minute had passed, the driver returned with a
large brown-paper bag in hand. ``I got this for you,'' he said, and
thrust the bag at Jim Hilton. Inside was a chilled bottle of
champagne.
</P>
<P>
   HOW DOES YOUR GARDEN GROW
</P>
<P>
   I have 10 fingers,
</P>
<P>
   two are thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Neither one
</P>
<P>
   is green.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot grow
</P>
<P>
   chrysanthemums
</P>
<P>
   or a single
</P>
<P>
   lima bean
</P>
<P>
   I plant with peat,
</P>
<P>
   I hoe with fert,
</P>
<P>
   solicitously
</P>
<P>
   plant my seeds:
</P>
<P>
   and wait and watch
</P>
<P>
   the fat black dirt
</P>
<P>
   grow radiant
</P>
<P>
   with weeds.
</P>
<P>
   _ KATHLEEN PARRISH
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   It was a chilly day and I was waiting inside the ATM vestibule
of a bank, watching for an M104 bus. An attractive young woman
entered, pushing a stroller with a toddler in it, and accompanied
by two small dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The woman stopped short and yelled at one of the dogs, named
Henry, ``Don't do that.'' In front of Henry was one of the baby's
socks, and although the baby seemed quite content with one sock,
the mother wasn't. She hollered again at Henry and pulled the sock
onto the baby's bare foot.
</P>
<P>
   Henry waited a moment and proceeded to pull the sock off the
baby's foot again. He dropped the sock on the floor and looked at
the now distraught young woman. ``Stop that,'' she yelled, and
pulled him away from the baby.
</P>
<P>
   Then the mother started to negotiate her way through one of the
inner doors leading into the bank. She accidentally brushed against
an adjacent door, which opened just enough that when it was
released, it hit her other small dog, whose name was Oscar, on the
rump.
</P>
<P>
   The woman was laughing while apologizing to him, but Oscar
looked as though apologies didn't make up for life's being so
unfair. The expression on his face seemed to ask, ``Why am I the
one being hit on the rump when it's Henry that's doing
everything?''
</P>
<P>
   I remember thinking about how the woman could handle it all _
the toddler and stroller and dogs and door slams _ and that she was
a real New Yorker. But then again, so was Henry.
</P>
<P>
   _ GARY S. RICHTER
</P>
</TEXT>
