<HEADLINE>
GORE SPREADS THE WORD VIA `VALIDATORS': HE IS OK
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This article is part of TIMES EXPRESS. It is a condensed
version of a story that will appear in tomorrow's New York Times.) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When he was in Seattle last week, Vice President Al
Gore dropped by a fund-raising reception for Gov. Gary Locke of
Washington. The governor, in introducing the vice president to the
crowd, followed a script suggested by Gore's presidential campaign.
And here is what the campaign wanted these people to know:
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not only a great person, but he's very funny,'' Locke
said of the vice president. He is ``a person who is committed to
his family,'' Locke went on. ``He is always picking up the phone to
check on his mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Locke, like countless others who are introducing Gore around the
country these days, is what is known in the trade as a
``validator,'' or a character witness, someone who can reassure
voters that the real Al Gore is a decent man, a family man, a good
guy.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore has been campaigning intensely for more than a
year now, and has been in public life for nearly a quarter century,
he is still having trouble getting across this basic message. That
is one reason the campaign is enlisting scores of validators _
Democrats like Sen. Evan Bayh of Indiana and Sen. John F. Kerry of
Massachusetts _ and deploying them on talk shows and the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment of validators is just one element of a new phase
of the Gore campaign, which includes a media blitz he plans to
begin Tuesday in New York, one so extensive that it will almost
seem like a re-launch of his campaign, as he begins a ``progress
and prosperity tour'' across the mid-Atlantic and Midwest states.
The new phase also features a multimillion-dollar advertising
campaign, a retreat from harsh assessments of Bush and a cheery
message of optimism.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Gore, the shift in strategy plays into one of
the Republicans' chief criticisms of him _ that he lacks
consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore Reinvents Himself _ Again!'' blares a press release
from the Bush campaign. It goes on to list six Gore incarnations
since last summer: the underdog, the average Joe, the alpha male,
the crusading reformer, the negative attacker and, now, the
thinking man with a heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1023 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-RICH-KIDS-500&AMP;ADD-     06-11 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RICH-KIDS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MANHATTAN'S WEALTHY PARENTS, TIPS ON BRAT CONTROL
</HEADLINE>
  By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If your 5-year-old asks how much money you make, and
you make tons, then the appropriate reply is, ``That is not a nice
question.''
</P>
<P>
   If your 22-year-old gives a big, boozy party and breaks up the
million-dollar apartment that you just bought as a graduation gift,
then that child is not yet ready to be trusted with serious
inheritance money.
</P>
<P>
   If your son insists on marrying someone who is poor, then, as
soon as is seemly, you should persuade the future daughter-in-law
to sign a prenuptial agreement. After the signature, it is prudent
to smooth ruffled feathers with a sizable cash gift that says,
``Welcome to the family.''
</P>
<P>
   These and other strategies for raising the rich in Manhattan
were served up last week in an auction room at Christie's filled
with wealthy parents and grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   Rich kids are something of a growth industry in Manhattan and
across the country, as the number of families worth $10 million or
more has jumped more than fourfold in the past decade to 275,000
from 65,000, said Edward N. Wolff, a professor of economics at New
York University and editor of The Review of Income and Wealth.
</P>
<P>
   At least 41,000 of those families live in New York City,
constituting the largest concentration of the rich in any American
city, Wolff said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's strategy session at Christie's marshaled the
expertise of four rich-kid specialists _ a headmaster at a private
school, a lawyer specializing in trusts and estates, a child
psychiatrist and a psychoanalyst. Together, they explained how to
increase the odds that children who know they will never have to
work for a living will turn out to be something other than pouty
layabouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``An awful lot of people have made an enormous amount of money
and are scared what it is going to do to their kids,'' said Dale
Burch, who organized the box lunch and panel discussion, for which
tickets cost between $100 and $500. It was the second such panel in
two years at Christie's, with proceeds going to charity.
</P>
<P>
   The ideal rich kid that the experts talked about would grow up
to be a hard-working adult _ smart with investments, inclined to
philanthropy and comfortable in social settings with the nonrich.
</P>
<P>
   Unmentioned by the press-shy parents at the box lunch were the
flame-outs, drug overdoses and suicides that periodically burn the
names of rich families _ and their profoundly unhappy progeny _
into the public mind.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan in the past 13 months, Raphael de Rothschild, 23,
heir to one of the largest fortunes in the world, died of an
apparent heroin overdose on a sidewalk; Robert Bingham, 33, a
promising fiction writer and heir to a newspaper fortune, died of
an apparent heroin overdose in his loft; and William Woodward III,
54, scion of a society family known as much for violent deaths as
for wealth, took off his slippers and jumped to his death from his
14th-floor apartment on the Upper East Side.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Judging from last week's two-hour advice session (and a
videotape of last year's), three particularly vexing clusters of
trouble confront parents trying to raise well-adjusted children in
Park Avenue circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   First, motivation and discipline. Or, ``You can buy whatever you
want without lifting a pudgy finger,'' as Hume R. Speyer, the
trusts and estates lawyer on the panel, summed up the fundamental
risk facing rich children.
</P>
<P>
   Parents should show their children, by example, that meaning in
life comes from work, education and concern for others _ not from
buying and bragging about clothes, cars, airplanes, apartments,
summer houses and fancy foreign vacations.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, parents should insist that children do real work
around the house, even if it means ordering servants to back off
and let a child wash a dish, vacuum a rug or clean a closet.
Parents should meet regularly with other parents to compare
allowances, credit-card policies and set rules for how much money
rich children can spend on one another.
</P>
<P>
   The second difficult area is dealing with those who are not
rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I have to fly coach so my son will not alienate other
kids?'' asked one parent, who said he could not control his son's
bragging about family money.
</P>
<P>
   The panel said such bragging was common among insecure rich kids
trying to establish a sense of self. To smooth a child's entry into
a world where most people are not rich, the panel agreed, parents
should talk early and often with him about family money _ and about
the obligations that go with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be honest and matter of fact with children inside the family
about the money,'' said Speyer, the lawyer, who advises starting
frank discussions about money when children are in their early
teens. He said the chats should become more detailed _ and should
be supported with paperwork from brokers and banks _ as a
teen-ager's capacity to understand increases.
</P>
<P>
   But in all these conversations, Speyer said, parents should draw
a firm line between proper discussions of money inside the family
and improper boasting about money with friends and all other
outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``By not acting like an extremely rich person,'' he said, ``you
may not be treated like an extremely rich person, and that is a
good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The third problem was whether parents owed their children a
permanently luxurious lifestyle, a question that seemed to arouse
the most passion from panelists and parents.
</P>
<P>
   All the experts argued that parents did indeed owe their
children continuity with the lives to which they had become
accustomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have lived themselves a life of plenty, that is all
they will have learned in their lives,'' said George P. Davison,
head of Grace Church School, a private school in Manhattan. ``They
will have been really good at it in order to please you as their
parents. Then, after doing everything right for 21 years, you say,
`Sorry, you are out.' Of course, they are going to be angry. Of
course, they are going to be uncomprehending.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
