</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HOW TO MOVE THE SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, June 12:
</P>
<P>
   With 1.1 million students spread across 1,100 buildings, New
York City's public schools have historically contained some of the
best and worst schools in the country. The problem is finding a way
to extend teacher talent and enthusiasm for learning beyond those
schools that have traditionally flourished to schools at the low
end of the performance scale.
</P>
<P>
   The system has a long way to go to reach this goal. But as the
school year draws to a close, New York City's schools are showing
indisputable signs of improvement as measured by state and local
reading tests.
</P>
<P>
   To solidify and build upon these gains, the city and the state
will need to commit more energy and money to two vital objectives.
The first is attracting the most talented teachers into the
lowest-performing schools. The second is to build more schools as
quickly as possible, to alleviate poor conditions and overcrowding
that typically make the best teachers go elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The school system will also need to assure that funds are
directed to teacher training and other instructional needs instead
of to administrative activities that have less to do with improving
academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   This school year got off to a chaotic start, with the system
roiled by uncertainty over whether then-Schools Chancellor Rudy
Crew would stay or go. The Board of Education finally voted to buy
out his contract and seek a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Then the search for a successor turned into a political
slugfest, as Mayor Rudolph Giuliani worked to undermine the prime
candidate, Harold Levy, on the grounds that Levy was too close to
the teachers union. The board's willingness to appoint him over
Giuliani's objections came as a relief to New Yorkers who had grown
tired of political brinkmanship at the expense of the city's
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Levy got the permanent job after impressing the board during his
stint in the interim post. He pushed the state Legislature for a
bigger share of state aid, started a review of the system's huge
bureaucracy and began to streamline the disciplinary procedures
through which incompetent teachers are removed.
</P>
<P>
   As for student performance, Levy is reaping the results of four
years of intensive work by Crew, who devoted himself to high
standards and championed the belief that all the system's children
can learn. This gospel of high achievement allowed the system to
boost reading scores slightly for three consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   But the system posted the largest gains yet just recently, when
both state and local reading scores showed significant improvements
all over the city, even in some of the most troubled districts. To
a large extent, these improvements are attributed to Project Read,
an intensive program that provides children with small-group
instruction after school or during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Though encouraging, the most recent test scores show a clear
division between middle-class neighborhoods, which are improving
quickly, and poor neighborhoods, which are improving at a slower
rate. It is no secret that schools in the poorest neighborhoods
suffer the worst overcrowding and are staffed by the least
experienced teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, recent surveys show that the most talented teachers
are the first to leave for the suburbs, citing not just higher pay,
but also the need for relief from huge and unwieldy classes.
Stopgap solutions are imposing an educational cost. In Queens, for
example, the city has eased overcrowding by running two split
sessions that cheat students of one or two class periods per day.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature has wisely committed itself to provide
incentives that could lure more experienced teachers to
low-performing schools and keep them there. But the class-size
problem will remain insoluble until more money is found to build
some badly needed schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
