u i BC-SYRIA-BASHAR-BOS &LR;      06-11 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYRIA-BASHAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPS TAKEN TO TRANSFER POWER IN DAMASCUS TO ASSAD'S SON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS _ President Hafez Assad's son Bashar was named
commander of Syria's armed forces Sunday, virtually guaranteeing he
will lead a country that knows little about him beyond a reputation
for honesty, a penchant for surfing the Internet, and a passion for
the music of Phil Collins.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old former eye doctor was appointed to the top
military post by Vice President Abdel-Halim Khaddam, a government
spokesman said, the day after his father, whose health had been
declining for years, died at the age of 69.
</P>
<P>
   The state television also said that the leadership of the ruling
Baath Party had voted unanimously to nominate Bashar Assad for the
presidency. The rubber-stamp parliament will reconvene on June 25
and is expected to approve the nomination and then carry out an
election in which Bashar would be the only candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Hafez Assad survived nearly 30 years of wars, coup attempts,
assassination plots, diplomatic isolation and a struggling economy,
and Syrians have feared that a power vacuum and instability could
consume the country and the region when he died.
</P>
<P>
   But it appeared Sunday that Assad's careful grooming of Bashar
over the last six years has paved the way for a smooth transition
of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be pretty well orchestrated,'' said a Western
diplomat in Damascus. ``Dissent, one way or another, is going to be
kicked in the back row of the theater. The sense is that they are
going to orchestrate this right through, and then people will sit
by and watch for four, six, or eight months down the road and
assess how it's going.''
</P>
<P>
   That Bashar Assad will inherit power seems inevitable, but
whether he can hold on to them remains an open question. There are
many vying military and business interests in a regime that was
famously insular, secretive, and ruled by fear. It is too early to
tell if Bashar Assad may have enemies lurking in the corners
plotting to derail his consolidation of power.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the streets of Damascus are clogged with an outpouring
of grief at the loss of Hafez Assad and well-organized marches in
support of his son. Posters with Bashar's boyish face and
well-groomed mustache are cropping up on corners and lightposts and
walls all over the city.
</P>
<P>
   Syrians thronged the capital throughout the scorching heat of
midday and into the cooler winds that come at night. In the
downtown Omayad Square, young teenagers dressed in black headbands
chanted, ``God, Syria, Bashar.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands wept and waved placards of Assad's smiling face in
front of the hospital where his body lay before a state funeral
scheduled for Monday that is expected to be an extraordinary
gathering of world leaders and dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Youths beating drums conducted solemn funeral marches, some of
which seemed less than spontaneous. Observers suggested they had
been organized along the lines of the different government
ministries, political youth organizations, and Baath Party
districts. A fleet of old buses was used to bring Syrians from
every corner of the country to take part in the capital's
street-level expression of mourning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at our eyes. We cannot express our sadness,'' said Ahalam
Alia, 25, a government employee who, like Assad's family, hails
from the northern coastal region near Latakia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take comfort that Bashar will be like his father,
God willing. All the people are with him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Assad's often brutal rule, there was not a bad word to
be heard about him or his regime on the streets. It seemed to be
more than just fear of speaking out, but a sincere appreciation
that Assad had held the country together through a tumultuous three
decades in the Middle East. And there was optimism about Bashar and
his apparent interest in opening up Syria's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our dream for the future,'' said Jamal Saleh, 17, dressed
in black and carrying a poster of Bashar. ``And he will be like his
father.
</P>
<P>
   Saleh said he dreamed of working in computers, and that Bashar
was a leader who could make that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet and computers are very important for us, he knows
this very well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar Assad has struck a chord with young Syrians by arguing
that Syria, where the Internet is strictly controlled and satellite
dishes are outlawed, must adapt itself to the age of technology and
the openness it engenders. Introducing technology, he maintains, is
the best way for Syria to move beyond the centrally controlled
economy that has bogged down Syria with 30 percent unemployment,
strict restrictions on trade, and an unstable currency.
</P>
<P>
   The daunting challenge of learning to lead Syria fell upon
Bashar after his brother, Basil, was killed in a car crash while
rushing to catch a plane in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Basil was regarded as more charismatic and outgoing. Bashar, who
is fluent in Arabic, English and French, is more modest, even
awkward. Until his brother died, he was quietly studying
ophthalmology in London. Now, at times, he is caught on television
or in newspaper photographs with his sunken eyes appearing consumed
with worry about the responsibility he has inherited.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bashar Assad's most difficult tasks will be to preserve
his father's base of power among Syria's Alawite minority,
historically an underprivileged and oppressed rural group that
numbers 12 percent of Syria's 17 million people. Many Alawites,
incuding the senior Assad, joined the military as a means of social
mobility. Today they form the military elite that has clung to
power through Assad's authoritarian rule.
</P>
<P>
   But for Bashar Assad to be successful in bringing Syria out of
its economic troubles and diplomatic isolation, he may have to
challenge this very elite.
</P>
<P>
   The Alawite circle that surrounded his father had tight bonds
with an often corrupt merchant class which some academics here
dubbed the ``merchant-military complex.'' A significant part of
Bashar Assad's popularity is that he has already taken on a public
campaign to root out this corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The Alawites' dominance relies on their control of the military.
Some analysts said the Alawites are hesitant to sign an accord with
Israel because, as Glenn Richardson of the University of California
at Berkley put it, peace would diminish their importance and ``put
the perpetuation of Alawi rule at risk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
