A1030 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      06-11 0293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HEALTH TASKS BEFORE THE LEGISLATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, June 12:
</P>
<P>
   Empire Blue Cross and Blue Shield, the largest health insurer in
New York state, cannot earn enough money to survive if it remains a
nonprofit company. But state authorities have dawdled over its
application to convert to for-profit status for nearly four years,
and the Legislature is threatening to exit Albany without approving
Empire's request.
</P>
<P>
   Empire used to be the only insurer to extend coverage to all
individual applicants _ those not covered through employers _ at
rates that did not depend on the applicant's medical condition. But
since 1996, the state has required every managed care plan to
enroll individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Empire's special role ceased. The only way to preserve Empire's
contribution to the uninsured is to approve the conversion. Empire
would turn over all of its stock, worth perhaps $600 million, to an
independent foundation. The foundation would later sell the stock,
using the proceeds to help extend coverage to the uninsured. Empire
would then issue new stock to pay for the information systems and
other hugely expensive investments that are needed to match those
of for-profit plans.
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofit plans are struggling across the country. The simple
fact is that Empire cannot provide enrollees high-quality service
unless it can raise capital. The insurance commissioner supports
conversion. So does Eliot Spitzer, the attorney general. Four years
is long enough to wait for something that benefits Empire's 4
million enrollees and has widespread approval among the state
authorities in charge of protecting the public interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
