<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA HOME RUNS BEAT ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -- Scott Schoeneweis got the first hit and RBI of his
major league career Sunday afternoon, but the ball probably will
wind up in the garage and not the trophy case.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels pitcher singled with two out in the seventh inning to
drive home Bengie Molina from second to give the Angels a 2-1 lead
over the Arizona Diamondbacks. But after the ball was secured for
safekeeping and Schoeneweis took the mound in the bottom of the
seventh, the ball's value sustained a big hit.
</P>
<P>
   Make that two big hits.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Colbrunn and Danny Bautista hit back-to-back homers with
one out in the seventh, turning a 2-1 deficit into a 3-2
Diamondbacks victory before 36,349 at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Only one day earlier, Angels pitcher Jarrod Washburn got his
first major league hit and RBI while pitching the club to a 10-3
win. But Schoeneweis didn't get nearly the same run support, and
consequently he got a different outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't care, I couldn't care less,'' Schoeneweis said
of getting his first major league hit. ``I would rather strike out
and put up another zero (in the bottom of the inning). Let the guys
who get paid to do that stuff take care of that.''
</P>
<P>
   And what will he do with the baseball?
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll go somewhere with all of the rest of the crap that's
accumulating,'' Schoeneweis said.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were in good shape after Schoeneweis' hit, because it
brought up the league's leading hitter Darin Erstad with runners on
first and third. Diamondbacks manager Buck Showalter brought in
lefty Dan Plesac to replace Armando Reynoso (6 2/3 innings, 2 runs,
8 hits) and Plesac struck Erstad out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Byung-Hyun Kim entered the game for the Diamondbacks in the
eighth, and made quick work of the Angels. He struck out the side
in the eighth (Benji Gil, Mo Vaughn and Tim Salmon) and struck out
two more in a 1-2-3 ninth for his eighth save.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's submarine-style delivery obviously fooled the Angels, who
had only one batter -- Garret Anderson with a pop to short -- put
the ball in play against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interleague play you're going against guys you've never seen
before,'' Vaughn said. ``It's almost like spring training. We'll
swing the bats (Tuesday). Interleague is tough, we'll be all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia said it wasn't so much the delivery
as it was Kim's ability to simply make good pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not quite a (Kent) Tekulve or a (Dan) Quisenberry,''
Scioscia said. ``He threw a couple pitches at a low three-quarter.
But he's not trying to trick everyone, he made some good pitches.
Whatever angle you're throwing from, that's the key.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson slugged his 16th home run of the season with one out in
the second inning to give the Angels a 1-0 lead. The lead lasted
until the bottom of the fourth, when Tony Womack singled and
eventually scored on an RBI-groundout by Matt Williams.
</P>
<P>
   After Schoeneweis gave the Angels a lead with his bat in the top
of the seventh, he quickly gave it right back when he left a couple
pitches up, and Colbrunn and Bautista took advantage by smacking
the back-to-back homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I throw a pitch above the knees, it seems to get hit far
every time,'' Schoeneweis said. ``They don't foul it off, they
don't swing and miss. It seems like one time they should foul it
off. That was the ballgame right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't won a game in it seems like six months (it was May
25). It's been a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
