<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-RACES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NY SENATE REPUBLICANS WHOSE SEATS ARE VULNERABLE  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (With NY-SENATE-REPUBLICANS)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the Republicans in the State Senate who are widely
viewed as vulnerable in this year's elections. They are listed in
order, from most vulnerable to least, as seen by a wide sampling of
politicians and political analysts.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GUY J. VELELLA _ Bronx and Westchester Counties. 1996 election:
unopposed; 1998: 58 percent district voter registration (54 percent
Democrat, 22 percent Republican).
</P>
<P>
   Of the districts in New York held by Republicans, this district,
arcing across the north and east Bronx and into southern
Westchester, is the most heavily Democratic. But the greatest
threat to Velella could be from Robert M. Morgenthau, the Manhattan
district attorney, who recently sent investigators with search
warrants to take files from the senator's offices, as part of an
investigation whose purpose has not been revealed. Velella, a
senator since 1986, could face a serious challenger for the first
time in many years. Lorraine Coyle Koppell, wife of a former
attorney general, G. Oliver Koppell, is running for this seat, but
she must first win a Democratic primary against Michael Benedetto.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRANK A. PADAVAN _ Queens 1996 election: unopposed; 1998: 59
percent voter registration (52 percent Democrat, 23 percent
Republican). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In this district in northeastern Queens, the minority and
immigrant populations have increased steadily for years, a shift
that could work in a Democrat's favor. Padavan, a senator since
1973, is generally more conservative than his district. His
opponent this year, Rory Lancman, a young lawyer and community
board member, may be the strongest Democrat he has faced in many
years.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NICHOLAS A. SPANO _ Westchester County. 1996 election: 52
percent; 1998: 59 percent voter registration (44 percent Democrat,
28 percent Republican). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spano's centrist politics are a good fit for his district, but
he has had some close calls. In 1996, he had a political near-death
experience running against Thomas Abinanti, majority leader of the
Westchester County Legislature, who is running again this year.
This time, Spano, a senator since 1987, will be taking Abinanti
more seriously, but then again, so will the Democrats, who put few
resources behind the challenger four years ago.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THOMAS A. MORAHAN _ Rockland and Orange Counties. 1999 special
election: 53 percent voter registration (42 percent Democrat, 28
percent Republican). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Morahan barely won this seat in a special election last year,
and the higher turnout of a general election in a presidential year
traditionally helps Democrats. He faces the same opponent he did
last year, Kenneth P. Zebrowski, chairman of the Rockland County
Legislature. Morahan has been in poor health, a factor that some
Republicans fear will limit his ability to campaign.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROY M. GOODMAN _ Manhattan. 1996 election: 62 percent; 1998: 56
percent voter registration (52 percent Democrat, 23 percent
Republican). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, a senator since 1969, is the most liberal Republican in
the Senate, and is well liked in his Upper East Side district, but
he, too, has had some close calls. In the 1998 election, he had the
weakest showing of any incumbent senator. He could face his
strongest Democratic opponent in years: Liz Krueger, who heads the
Community Food Resource Center and has some family wealth behind
her candidacy. She faces a Democratic primary against Rob
Bellinson, a lawyer who has run against Goodman twice.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KEMP HANNON _ Nassau County.1996 election: 57 percent; 1998: 60
percent voter registration (46 percent Republican, 31 percent
Democrat). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hannon's Republican colleagues sometimes grumble that he is more
enthusiastic about legislation than about campaigning, while
Democrats say he spends more time in Albany than in his district.
His district, strung across the midsection of the county, includes
the largest concentration of minority voters on Long Island, but
this is normally a safe Republican seat. The question, as with all
the Nassau districts, is whether last year's backlash against the
Nassau Republican party carries over to this November. Hannon, a
senator since 1989, faces Anthony D. Macagnone, a member of the
Oyster Bay Town Board and a carpenters' union official, who was
also the Democratic candidate two years ago.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL A. BALBONI _ Nassau County. 1997 special election: 61
percent; 1998: 58 percent voter registration (39 percent
Republican, 34 percent Democrat). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine Long Island districts, this is the one where
Democrats come closest to parity in voter registration. It is also
the place with the freshest example of rebellion by Nassau voters
against the Republican Party. In a special election last month for
County Legislature, in a district overlapping Balboni's, the
Democrat crushed a Republican and an independent. But politicians
in both parties say Balboni, a senator since 1997, has been
tireless and effective at making himself popular in his district.
He faces John Brooks, a lawyer who was his Democratic opponent two
years ago.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARL L. MARCELLINO _ Nassau and Suffolk Counties. 1996: 59
percent; 1998: 60 percent voter registration (41 percent
Republican, 30 percent Democrat). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marcellino, a senator since 1995, has the advantage that almost
half his district lies in Suffolk County (he also represents the
northeast section of Nassau), where there has been no rebellion
against Republicans. But even his colleagues say he is not much of
a campaigner, and this year he has a fairly well-known opponent.
The Democrat is Lawrence H. Silverman, president of the Long Island
Rail Road Commuters Council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
