<HEADLINE>
BELCHER MAY START SATURDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -- Tim Belcher is ``penciled in'' to come off the
disabled list and make his first start of the season Saturday in
Baltimore, according to manager Mike Scioscia.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, who had off-season elbow surgery, made a rehab start at
Sacramento for Triple-A Edmonton on Saturday, throwing 85 pitches
in six innings, giving up three runs and four hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to go,'' Belcher said. ``I'm done with my
barnstorming tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher hasn't pitched in a major league game since last Sept.
14 and is eager to get back out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only adjustment will be to make sure I'm not too amped
up,'' he said. ``I'm pretty excited, but that's a good thing too. I
I didn't have that feeling of getting excited I probably shouldn't
be here. I'm looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher said he knows he's ready and his elbow is fine because
of the way he finished in Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out for the sixth inning knowing it was going to be my
last inning, so I went out and aired out every fastball,'' he said.
``I had to see what kind of velocity I had, and it was very good.
... And everything held together, so that's a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Al Levine likely would get the start if Belcher can't
go, but that isn't likely.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hill also made a rehab start Saturday, throwing 65 pitches
over four innings, giving up two runs (unearned) and five hits.
Hill, recovering from a strained rib-cage muscle, will make his
next rehab start for Edmonton on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Dickson, recovering from a strained hip, made a rehab
start for Edmonton Sunday. He pitched 4 fr 1/3 innings and allowed
one run and five hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got a scare in the second inning Sunday when Troy
Glaus fell to the ground in pain while grabbing his right knee
after being picked off first base. After lying on the ground for a
few minutes and being checked by trainer Rick Smith, Glaus got up
and jogged over to his position at third base without a limp.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus had banged knees with Diamondbacks first baseman Greg
Colbrunn.
</P>
<P>
   ``None, zero,'' Glaus snapped when asked if he considered coming
out of the game. Asked if he thought for a moment the injury might
be serious, he said: ``Have you ever hurt your knee? I haven't, so
I don't know. ... If we had a game (today), I'd be in there ready
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing Glaus would be a major blow to the Angels offense. Glaus
is hitting .327 with 18 homers (fifth in A.L.), 42 RBI, 50 runs
(tied for third), 145 total bases (fifth), 20 doubles (tied for
second), 47 walks (second), .449 on-base percentage (fourth), .671
slugging percentage (sixth), and 38 extra-base hits (fourth).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
