<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR MONDAY, JUNE 12
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Monday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(ss) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-AFRICA-PIPELINE-NYT (moved on Monday, June 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article senr on Monday, June 5
about the World Bank's consideration of an oil pipeline in Africa
referred incorrectly to a recent report by the bank on African
poverty. The study concluded that Africans were poorer than 40
years ago and that a share of the blame belonged to the bank and
the International Monetary Fund. But the contention that the two
organizations had made the continent poorer through failed lending
policies came from recent Washington demonstrators, not from the
study.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-BASKIN-NYT (moved on Monday, June 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service obituary sent on Monday, June 5 of
the sculptor Leonard Baskin on Tuesday misinterpreted a statement
he made in 1964 about the forms he preferred to depict. His
comment, ``The female form is useful for some ideas, but the
colossal male is better suited to the ghoulish ones I try to
portray,'' did not mean he never portrayed women. The female form
appeared in a number of his lithographs, etchings and woodcuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
