<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S PRIOR TO FACE LSU AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. - USC pitcher Mark Prior's prior meeting with
Louisiana State sounds like something better left forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone probably would have, if not for the fact the
Trojans face LSU today in a winners' bracket game at the College
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But once today's matchup was set, Prior's career at Vanderbilt
suddenly became newsworthy, specifically his one meeting against
LSU. Prior allowed six earned runs and 11 hits in 5 innings, but
he's not worried facing the second-ranked Tigers again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little kid last year,'' Prior said. ``I don't feel
overmatched. I think I'm a lot better mentally. Win or lose,
they'll think I'm a better pitcher. It's a way to redeem myself.''
</P>
<P>
   USC certainly hopes so, because today's game is critical, even
if the loser is not eliminated from the World Series. A victory
means the Trojans would have two days off before playing again
Thursday. A loss means playing Tuesday night in an elimination
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it is kind of do-or-die,'' Prior said. ``We need a
victory. We don't have the luxury other teams do because we don't
have a lot of offense. We don't want to get in a situation where we
have to outhit the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   LSU (49-17) is already drawing raves in Omaha, after hitting
three home runs in a 13-5 rout of Texas on Saturday night, and
Prior doesn't expect a pitchers' duel today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know things will happen. There will probably be home runs,
because of the team we're playing and the ballpark we're playing
in,'' Prior said. ``My job is to keep things close so that in the
eighth or ninth inning, maybe we have a chance to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (44-18) played LSU three times in the 1998 World
Series, losing the opener 12-10, before defeating the Tigers, 5-4
and 7-3, in elimination games that sent USC to the championship
contest.
</P>
<P>
   LSU also eliminated the Trojans twice in regional play in 1990
and 1994, although those games were in Baton Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost to them more than we've beaten them, that's for
sure,'' USC coach Mike Gillespie said. ``The thing I'm not prepared
for in this Omaha deal is that it has become the northern version
of Baton Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have, to their credit, won over the Omaha fans. When we
played them in '98 and heard the noise, I was astounded. I naively
thought the local people would root for the underdog.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
