<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-SYRIA-LEBANON-VILLA     06-11 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SYRIA-LEBANON-VILLAGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLAN HEIGHTS VILLAGE VOWS TO FIGHT ANY ATTEMPTS AT DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add photo note) (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo _ NYT 13
_ is being sent to NYT photo clients.nNonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GHAJAR, Golan Heights _ Carrying black flags and a
flower-wreathed portrait of Hafez Assad, the people of this border
village held a memorial ceremony Sunday for the leader of the
country they call their own.
</P>
<P>
   The villagers, members of Assad's minority Alawite sect, chanted
and wept in a demonstration of loyalty to Syria that was repeated
Sunday in the neighboring Druse villages of the Golan Heights,
which was captured by Israel from Syria in the 1967 Arab-Israeli
war.
</P>
<P>
   In Majdal Shams, the largest village of Druse, a separate sect,
hundreds gathered in the main square under Syrian flags to hear
eulogies and poems of tribute, marching to a border fence to send
condolences into Syria over a sound truck.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the ceremony here in Ghajar had a peculiar twist, befitting
a village in limbo at the junction of Israel, Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   After Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon last month, United
Nations teams surveying the border determined that according to the
line drawn in the 1920s, part of Ghajar actually lies in Lebanon,
not the Israeli-held Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that a border fence could soon divide families and
separate people from their farmlands, village residents have
barricaded entrances to Ghajar with burning tires and are standing
guard armed with clubs to repel any United Nations teams that might
come to mark the border.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts have been posted to summon the 1,700 residents to the
streets if United Nations vehicles are spotted nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The village will be divided over our dead bodies,'' said Imad
Khatib, 35, a teacher. ``Without our lands we will be refugees.
This is inhuman.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials said they were simply marking the border and will
not build a fence. They stopped short of entering Ghajar, surveying
the village by helicopter, residents said.
</P>
<P>
   The village's residents insist that for generations they have
been considered Syrian, not Lebanese, with Syrian identification
papers and property deeds _ a message that was hammered home Sunday
by the memorial ceremony for Assad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in Ghajar are Syrian, and this is Syrian soil,'' said
Salman Khatib, the leader of the local council. He stood in the
village square, near an outlook over the Hasbani River that was
decorated Sunday with a likeness of Assad and a Syrian flag.
</P>
<P>
   Village residents said that in June 1967, when Israel captured
the Golan Heights, its troops stopped short of Ghajar, considering
it Lebanese territory. But the Lebanese authorities, reluctant to
absorb an Alawite community into a land already divided by
religious strife, told a delegation from Ghajar that their village
was part of Syria and warned the group that if villagers crossed
the Hasbani River into Lebanon, they would be shot or jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Residents then invited Israeli forces to take the village with
the rest of the Golan, and the villagers were granted Israeli
citizenship in the 1980s. Many now work in neighboring Israeli
communities and speak fluent Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   Matan Vilnai, an Israeli cabinet minister, visited Ghajar last
week to calm residents' fears, telling them that his government was
in contact with the United Nations and would work to ensure that
the village remained undivided under Israeli control. An Israeli
army vehicle patrolled the village Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Israeli assurance, worried village residents said
Sunday that they wanted to avoid partition at all costs, even if
that meant coming entirely under Lebanese control. A fence, they
said, is out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either we stay together or we will all die,'' said Mahmud
Khatib, 40, a factory worker who stood guard with a club Sunday at
the village entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Kamal Asad, 36, who also held a club, said: ``We didn't choose
this situation. We've simply stuck to our land. The Berlin wall
came down after 30 years, and it can't be that in the year 2000 we
will be divided by a fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a herd of cows that can be split up. We're talking
about human beings. The United Nations is supposed to unite people,
not cut us in two. It should make peace, not pain. This is not
political. We only want to live in dignity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
