<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1052 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-NYT     06-11 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER TRIPS UP LAKERS' MARCH IN THE FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Size and position prevent Reggie Miller from ever
waging a genuine duel against Shaquille O'Neal. But for one,
raucous night on his home floor, the corn-silk thin swingman of the
Indiana Pacers pulled back his slingshot and fired. And fired. And
fired.
</P>
<P>
   And when he had finished wiping the perspiration away with his
multi-colored wristbands from another era _ and the Pacers had
survived the Los Angeles Lakers much more than they had scaled
Mount Shaquille _ Miller and 18,345 fans at the Conseco Fieldhouse
rejoiced wildly Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Small-market Pacers 100, big-city Lakers 91.
</P>
<P>
   Rebounding from a dismal showing in Los Angeles much the way his
team did, Miller erupted for 33 points on 11-of-22 shooting and 9
for 9 from the foul line as Indiana made the National Basketball
Association finals a contest instead of a coronation.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers now trail the Lakers by two games to one in the
four-of-seven-game series and can take more solace because they are
host to Games 4 and 5, on Wednesday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was held to  &UR; only  &LR;  33 points and 13 rebounds and made
only three of 13 free throws after imploding for 83 points and 43
rebounds in Games 1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers played without Kobe Bryant, whose sprained left ankle
in the first quarter of Game 2 kept him on the sidelines. His
status for Game 4 is not known. After breakdowns on both ends by
the Lakers, they clearly need help on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers trimmed Indiana's lead to 4 points twice in the final
three minutes to prevent an embarrassing blowout. But each time
O'Neal and his teammates were on the cusp of finishing the job,
Miller or another Pacer would hit a crucial shot.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper's driving scoop layup trimmed Indiana's lead to 4, at
89-85, with 2:55 left.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller's two free throws with 2:02 left gave Indiana the
cushion it needed.
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose finished with 21 points and six rebounds for the
Pacers, who shot 46.2 percent from the field and outrebounded the
Lakers, 38-33. Travis Best and Austin Croshere combined for 26
points off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   With a major role reversal, Sunday night almost resembled Game
1. Like the outplayed Pacers last Wednesday, the Lakers spent so
much energy trying to recover from Indiana's first-half barrage,
they had little left to finish the comeback.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal brought the Lakers within 5 points, at 57-52, midway
through the third quarter as the Pacers fell into a rare offensive
funk. Every call against the Pacers was roundly booed, whether
questionable or not. With the lead slipping away, concern then
panic set in. But it did not last long.
</P>
<P>
   For every overpowering jump hook of O'Neal's released 12 inches
from the rim, Miller answered with a jab-step jump shot. He became
flammable near the end of the period as the Pacers first went on a
12-0 binge and then blew the game open.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's 3-pointer from the right wing with 2:13 left in the
quarter put the Pacers in front, 76-58, and turned Conseco into a
tunnel of sound. He raised his hands and motioning for the fans to
rise from their seats, skipping gleefully down court. Miller time
had finally arrived in the league championship series.
</P>
<P>
   So convincing a victory was transpiring that the Pacers would
not even have to resort to the Hack-a-Shaq defense to try to
throttle O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal scored 10 of the Lakers' first 14 points in the second
period, and for a while it appeared as if he would need 60 to keep
Los Angeles in the game.
</P>
<P>
   After shooting eight for 32 in the first two games and showing
little of the passion and purpose he showed in the conference
finals against the Knicks, Miller locked away the impostor in the
No. 31 jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The player who suited up for Game 3 knew his and his teammates'
reputations were at stake. He understood the magnitude of a
possible 0-3 deficit, knowing no team had come back from such a
hole in any seven-game playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, he had 14 points on seven-of-14 shooting. It was
not just his long jumpers hurting the Lakers either.
</P>
<P>
   Miller hung in the air after O'Neal fouled him with 8:10 left in
the second quarter, clutched once and lofted a layup that fell
through. He pumped his fist wildly after the basket, and the free
throw gave Indiana a 30-19 cushion.
</P>
<P>
   After holding a lead of no more than three points in Games 1 and
2, it was easy to see how different a team the Pacers were on their
home floor, where they were a league-best 35-6 this season.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they were rattled by the crowd, thrown off by Bryant's
absence or both, the Lakers had none of the cohesion that carried
them to a 2-0 series lead. They produced 10 turnovers in the first
24 minutes, some of which were unforced and outright clumsy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 2241EDT &QL; 
