<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1053 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-DODGERS-LADN     06-11 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A'S JUMP ON GAGNE, DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dodgers rookie right-hander Eric Gagne has talked
to Kevin Brown and Orel Hershiser about what it's like to be a
young pitcher. He knows the learning never stops, but also realizes
the pace is highly accelerated in the first few years of pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne, with 14 big-league starts behind him, finds something new
with every inning, every batter, every pitch. And even with that
understanding, Gagne said it helps very little because he wants to
win now.
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes the latest lesson again difficult for the 24-
year-old Gagne to endure. He allowed five first-inning runs and had
trouble locating anything close to home plate. Oakland right-hander
Kevin Appier took the lead and ran off with a seven-hit, 6-0 win
against the Dodgers on Sunday at Chavez Ravine.
</P>
<P>
   And losing two of three to the A's was not the way the Dodgers
wanted to head into a four-game series with Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just struggled with my control, with my mechanics,'' said
Gagne, who allowed all six runs in five innings. ``My lower body
was too quick and my arm couldn't catch up. ... It's really
frustrating. Right now we're close to Arizona (three games back)
and would like to win four or five and stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   The shutout was the 11th for Appier, who often made the trek
from his Antelope Valley home to Dodger Stadium during his
childhood. In cruising to his first shutout since 1997, Appier
allowed one Dodger to reach third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty cool playing there, being that I came here as a
fan,'' Appier said. ``As far as throwing a shutout, that's special
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help the Dodgers hitters that Appier was spotted a 5-0
lead before he threw a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, before Gagne (1-4) recorded an out, the A's had three
runs. Terrence Long singled to start the game, Randy Velarde and
Jason Giambi walked and Matt Stairs was hit by a pitch to force in
the first run. Miguel Tejada doubled to right to make it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gagne was rushing early,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
``Sometimes he has a little problem getting out in front of
himself. He went to his mouth two or three times, was warned and
then (home-plate umpire) John (Shulock) had to get him. He gets all
psyched up. Five days between when he pitches is tough on him right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off his first win of the season, and just second of his
career, Gagne expected much more out of this performance. But it
got worse when Eric Chavez, batting eighth, singled in two more
runs with two outs in the first on a 3-2 pitch. It came with first
base open and Appier on deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets excited out there and is overthrowing the ball a
little bit,'' said Dodgers catcher Paul LoDuca, who had two hits.
``After the first inning, he was fine. He has to get over the
little jitters. He gets too pumped up. You can't take it away from
him. I'd rather have that than someone who's scared. He wants to
throw it 100 miles per hour.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
