<DOCNO> NYT20000611.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-SYRIA-SCENE-ART-NYT     06-11 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SYRIA-SCENE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS OF SYRIANS FLOOD DAMASCUS TO MOURN ASSAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add photo note) (With SYRIA, SYRIA-ISRAEL) 
(ART ADV: Photo _ NYT 12 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ Tens of thousands of Syrians streamed into
Damascus on Sunday to mourn their president, Hafez Assad. By
sunset, the crowd had flooded the Umayyad Square near the Chami
Hospital where they believed his body still lay, awaiting Tuesday's
burial, in his hometown of Qurdaha.
</P>
<P>
   In normal times, public gatherings are not permitted in Syria.
But Sunday, under the watchful eyes of security guards, the crowds
of mourners expressed their grief through chants of love and
support for Assad and his son, Bashar, the heir apparent. Some
mourners wept. A group of young men beat their bare chests so hard
they left welts.
</P>
<P>
   Chanting over and over, ``Hafez, the beloved of God,'' in
Arabic, the mourners carried poster-sized photographs of both
father and son. ``Our blood, our soul, we redeem you, Bashar,''
they called.
</P>
<P>
   One young man, seated atop the shoulders of his friends, with a
portrait of Assad stenciled in black on his bare chest, thrust his
fists in the air and implored the crowds to respond with ever
greater adoration for the only leader many of them have ever known.
</P>
<P>
   ``We loved Assad too much,'' said Rifaat, a taxi driver, who
would not disclose his last name. ``He brought stability to our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the noise and tumult of the streets, Syrian
television played Koranic verses and besides images of mourners,
showed scenes of Bashar Assad meeting with Lebanese officials _
President Emile Lahoud, Prime Minister Selim Hoff, and the Speaker
of Parliament Nabih Berri _ at his home. The Lebanese delegation
also went to the hospital where Assad's body is presumed to lie.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the streets where the mourners gathered, the rest of
Damascus was shuttered with the somber quiet broken only by small
bands of marchers. Soldiers blocked the streets near the
president's home, turning away cars and pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning continued into the evening as torch-bearing youth
groups marched to the sounds of drums in the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Basam Salameh, 17, a secondary student in the crowd, said he
reacted to Assad's death with disbelief. He described the president
as a father for the people, but to many Syrians, he said, the
34-year-old Bashar represents the hope for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the people want Bashar Assad to be president of Syria.
Maybe he can do what the people want for our country and our
population,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be the same as his father,'' he said. ``He will do
great things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 2246EDT &QL; 
