whether high intensity standardization tests - driven by
politicians' and parents' demands for firmer evidence of school
improvement - risks skewing education. (Paul Hosefros/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- June 11, 2000 -- SECURITY-ADVISOR-PROFILE
-- James B. Steinberg tends to remain in the background at public
appearances of the president, but his influence as deputy national
security advisor has been widely felt in the Clinton administration
through his role as chairman of the committee of deputies of the
government's national security agencies. Later this summer, he is
leaving his job to join the Markle Foundation in New York to work
on a $100 million project to study the impact of the digital
revolution on international relations and economic development.
(Stephen Crowly/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) HARRISON, NY -- June 11, 2000 -- GLF-BUICK -- Dennis
Paulson celebrating his victory in the Buick Classic, his first on
the PGA Tour, after sinking a winning putt on the fourth playoff
hole, with David Duval behind him. (Barton Silverman/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ELMONT, NY -- June 11, 2000 -- RAC-BELMONT-COLUMN-3 --
For the first time in 30 years, the Belmont was run without the
winners of either the Kentucky Derby or the Preakness. The Belmont
Stakes winner, Commendable, had lost six in a row since winning his
debut 10 months earlier at Del Mar, and he ran 17th in the Kentucky
Derby. He was entered almost in desperation by D. Wayne Lukas, the
king of Triple Crown racing. D. Wayne Lukas greet Pat Day and
Commendable after winning the Belmost. The race, which did not have
the top 3-year-olds, drew 67,810 fans. (Barton Silverman/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 11, 2000 -- BUSH-INFLUENCES -- Gov.
George W. Bush has said his political views have been shaped by the
work of Myron Magnet of the Manhattan Instiustute who wrote ``The
Dream and the Nightmare,'' which is an indictment of the attitudes
of the 1960s counterculture and its legacy to the poor. Books like
this helped the development of the ``compassionate conservative''
platform Bush is running on today. The core concept of this
platform is that while government has a responsibility to provide
services for the needy it does not have to provide them itself.
(Don Hogan Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia -- June 11, 2000 -- ETHIOPIA-MUSEUM
-- Sebatu Gebre Yesus, 79, is a collector from Addis Ababa,
Ethiopia who makes no distinction between the priceless and the
trash. A pair of Baccarat chandeliers from the palace of Emperor
Haile Selassie sit not far from a souvenir thermometer larded with
a fat Napoleon. He began collecting things when he was young and
now everything is on display in a new museum he has opened in Addis
Ababa. The Museum, scheduled to open in May will apparently be the
only private collection in Ethiopia open to the public. (Ian
Fisher/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ZHONGSHAN, CHINA -- June 11, 2000 -- CHINA-TRADE -- As
China moves closer to its dream of entering the World Trade
Organization, people in the Guangdong Province are nervous. Far
from relishing the prospect of free trade and wide-open markets,
they worry that the new competition could threaten their
livelihood. To enter the WTO, China will have to throw open its
doors to foreign companies. And by reducing tariffs on imports, it
will level its commercial playing field. A worker lifts finished
diapers off an assembly line in a disposable-diaper factory in
Zhongshan, a boom town in Guangdong Province. (Mark Landler/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- June 11, 2000 -- ECOMMERCE-COLUMN -- Consumers
are still abandoning their Web shopping carts at the same rate as
they did in 1998, according to a recent report by Shop.org, an
industry trade group. But now, with e-tailers under increasing
pressure to start actually making money, Web merchants are suddenly
getting serious in their efforts to squeeze whatever cash they can
from site visitors. On marethastewart.com, shoppers cannot tell if
an item is in stock or not. (The New York Times/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NAPLES, FLA -- June 11, 2000 -- GE-SIX-SIGMA -- Six
Sigma, the quality program that big companies including Motorola,
Honeywell and now GE have credited with squeezing billions of
dollars in costs out of products and processes, without losing
quality or service. It is a statistical method of breaking a
customer's requirements into tasks or steps, and setting the
optimum specification for each part of the process, based on how
the parts interact.At a Home Depot in Naples, Fla., appliances can
be ordered, and delivery scheduled, on General Electric's Web site.
(David Carson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ELMONT, NY -- June 11, 2000 -- RAC-BELMONT-COLUMN-2 --
For the first time in 30 years, the Belmont was run without the
winners of either the Kentucky Derby or the Preakness. The Belmont
Stakes winner, Commendable, had lost six in a row since winning his
debut 10 months earlier at Del Mar, and he ran 17th in the Kentucky
Derby. He was entered almost in desperation by D. Wayne Lukas, the
king of Triple Crown racing. Commendable winning the Belmont Stakes
Saturday with the jockey Pat Day aboard. (Barton Silverman/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ELMONT, NY -- June 11, 2000 -- RAC-BELMONT-COLUMN-1 --
For the first time in 30 years, the Belmont was run without the
winners of either the Kentucky Derby or the Preakness. The Belmont
Stakes winner, Commendable, had lost six in a row since winning his
debut 10 months earlier at Del Mar, and he ran 17th in the Kentucky
Derby. He was entered almost in desperation by D. Wayne Lukas, the
king of Triple Crown racing. Beverly and Bob Lewis, the owners of
Commendable, enjoyed their first victory in the Belmost Stakes
after close losses in recent years. (Barton Silverman/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
