<P>
   (NYT13) GHAJAR, Golan Heights -- June 11, 2000 --
SYRIA-LEBANON-VILLAGE -- After Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon
last month, United Nations teams surveying the border determined
that according to the line drawn in the 1920s, part of Ghajar
actually lies in Lebanon, not the Israeli-held Golan Heights. A day
after the death of Hafez al-Assad, Druse and other Golan Heights
villagers who consider themselves Syrian carry portraits of Hafez
al-Assad, Syrian flags and black flags of mourning in Majdal Shams.
(Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) DAMASCUS, Syria -- June 11, 2000 -- SYRIA-SCENE -- In
normal times, public gatherings are not permitted in Syria. But
Sunday, under the watchful eyes of security guards, the crowds of
mourners expressed their grief through chants of love and support
for Assad and his son, Bashar, the heir apparent. Some mourners
wept. A group of young men beat their bare chests so hard they left
welts. Ousama Franza, 25, has a portrait of the man who led Syria
for three decades painted on his chest. (Courtney Kealy/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) POTPMAC, Md. -- June 11, 2000 -- SCHOOLS-CHEATING --
Reports of cheating on a state test are being investigated at
Potomac Elementary School in Potomac, Md. The test incident
catapulted Potomac Elementary into the national debate about
whether high intensity standardization tests - driven by
politicians' and parents' demands for firmer evidence of school
improvement - risks skewing education. (Paul Hosefros/The New York
Times)
</P>
