<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-11 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1196 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-GANG-VIOLENCE-2Takes-     06-11 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANG-VIOLENCE-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW WAVE OF GANG VIOLENCE FEARED IN LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
By BETH BARRETT and LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Inner-city gang warfare _ symbolized by the
murder of LAPD Chief Bernard C. Parks' granddaughter _ has erupted
in an intensifying battle over turf, money, drugs and power among
Bloods and Crips and between Latino and African-American gangs.
</P>
<P>
   The killing of 20-year-old Lori Gonzalez, victim of a gang hit
that missed its target, symbolizes what gang experts, community
activists and emergency medical personnel see as the shattering of
a fragile peace that has lowered crime rates in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Police Department officials note that overall
gang-related crime is down as much as 15 percent citywide this year
but acknowledge that signs of rising tensions are appearing in a
wave of attacks from downtown to the harbor since the May 28
Gonzalez shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Waymon Baker, a former gang member who works in
intervention programs, said efforts are under way to try to bring
leaders of various factions together to try to preserve an uneasy
truce.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like an army. If it appears they're going to lose all
they've acquired, they go to war by any means necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   He said concern is high that ``there's going to be a full-scale
war between the black and Latino gangs'' unless intervention
efforts are stepped up.
</P>
<P>
   An LAPD source close to the Gonzalez investigation said the
shooting occurred in supposedly neutral gang territory that is
normally free of turf wars. Samuel Sharad Shabazz, affiliated with
the West Boulevard Crips, was reportedly firing at Ernest Gray, a
member of the P-Stones gang who was a childhood friend of Gonzalez,
but instead struck the chief's granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been going on hot and heavy here for the past couple
months. We believe it's most likely because of territory and drug
sales,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Najee Ali, a community activist and former Crips gang member who
lives in the neighborhood where Gonzalez was killed, said local
gang members say the feud is over control of the crack cocaine
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the gangs are selling crack coke. It's the quickest way to
generate a cash load so they're able to buy more weapons and defend
their drug turf.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali said Latino gangs outnumber African-American gangs in the
area, fueling the risk of escalating war over control of
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's trying to carve out their own territory and
maintain it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Masterson, a school police officer at Dorsey High, said
that within the past few months, there have been about a half-dozen
shootings on the weekends and after school.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, it's been escalating,'' Masterson said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been at least nine gang-related homicides in South
Central Los Angeles in the last month, but police say there is as
yet no evidence the city's on the verge of a full-scale gang war,
nor that territorial battles between ethnic gangs are on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Total gang-related crimes are down 15 percent over last year
citywide, said LAPD Lt. Robert Swanson of the Career Criminal
Apprehension Section.
</P>
<P>
   In the Southwest Division, which initially handled the Gonzalez
homicide, there were 134 gang-related crimes through April 30,
compared to 198 during the same period last year, Swanson said.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Lt. Art Miller said he believes the last few weeks'
violence is more the result of dismantling the Community Resources
Against Street Hoodlums anti-gang units in the wake of the Rampart
Division police corruption scandal than a trend. Reconstituted
anti-gang units now are back on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gang crime was down for the last seven months, with the
exception of the last month,'' Southwest Lt. Art Miller said. ``We
expect it to go down now.''
</P>
<P>
   South Central paramedics also said they've noticed an increase
in gang violence going back about six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen an uptick,'' said Los Angeles County Fire Capt.
Brian Askari, whose paramedics are stationed across from Martin
Luther King Jr./Drew Medical Center and respond throughout gang
territories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've probably seen 10 gunshot cases in the last six months.
It's not at the early '90s level, but it seems like there's two or
three a month now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the San Pedro area, near the Port of Los Angeles, two people
were arrested last week on suspicion of murder and attempted
murder, and are among suspects in a series of racially motivated
shootings _ primarily between Latino and African-American gangs _
in the port area, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Baker and others said the city and local communities should
intervene quickly. ``It's all about money and power in the dope
world, and position in that trade,'' said Baker, who also serves as
local chapter chaplain for The Black American Political Association
of California Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to escalate.''
</P>
<P>
   (more)
</P>
<P>
   Juan Delreal, a 10th-grader at George Washington High School at
108th Street and Denker Avenue, knows about living with the fear of
gangs since he has to tread carefully just going about his life in
gang-controlled territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``At nighttime, I'm afraid. When we go to a friend's house, we
walk in a group,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Thompson, 27, has lived in the Crips-dominated
neighborhoods of 120th Street and Central Avenue for years, and
says he quickly learned the rules of the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence is just an everyday thing,'' he said. ``So you learn
what might be trouble and you don't go that route.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson, working on his car Friday afternoon in a
neighborhood a few miles from where Gonzalez was killed, shared the
siege mentality of his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they start, they escalate,'' he said. ``It seems like
somebody always has some kind of weapon. Now nobody just fights and
then shakes hands. Now they shoot, or stab or run over you with a
car.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People have just learned to survive when they walk through
gang areas. You keep your mouth shut and you walk on through.''
</P>
<P>
   It was silence of witnesses that resulted in shooting charges
being dropped against Shabazz about three weeks before Gonzalez was
slain.
</P>
<P>
   The case was dismissed because none of the six victims in the
Dec. 10, 1998, gang-related shooting could be found, resulting in
Shabazz's release from jail, where he'd been held on a $4 million
bail, said Los Angeles District Attorney's Office spokeswoman Sandi
Gibbons. ``It's not unusual in a gang case for all the witnesses to
disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   That the gangs are capable of instilling such terror in
community members is a crime, said Theresa Sharp, a parent
volunteer at George Washington High.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like we're losing control of our community once
again,'' said Sharp, whose grandson is a freshman at the high
school. ``We need community support.''
</P>
<P>
   Percy Pinkney, state president of the Black American Political
Association, will hold a summit against gang violence in Los
Angeles on Sept. 8-10. ``We want to decrease the violence, decrease
the use of guns and people being able to buy guns.''
</P>
<P>
   He has called on civic and clergy members, elected officials and
community organizations to come up with a statewide plan to deal
with the gang problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's simply too many funerals caused by gang violence. ...
We intend to try to do something to cease it and decrease it,''
Pinkney said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Tony Pierce, pastor at 1st African Methodist Episcopal
Zion Church on Adams Boulevard, said ministers meet with Parks
regularly to talk and pray about the gang violence in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very saddened by it. I think it's terrible. It's
unfortunate the minority community is hurting itself in this way,''
Pierce said.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said many young gang members are manipulated by older
operatives, or outsiders, into running drugs, fighting turf wars
and killing for financial gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids don't want to be involved, but they don't feel
like they have a choice. Either you're in or you're out.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce said drugs, poverty and a spiritual void in many gang
members' lives fuel the violence. He said the problem is so
daunting, he's begun to favor prayer in schools and
re-establishment of the draft to put some morality and discipline
back into young lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of children having children. When we were young,
our parents made sure we went to church. These kids aren't going,
and they're not sending their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Masterson, the police officer at Dorsey High, said jobs and
intervention programs for young people are essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be more things for the kids to do, other than
hang out, get drunk and shoot each other up.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said strong community support working with gang leaders
who want to maintain a truce could make a difference. ``Some want
it to fail. They don't care. Their lives are built around the
gangs. But many are really tired of the war, of it tearing the
community apart. The truce will stay on, if those with positive
minds prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
