<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSLEY WON'T PASS OSCAR TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shane Mosley is all people say he is. He's
skillful and powerful, fierce and hungry, calm and confident. Most
agree he's one of the best fighters in the world.
</P>
<P>
   One thing he isn't is good enough to beat Oscar De La Hoya on
Saturday at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: De La Hoya by late knockout.
</P>
<P>
   This is anything but an easy fight for the WBC welterweight
champ. Mosley is as complete as any opponent De La Hoya has faced
in his eight-year career. No one will be shocked if he wins.
</P>
<P>
   However, Mosley has two distinct disadvantages and they will
cost him the fight.
</P>
<P>
   One, he's fighting at the 147-pound weight limit for only the
third time after moving up from 135 and skipping over 140, an
unusual and potentially perilous move. De La Hoya has fought 10
times at 147.
</P>
<P>
   And, two, Mosley has relatively no big-fight experience. He's
had some credible opponents _ James Leija, John Molina and Wilfredo
Rivera, for example _ but has fought in utter obscurity compared to
one of the sport's biggest stars. De La Hoya has faced Felix
Trinidad, Ike Quartey, Pernell Whitaker and Julio Cesar Chavez in
(begin ital)huge(end ital) events.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley is hardly a weak welterweight. He was strong enough to
knock out Rivera last September and Willy Wise in January.
</P>
<P>
   He claims he's much stronger now. He said he could bench press
235 pounds at the time of the Rivera bout but can lift 315 now,
although he claims he doesn't overdo it in the weight room.
</P>
<P>
   Even more impressive, his knockout percentage _ 94 percent, 32
KOs in 34 fights _ is believed to be the best in the history of
boxing.
</P>
<P>
   However, the vast majority of the knockouts came at lightweight.
One must assume his power has suffered after jumping two weight
classes and, at the same time, wonder whether he has yet to grow
into the division.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya is a mature welterweight, one who will move up to 154
sometime soon. Rivera, one of three fighters to face De La Hoya and
Mosley, said De La Hoya is clearly the stronger of the two.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Mosley can handle fighters like Rivera and Wise even
as he grows into the division but to cope with the strength and
power of De La Hoya in only his third bout at 147 might be too much
to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the experience issue.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, as easygoing as they come outside the ring, seems to
have the makeup to handle prefight pressures. He's certainly shown
no signs of cracking as Michael Grant did in the weeks preceding
his disastrous bout with Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The fact Mosley has had an extensive and successful amateur
career and 34 pro fights probably contributes to his veneer.
</P>
<P>
   However, that doesn't compensate for the fact he's never been in
this position before. He's never seen the kind of media attention
he's receiving, he's never fought in front of 19,000-plus screaming
fans or a pay-per-view audience that could approach 1 million, he's
never been the underdog (De La Hoya is about a 2-1 favorite). It
has to take a toll. For De La Hoya, all that is no longer an issue.
He's been through it enough to know how to cope.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Mosley might fool those of us who lean toward De La
Hoya in this fight. He certainly has the ability and drive to beat
anyone in the division, including De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   However, the De La Hoya people think they're catching Mosley at
a good time, a time when he's not quite ready for the likes of
their fighter.
</P>
<P>
   And, it appears, they're right.
</P>
<P>
   Word wars: De La Hoya and Mosley have been respectful to one
another leading up to the fight. Their trainers have been less
diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Alcazar, De La Hoya's trainer, said Mosley has only ``a
decent punch, a medium punch'' when asked to assess Mosley's power.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley's trainer, his father, Jack Mosley, took exception when
he heard about the comments and went after Alcazar.
</P>
<P>
   And he focused his attack on one area Alcazar is particularly
vulnerable: The fact three trainers had been hired to work with De
La Hoya because of limited confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
   Alcazar now works alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He trains Oscar, so he has to say those things or else they
will kick him out of camp,'' the elder Mosley said. ``He has been
kicked out several times before. What does that say about him?
</P>
<P>
   ``.... You gotta take that with a grain of salt.''
</P>
<P>
   !More Alcazar: Alcazar went further than the comments about
Mosley's power. He said it's going to be ``an easy fight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it'll be an easy fight,'' he said. ``It'll be as hard as
Oscar makes it. It's up to him whether or not he sticks with the
game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``....As soon as Oscar hits him, he's going to start going
backward. And he doesn't know how to fight going backward. As soon
as he starts taking steps back, it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone reminded Alcazar that he also said the Trinidad fight _
in which De La Hoya lost a decision when he ran the final three
rounds of the fight _ would be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Alcazar's response? It (begin ital)was(end ital) easy.
</P>
<P>
   `He ran away and lost three rounds. I agree with you,'' he said.
``But what happened the other nine rounds?''
</P>
<P>
   Honest Oscar: De La Hoya can't stand Fernando Vargas the person
but apparently he respects Fernando Vargas the boxer.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked the other day whom he believed were the
most-skilled fighters in the world. To the shock of those who know
his distaste for his Oxnard rival, Vargas' was the first name he
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya has said he will never fight Vargas because of
disparaging comments the junior middleweight champ has made
publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: Antonio Diaz's original opponent, Demetrio
Ceballos, has pulled out of their Friday fight in Indio for medical
reasons. He was replaced by Argentine champion Omar Gabriel Weis.
</P>
<P>
   The fight will be televised on ESPN2....
</P>
<P>
   Vargas is negotiating to fight IBF No.1 contender Ross Thompson
on April 26 on HBO's ``Boxing After Dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on that card, Vernon Forrest is finally getting his world
title shot. He'll face IBF No.1 Raul Frank for the vacant
welterweight championship....
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya and Arturo Gatti are near a deal to fight on Sept. 9,
according to Main Events, Gatti's promotional firm....
</P>
<P>
   The next heavyweight in Showtime's big-man series is Andrew
Golota, who faces Orlin Norris on Friday in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Golota is trying to remain in the heavyweight championship
picture while Norris is attempting to come back from a knee injury
he suffered in his bout with Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   A tape of the fight will be televised at 11 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
