<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SIDEWAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREATEST FATHER'S DAY GIFT EVER (GET THE HINT?)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The company: Ebbets Field Flannels, based in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   What they make: Replicas, as close to the originals as possible,
of jerseys and caps from baseball teams of yesteryear. Lately,
they've added a line of football and hockey apparel.
</P>
<P>
   Why they're so special: They're not just something to wear, but
a history lesson comes with it. In fact, this is where teams go for
their special ``Turn Back The Clock'' uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   First, company president Jerry Cohen has been researching and
making these classic reproductions since 1987, obsessed with how
they were produced. He uses only the same lightweight wool blend
material that pro baseball uniforms were made of in the '50s and
'60s, but in the original ``baggy'' style. Every detail from the
buttons to zippers, collars to sleeve lengths are true.
</P>
<P>
   The lettering is hand-sewn felt, and there's even the lost art
of chain-stitched embroidering.
</P>
<P>
   What they have for sale: A 1940-era Pacific Coast League Los
Angeles Angels or Hollywood Stars jacket ($310) may be on the high
end, but it's worth every dollar. As is the 1957 Angels ballcap
($29) with the forerunner ``L.A.'' interlocked letters that the
Dodgers use today.
</P>
<P>
   Gray T-shirts with minor-league team logos are also available at
$18. There's also a group of teams in the ``Blue Route Series'' for
$22 that include the 1903 Nevada Lunatics, 1903 Des Moines
Undertakers and 1910 Santa Rose Prune Pickers.
</P>
<P>
   There's a $175 replica of the 1939 New York Knights home jersey
from ``The Natural,'' complete with the ``Wonderboy'' and Baseball
Centennial patch on the sleeves. (The ``NY'' hat goes for $29; the
jacket for $310).
</P>
<P>
   In the football collection, there's a 1937 Los Angeles Bulldogs
jersey ($59) from the American League of Professional Football. The
No. 13 is what Ed ``Crazy Legs'' Stark wore during their games at
Gilmore Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And in the hockey section, how about a gaudy
yellow-with-purple-trim 1967-68 L.A. Kings sweater ($99)?
</P>
<P>
   In a Father's Day pinch: They have gift certificates (in the
shape of an old baseball ticket stub) that come with an amazing
catalog and a gift card.
</P>
<P>
   How to order: By phone, (800) 377-9777, or through the Internet
site (www.ebbets.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-11-00 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
